{"title_page": "Land grant", "text_new": "{{about||feudal land grants|fief|other uses|Grantland (disambiguation)}}\nA '''land grant''' is a gift of [[real estate]] \u2013 land or its use privileges \u2013 made by a government or other authority as an incentive, means of enabling works, or as a reward for services to an individual, especially in return for [[military service]]. Grants of land are also awarded to individuals and companies as incentives to develop unused land in relatively unpopulated countries; the process of awarding land grants are not limited to the countries named below. The United States historically gave out numerous land grants as Homesteads to individuals desiring to prove a farm. The American Industrial Revolution was guided by many supportive acts of legislatures (for example, the [[Main Line of Public Works]] legislation of 1826) promoting commerce or [[transportation]] [[infrastructure]] development by private companies, such as the [[Cumberland Road]] [[Toll road|turnpike]], the [[Lehigh Canal]], the [[Schuylkill Canal]], and the many railroads that tied the young United States together.fa\n\n==Ancient Rome==\n[[Military history of ancient Rome|Roman soldiers]] were given [[pensions]] (''[[Aerarium militare#Benefits|praemia]]'') at the end of their service including cash or land. [[Augustus]] fixed the amount in AD 5 at 3,000 [[Denarius|denarii]] and by the time of [[Caracalla]] it had risen to 5,000 denarii.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roman-empire.net/army/army.html |title=The Roman Army |publisher=Roman-empire.net |date=2012-04-08 |accessdate=2013-02-12}}</ref>  One denarius was roughly equivalent to a day's wages for an unskilled laborer.\n\n==Australia==\nIn 1788 the British claimed all of eastern [[Australia]] as its own, and forming the colony of [[New South Wales]] in Australia. The land was claimed as [[crown land]]. Over time, it granted land to officers and released convicts.<ref>[http://www.records.nsw.gov.au/guides/short_guide_8_land_grants_1788-1856_9703.asp#Historicalbackground State Records NSW] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080828053645/http://www.records.nsw.gov.au/guides/short_guide_8_land_grants_1788-1856_9703.asp#Historicalbackground |date=2008-08-28 }}, citing ''[[Historical Records of Australia]]'' 1.1.14, 1.1.124-8, 1.7.268, 1.12.107-125, 1.16.22.</ref> Males were allowed {{convert|30|acre|abbr=on}}, plus {{convert|20|acre|abbr=on}} if they were married, and {{convert|10|acre|abbr=on}} additional per child.  Instructions were issued on 20 August 1789 that non-commissioned marine officers were to be entitled to {{convert|100|acre|abbr=on}} additional and privates to {{convert|50|acre|abbr=on}} additional.\n\n[[Lachlan Macquarie|Governor Macquarie]] canceled land grants issued during the [[Rum Rebellion]] of 1808-09, although some were later restored.\n\nLand grants started to be phased out when private tendering was introduced, and stricter limits were placed on grants without purchase. The instructions to [[Thomas Brisbane|Governor Brisbane]] were issued on 17 July 1825. From 9 January 1831, all land was to be sold at [[public auction]].\n\nThere were also significant [[land grants in the Swan River Colony]] (Western Australia), and in [[Van Diemen's Land]] (Tasmania) from 1803.\n\n=== Land grant railways ===\n* In 1886, the [[Midland Railway of Western Australia]] was granted land concessions to build and operate a railway from Midland, near Perth, to Walkaway, near [[Geraldton]].  This was built, but taken over by the government railway in the 1950s. It was and is {{RailGauge|1067mm}} gauge.\n* In 1889, a land grant railway from [[Roebuck Bay]] in [[Western Australia]] to [[Angle Pole]] in [[South Australia]] was proposed.  This would have been 1000 miles (1600&nbsp;km) long.  Angle Pole was a locality where the Telegraph line had a bend in it.  It was stillborn.    The gauge would have been {{RailGauge|1600mm}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.exploroz.com/Places/77748/SA/The_Angle_Pole_Memorial.aspx |title=The Angle Pole Memorial SA @ ExplorOz Places |publisher=Exploroz.com |date= |accessdate=2013-02-12}}</ref>\n* In 1897, a transcontinental North-South land grant railway was proposed to complete the missing link between [[Oodnadatta]] and [[Darwin, Northern Territory|Darwin]], the latter then called Palmerston or [[Port Darwin]]. The plan was abandoned, though the government railway was extended in the 1920s from [[Oodnadatta]] to [[Alice Springs]], with similar extensions at the [[Darwin, Northern Territory|Darwin]] end.  It was originally {{RailGauge|1067mm}} gauge, but was replaced by a new {{RailGauge|1435mm}} gauge line on a different route.\n* In 1909, a land grant [[transcontinental railway|railway]] was proposed in [[Queensland]] from [[Charleville, Queensland|Charleville]] to [[Point Parker]] on the shores of the [[Gulf of Carpentaria]], but the plan was abandoned.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article32136123 |title=TRANSCONTINENTAL RAILWAY. |newspaper=[[Cairns Morning Post|Cairns Morning Post (Qld. : 1907-1909)]] |location=Qld. |date=22 February 1909 |accessdate=19 January 2011 |page=5 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\n==Canada==\nThe [[Hudson's Bay Company]] was incorporated in 1670 with the grant of [[Rupert's Land]] by King [[Charles II of England]]; this vast territory was greater than one third the area of Canada today. Following the [[Rupert's Land Act 1868|Rupert's Land Act]] in the British Parliament, Rupert's Land was sold in 1869 to the newly formed [[Canadian Government]] for the nominal sum of \u00a3300,000.\n\nLand grants were an incentive for the construction of the [[Canadian Pacific Railway#The CPR and the colonization of Canada|Canadian Pacific Railway]].\n\n==Ireland==\nThe [[Plantations of Ireland]] in the 16th and 17th centuries involved the confiscation of some or all the land of Irish lords and its grant to settlers (\"planters\") from England or Scotland. The English Parliament's [[Adventurers Act]] 1642 and [[Act for the Settlement of Ireland 1652]] specifically entitled \"Adventurers\" who funded the [[Cromwellian conquest of Ireland]] to lands seized from the leaders of the [[Irish Rebellion of 1641]] and the ensuing [[Confederate Ireland|Confederacy]].\n\n== New Zealand ==\nIn New Zealand two private railway companies were offered land grants to build a railway, though both were eventually taken over by the government and incorporated into the government-owned [[New Zealand Railways Department]].  \n:The [[Wellington and Manawatu Railway Company]] built and operated the 134 km [[Wellington-Manawatu Line]] north of Wellington to the Manawatu from 1881. The company was New Zealand owned. It was taken over by the government in 1908, and the line became part of the [[North Island Main Trunk]]. \n:The [[New Zealand Midland Railway Company]] started the [[Midland Line, New Zealand|Midland Line]] between Canterbury and the West Coast in 1886 but the British-owned company was taken over by the government in 1895, having constructed only 131 km of the 376 km route.\n\n==United States==\n[[File:Virginia Land Office Warrant Number 229 to Joseph Cabell for Gabriel Penn.jpg|thumb|[[Virginia]] Land Office warrant issued in 1779 to Joseph Cabell, assignee of [[Sergeant|Sgt.]] Gabriel Penn, to receive 200 [[acres]] of land in return for Penn's service in the [[French and Indian War]]]]\n\n===Colonial era===\n\nIn America, starting in the 16th century, land grants were given for the purpose of establishing [[town|settlements]], missions, and [[farm]]s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.encyclopedia.com/science-and-technology/astronomy-and-space-exploration/space-exploration/land-grants|title=Land grants {{!}} Encyclopedia.com|website=www.encyclopedia.com|language=en|access-date=2018-08-09}}</ref> England started with a [[headright]] system, used both by the [[Virginia Company of London]] and the [[Plymouth Colony]], but later used primarily in colonies south of [[Maryland]]. Under this system, emigrants or those paying for their passage would receive land if they survived for a certain period of time (although many indentured servants did not survive their contracts and enslaved Africans were ineligible for headrights). Countries granting land included Spain, Portugal, the Netherlands, and Britain.\n\nAs English colonial law developed, headrights became patents and a '''patentee''' had to improve the land. Under this doctrine of '''planting and seeding''', the patentee was required to cultivate {{convert|1|acre|m2|adj=on}} of land and build a small house on the property, otherwise the patent would revert to the government.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rootsweb.com/~rwguide/lesson29a.htm |title=Roots web |publisher=Roots web |date= |accessdate=2013-02-12}}</ref>\n\nBetween 1783 and 1821, Spain offered land grants to anyone who settled in their colony of [[Florida]]. When the United States acquired that land by treaty, it agreed to honor all valid land grants. As a result, years of litigation ensued over the validity of many of the Spanish Land Grants. Spain and Mexico used the same system of offering land grants along the Rio Grande River near the Texas/Mexico border. These grants were given to help colonization of the area by Mexican and Spanish nationals, and strengthen frontier towns along the Texas border. During the [[Ranchos of California#Mexican era|Mexican period]] of [[California]] (and other portions of Mexican territories inherited from [[New Spain]]),the Mexican government granted individuals hundreds of [[Ranchos of California|ranchos]] or large tracts of land. The ranchos established land-use patterns that remain recognizable in the [[California]] of today.<ref>David Hornbeck,''Land tenure and rancho expansion in Alta California, 1784\u20131846'', Journal of Historical Geography, Volume 4, Issue 4, October 1978, Pages  371\u2013390</ref> Controversy over community land grant claims in [[New Mexico]] persist to this day.<ref name=\"Treaty of Guadalupe Hidalgo: Findings and Possible Options Regarding Longstanding Community Land Grant Claims in New Mexico\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gao.gov/new.items/d0459.pdf|title=Treaty of Guadalupe Hidalgo: Findings and Possible Options Regarding Longstanding Community Land Grant Claims in New Mexico|publisher=General Accounting Office|accessdate=5 June 2008|format=PDF}}</ref>\n\n===Public lands and bounty-land warrants===\nFuture President [[Thomas Jefferson]] crafted the [[Ordinance of 1784]] which carved out ten prospective states west of the [[Appalachian Mountains]] and established the basis for the [[Public Land Survey System]]. The [[Land Ordinance of 1785]] provided a method for settling that land and establishing governmental institutions, which became federal land policy until 1862. The [[Northwest Ordinance]] of 1787 established the [[Northwest Territory]], pursuant to which homesteading settlers could buy land, and certain land was set aside for public schools and other purposes. The Federal Government acquired additional lands by treaties with various Native American Tribes, such as the 1833 [[Treaty of Chicago]] by which many eastern tribes agreed to settle across the [[Mississippi River]]. Revenues from public land purchases were a major source of funding for the federal government through the 19th centuries, along with tariff revenues, since the federal income tax was not established until the 20th century.\n\nStarting with the [[American Revolutionary War]], United States veterans often received land grants instead of backpay or other remuneration.<ref>William D. Houghton {{cite web| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kXRzAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA86&lpg=PA86&dq=veterans+often+received+land+grants+in+lieu+of+other+remuneration&source=bl&ots=l01LZgpClF&sig=FB50wCNJrqXLczy6Jry-WF1sBMY&hl=en&sa=X&ei=IfagVILWEsf6UIP-gKAL&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=veterans%20often%20received%20land%20grants%20in%20lieu%20of%20other%20remuneration&f=false| title=Houghton Ancestors | pp=86}}</ref> Bounty-land warrants, often for 160 acres, were issued to United States military veterans from 1775 to 1855, thus including veterans of the [[American Revolutionary War]], [[War of 1812]] and the [[Mexican\u2013American War]] as well as various Indian wars. The land grants helped settle the [[Northwest Territory]] (and later smaller units such as the [[Indiana Territory]], [[Illinois Territory]] and [[Wisconsin Territory]]) and as well as the [[Platte Purchase]] in Missouri.<ref name=\"archives.gov\">https://www.archives.gov/research/military/bounty-land-1775-1855.pdf</ref><ref name=\"ancestry.com\">{{cite web|url=http://search.ancestry.com/search/db.aspx?dbid=1165|title=U.S. War Bounty Land Warrants, 1789-1858|author=|date=|website=search.ancestry.com|accessdate=3 April 2018}}</ref> Eligibility for the warrants expanded over the years through new Congressional acts of 1842, 1850, 1852, and 1855 to the point where they could be sold or could be handed out to descendants. The warrant program was discontinued before the [[American Civil War]].<ref name=\"archives.gov\"/><ref name=\"ancestry.com\"/>\n\nDuring the 19th century, various states (or even smaller units) as well as the federal government made extensive land grants to encourage [[internal improvements]], usually to improve transportation, such as construction of bridges and canals. The [[Land Grant Act of 1850]] provided for 3.75 million acres of land to the states to support railroad projects; by 1857 21 million acres of public lands were used for railroads in the [[Mississippi River]] valley, and the stage was set for more substantial Congressional subsidies to future railroads.<ref>Julian E. Zelizer, ''The American Congress: the building of democracy'', [https://books.google.com/books?id=_MGEIIwT5pUC&pg=PA288& p.288]</ref> Universities were also beneficiaries of land grants.<ref>{{Cite journal|date=1995-09-27|title=Colleges of Agriculture at the Land Grant Universities|url=https://www.nap.edu/read/4980/chapter/2|language=en|doi=10.17226/4980}}</ref> All five of the [[transcontinental railroad]]s in the United States were built using land grants.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://socialdemocracy21stcentury.blogspot.com/2011/07/government-intervention-james-j-hill.html|title=Social Democracy for the 21st Century: A Realist Alternative to the Modern Left: Government Intervention, James J. Hill and the Great Northern Railway|last=Lk|date=2011-07-26|website=Social Democracy for the 21st Century|access-date=2018-08-09}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Morrill Land-Grant Acts]] of 1862 and 1890 provided for the establishment of [[land-grant colleges]].\n\n==== Economic Impact ====\nThere is general agreement that the United States' federal policy of offering land grants had a positive impact on economic development in the 19th century.<ref>Whaples, R. (1995). Where is there consensus among American economic historians? The results of a survey on forty propositions. ''The Journal of Economic History'', ''55''(1), 139-154.</ref> {{further|Economic history of the United States#Land grants}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Atrisco Land Grant]]\n* [[Enclosure]]\n* [[Encomienda]]\n* [[Fief]]dom\n* [[Land patent]]\n* [[Land reform]]\n* [[Land-grant university]]\n* [[Military Tract of 1812]]\n* [[Province of Carolina]]\n* [[Ranchos of California]]\n* [[Sea Grant Colleges|Sea-grant college]]\n* [[Space grant colleges|Space-grant college]]\n* [[United States Court of Private Land Claims]]\n\n==Notes==\n<!--<nowiki>\nSee http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Footnotes for an explanation of how to generate footnotes using the <ref> and </ref> tags, and the template below. \n</nowiki>-->\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130502174501/http://floridamemory.com/collections/spanishlandgrants/ Online collection and history of the Spanish Land Grants in Florida; made available for public use by the State Archives of Florida.]\n* [http://www.nclandgrants.com/ Free online collection of 216,000 land grants issued by North Carolina from 1663 to 1960.  Many are linked to actual document images.]\n\n[[Category:Land grants| ]]\n[[Category:Real property law]]\n[[Category:Real estate terminology]]\n[[Category:United States federal agriculture legislation]]\n[[Category:United States public land law]]\n", "text_old": "{{about||feudal land grants|fief|other uses|Grantland (disambiguation)}}\nA '''land grant''' is a gift of [[real estate]] \u2013 land or its use privileges \u2013 made by a government or other authority as an incentive, means of enabling works, or as a reward for services to an individual, especially in return for [[military service]]. Grants of land are also awarded to individuals and companies as incentives to develop unused land in relatively unpopulated countries; the process of awarding land grants are not limited to the countries named below. The United States historically gave out numerous land grants as Homesteads to individuals desiring to prove a farm. The American Industrial Revolution was guided by many supportive acts of legislatures (for example, the [[Main Line of Public Works]] legislation of 1826) promoting commerce or [[transportation]] [[infrastructure]] development by private companies, such as the [[Cumberland Road]] [[Toll road|turnpike]], the [[Lehigh Canal]], the [[Schuylkill Canal]], and the many railroads that tied the young United States together.\n\n==Ancient Rome==\n[[Military history of ancient Rome|Roman soldiers]] were given [[pensions]] (''[[Aerarium militare#Benefits|praemia]]'') at the end of their service including cash or land. [[Augustus]] fixed the amount in AD 5 at 3,000 [[Denarius|denarii]] and by the time of [[Caracalla]] it had risen to 5,000 denarii.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roman-empire.net/army/army.html |title=The Roman Army |publisher=Roman-empire.net |date=2012-04-08 |accessdate=2013-02-12}}</ref>  One denarius was roughly equivalent to a day's wages for an unskilled laborer.\n\n==Australia==\nIn 1788 the British claimed all of eastern [[Australia]] as its own, and forming the colony of [[New South Wales]] in Australia. The land was claimed as [[crown land]]. Over time, it granted land to officers and released convicts.<ref>[http://www.records.nsw.gov.au/guides/short_guide_8_land_grants_1788-1856_9703.asp#Historicalbackground State Records NSW] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080828053645/http://www.records.nsw.gov.au/guides/short_guide_8_land_grants_1788-1856_9703.asp#Historicalbackground |date=2008-08-28 }}, citing ''[[Historical Records of Australia]]'' 1.1.14, 1.1.124-8, 1.7.268, 1.12.107-125, 1.16.22.</ref> Males were allowed {{convert|30|acre|abbr=on}}, plus {{convert|20|acre|abbr=on}} if they were married, and {{convert|10|acre|abbr=on}} additional per child.  Instructions were issued on 20 August 1789 that non-commissioned marine officers were to be entitled to {{convert|100|acre|abbr=on}} additional and privates to {{convert|50|acre|abbr=on}} additional.\n\n[[Lachlan Macquarie|Governor Macquarie]] canceled land grants issued during the [[Rum Rebellion]] of 1808-09, although some were later restored.\n\nLand grants started to be phased out when private tendering was introduced, and stricter limits were placed on grants without purchase. The instructions to [[Thomas Brisbane|Governor Brisbane]] were issued on 17 July 1825. From 9 January 1831, all land was to be sold at [[public auction]].\n\nThere were also significant [[land grants in the Swan River Colony]] (Western Australia), and in [[Van Diemen's Land]] (Tasmania) from 1803.\n\n=== Land grant railways ===\n* In 1886, the [[Midland Railway of Western Australia]] was granted land concessions to build and operate a railway from Midland, near Perth, to Walkaway, near [[Geraldton]].  This was built, but taken over by the government railway in the 1950s. It was and is {{RailGauge|1067mm}} gauge.\n* In 1889, a land grant railway from [[Roebuck Bay]] in [[Western Australia]] to [[Angle Pole]] in [[South Australia]] was proposed.  This would have been 1000 miles (1600&nbsp;km) long.  Angle Pole was a locality where the Telegraph line had a bend in it.  It was stillborn.    The gauge would have been {{RailGauge|1600mm}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.exploroz.com/Places/77748/SA/The_Angle_Pole_Memorial.aspx |title=The Angle Pole Memorial SA @ ExplorOz Places |publisher=Exploroz.com |date= |accessdate=2013-02-12}}</ref>\n* In 1897, a transcontinental North-South land grant railway was proposed to complete the missing link between [[Oodnadatta]] and [[Darwin, Northern Territory|Darwin]], the latter then called Palmerston or [[Port Darwin]]. The plan was abandoned, though the government railway was extended in the 1920s from [[Oodnadatta]] to [[Alice Springs]], with similar extensions at the [[Darwin, Northern Territory|Darwin]] end.  It was originally {{RailGauge|1067mm}} gauge, but was replaced by a new {{RailGauge|1435mm}} gauge line on a different route.\n* In 1909, a land grant [[transcontinental railway|railway]] was proposed in [[Queensland]] from [[Charleville, Queensland|Charleville]] to [[Point Parker]] on the shores of the [[Gulf of Carpentaria]], but the plan was abandoned.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article32136123 |title=TRANSCONTINENTAL RAILWAY. |newspaper=[[Cairns Morning Post|Cairns Morning Post (Qld. : 1907-1909)]] |location=Qld. |date=22 February 1909 |accessdate=19 January 2011 |page=5 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\n==Canada==\nThe [[Hudson's Bay Company]] was incorporated in 1670 with the grant of [[Rupert's Land]] by King [[Charles II of England]]; this vast territory was greater than one third the area of Canada today. Following the [[Rupert's Land Act 1868|Rupert's Land Act]] in the British Parliament, Rupert's Land was sold in 1869 to the newly formed [[Canadian Government]] for the nominal sum of \u00a3300,000.\n\nLand grants were an incentive for the construction of the [[Canadian Pacific Railway#The CPR and the colonization of Canada|Canadian Pacific Railway]].\n\n==Ireland==\nThe [[Plantations of Ireland]] in the 16th and 17th centuries involved the confiscation of some or all the land of Irish lords and its grant to settlers (\"planters\") from England or Scotland. The English Parliament's [[Adventurers Act]] 1642 and [[Act for the Settlement of Ireland 1652]] specifically entitled \"Adventurers\" who funded the [[Cromwellian conquest of Ireland]] to lands seized from the leaders of the [[Irish Rebellion of 1641]] and the ensuing [[Confederate Ireland|Confederacy]].\n\n== New Zealand ==\nIn New Zealand two private railway companies were offered land grants to build a railway, though both were eventually taken over by the government and incorporated into the government-owned [[New Zealand Railways Department]].  \n:The [[Wellington and Manawatu Railway Company]] built and operated the 134 km [[Wellington-Manawatu Line]] north of Wellington to the Manawatu from 1881. The company was New Zealand owned. It was taken over by the government in 1908, and the line became part of the [[North Island Main Trunk]]. \n:The [[New Zealand Midland Railway Company]] started the [[Midland Line, New Zealand|Midland Line]] between Canterbury and the West Coast in 1886 but the British-owned company was taken over by the government in 1895, having constructed only 131 km of the 376 km route.\n\n==United States==\n[[File:Virginia Land Office Warrant Number 229 to Joseph Cabell for Gabriel Penn.jpg|thumb|[[Virginia]] Land Office warrant issued in 1779 to Joseph Cabell, assignee of [[Sergeant|Sgt.]] Gabriel Penn, to receive 200 [[acres]] of land in return for Penn's service in the [[French and Indian War]]]]\n\n===Colonial era===\n\nIn America, starting in the 16th century, land grants were given for the purpose of establishing [[town|settlements]], missions, and [[farm]]s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.encyclopedia.com/science-and-technology/astronomy-and-space-exploration/space-exploration/land-grants|title=Land grants {{!}} Encyclopedia.com|website=www.encyclopedia.com|language=en|access-date=2018-08-09}}</ref> England started with a [[headright]] system, used both by the [[Virginia Company of London]] and the [[Plymouth Colony]], but later used primarily in colonies south of [[Maryland]]. Under this system, emigrants or those paying for their passage would receive land if they survived for a certain period of time (although many indentured servants did not survive their contracts and enslaved Africans were ineligible for headrights). Countries granting land included Spain, Portugal, the Netherlands, and Britain.\n\nAs English colonial law developed, headrights became patents and a '''patentee''' had to improve the land. Under this doctrine of '''planting and seeding''', the patentee was required to cultivate {{convert|1|acre|m2|adj=on}} of land and build a small house on the property, otherwise the patent would revert to the government.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rootsweb.com/~rwguide/lesson29a.htm |title=Roots web |publisher=Roots web |date= |accessdate=2013-02-12}}</ref>\n\nBetween 1783 and 1821, Spain offered land grants to anyone who settled in their colony of [[Florida]]. When the United States acquired that land by treaty, it agreed to honor all valid land grants. As a result, years of litigation ensued over the validity of many of the Spanish Land Grants. Spain and Mexico used the same system of offering land grants along the Rio Grande River near the Texas/Mexico border. These grants were given to help colonization of the area by Mexican and Spanish nationals, and strengthen frontier towns along the Texas border. During the [[Ranchos of California#Mexican era|Mexican period]] of [[California]] (and other portions of Mexican territories inherited from [[New Spain]]),the Mexican government granted individuals hundreds of [[Ranchos of California|ranchos]] or large tracts of land. The ranchos established land-use patterns that remain recognizable in the [[California]] of today.<ref>David Hornbeck,''Land tenure and rancho expansion in Alta California, 1784\u20131846'', Journal of Historical Geography, Volume 4, Issue 4, October 1978, Pages  371\u2013390</ref> Controversy over community land grant claims in [[New Mexico]] persist to this day.<ref name=\"Treaty of Guadalupe Hidalgo: Findings and Possible Options Regarding Longstanding Community Land Grant Claims in New Mexico\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gao.gov/new.items/d0459.pdf|title=Treaty of Guadalupe Hidalgo: Findings and Possible Options Regarding Longstanding Community Land Grant Claims in New Mexico|publisher=General Accounting Office|accessdate=5 June 2008|format=PDF}}</ref>\n\n===Public lands and bounty-land warrants===\nFuture President [[Thomas Jefferson]] crafted the [[Ordinance of 1784]] which carved out ten prospective states west of the [[Appalachian Mountains]] and established the basis for the [[Public Land Survey System]]. The [[Land Ordinance of 1785]] provided a method for settling that land and establishing governmental institutions, which became federal land policy until 1862. The [[Northwest Ordinance]] of 1787 established the [[Northwest Territory]], pursuant to which homesteading settlers could buy land, and certain land was set aside for public schools and other purposes. The Federal Government acquired additional lands by treaties with various Native American Tribes, such as the 1833 [[Treaty of Chicago]] by which many eastern tribes agreed to settle across the [[Mississippi River]]. Revenues from public land purchases were a major source of funding for the federal government through the 19th centuries, along with tariff revenues, since the federal income tax was not established until the 20th century.\n\nStarting with the [[American Revolutionary War]], United States veterans often received land grants instead of backpay or other remuneration.<ref>William D. Houghton {{cite web| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kXRzAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA86&lpg=PA86&dq=veterans+often+received+land+grants+in+lieu+of+other+remuneration&source=bl&ots=l01LZgpClF&sig=FB50wCNJrqXLczy6Jry-WF1sBMY&hl=en&sa=X&ei=IfagVILWEsf6UIP-gKAL&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=veterans%20often%20received%20land%20grants%20in%20lieu%20of%20other%20remuneration&f=false| title=Houghton Ancestors | pp=86}}</ref> Bounty-land warrants, often for 160 acres, were issued to United States military veterans from 1775 to 1855, thus including veterans of the [[American Revolutionary War]], [[War of 1812]] and the [[Mexican\u2013American War]] as well as various Indian wars. The land grants helped settle the [[Northwest Territory]] (and later smaller units such as the [[Indiana Territory]], [[Illinois Territory]] and [[Wisconsin Territory]]) and as well as the [[Platte Purchase]] in Missouri.<ref name=\"archives.gov\">https://www.archives.gov/research/military/bounty-land-1775-1855.pdf</ref><ref name=\"ancestry.com\">{{cite web|url=http://search.ancestry.com/search/db.aspx?dbid=1165|title=U.S. War Bounty Land Warrants, 1789-1858|author=|date=|website=search.ancestry.com|accessdate=3 April 2018}}</ref> Eligibility for the warrants expanded over the years through new Congressional acts of 1842, 1850, 1852, and 1855 to the point where they could be sold or could be handed out to descendants. The warrant program was discontinued before the [[American Civil War]].<ref name=\"archives.gov\"/><ref name=\"ancestry.com\"/>\n\nDuring the 19th century, various states (or even smaller units) as well as the federal government made extensive land grants to encourage [[internal improvements]], usually to improve transportation, such as construction of bridges and canals. The [[Land Grant Act of 1850]] provided for 3.75 million acres of land to the states to support railroad projects; by 1857 21 million acres of public lands were used for railroads in the [[Mississippi River]] valley, and the stage was set for more substantial Congressional subsidies to future railroads.<ref>Julian E. Zelizer, ''The American Congress: the building of democracy'', [https://books.google.com/books?id=_MGEIIwT5pUC&pg=PA288& p.288]</ref> Universities were also beneficiaries of land grants.<ref>{{Cite journal|date=1995-09-27|title=Colleges of Agriculture at the Land Grant Universities|url=https://www.nap.edu/read/4980/chapter/2|language=en|doi=10.17226/4980}}</ref> All five of the [[transcontinental railroad]]s in the United States were built using land grants.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://socialdemocracy21stcentury.blogspot.com/2011/07/government-intervention-james-j-hill.html|title=Social Democracy for the 21st Century: A Realist Alternative to the Modern Left: Government Intervention, James J. Hill and the Great Northern Railway|last=Lk|date=2011-07-26|website=Social Democracy for the 21st Century|access-date=2018-08-09}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Morrill Land-Grant Acts]] of 1862 and 1890 provided for the establishment of [[land-grant colleges]].\n\n==== Economic Impact ====\nThere is general agreement that the United States' federal policy of offering land grants had a positive impact on economic development in the 19th century.<ref>Whaples, R. (1995). Where is there consensus among American economic historians? The results of a survey on forty propositions. ''The Journal of Economic History'', ''55''(1), 139-154.</ref> {{further|Economic history of the United States#Land grants}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Atrisco Land Grant]]\n* [[Enclosure]]\n* [[Encomienda]]\n* [[Fief]]dom\n* [[Land patent]]\n* [[Land reform]]\n* [[Land-grant university]]\n* [[Military Tract of 1812]]\n* [[Province of Carolina]]\n* [[Ranchos of California]]\n* [[Sea Grant Colleges|Sea-grant college]]\n* [[Space grant colleges|Space-grant college]]\n* [[United States Court of Private Land Claims]]\n\n==Notes==\n<!--<nowiki>\nSee http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Footnotes for an explanation of how to generate footnotes using the <ref> and </ref> tags, and the template below. \n</nowiki>-->\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130502174501/http://floridamemory.com/collections/spanishlandgrants/ Online collection and history of the Spanish Land Grants in Florida; made available for public use by the State Archives of Florida.]\n* [http://www.nclandgrants.com/ Free online collection of 216,000 land grants issued by North Carolina from 1663 to 1960.  Many are linked to actual document images.]\n\n[[Category:Land grants| ]]\n[[Category:Real property law]]\n[[Category:Real estate terminology]]\n[[Category:United States federal agriculture legislation]]\n[[Category:United States public land law]]\n", "name_user": "2605:6000:1714:4088:e48d:1991:ad35:bcb1", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Land_grant"}
{"title_page": "Fran\u00e7ois Pidou de Saint Olon", "text_new": "[[Image:ReceptionOfLouisXIVsAmbassadorToSultan.jpg|thumb|upright=1.5|[[Moulay Ismail|Isma\u00efl Ibn Sharif]] receiving Ambassador Fran\u00e7ois Pidou de Saint Olon from [[Louis XIV of France]], by [[Pierre-Denis Martin (1663-1742)|Pierre-Denis Martin]] (1693).]]\n'''Fran\u00e7ois Pidou de Saint Olon''' (1640, [[Touraine]] - 1720, [[Paris]]) was a French diplomat under [[Louis XIV]].\n\n==Embassy to Genoa and Spain==\nIn 1682, he was nominated as the first French resident envoy to the [[Republic of Genoa]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=g4p45mbr02sC&pg=PA240 ''Europa triumphans: court and civic festivals in early modern Europe'' J. R. Mulryne p.240 Note 14]</ref> He was then sent as an envoy to [[Madrid]].\n\n==Embassy to Morocco==\n[[File:Relation de l Empire du Maroc 1695.jpg|thumb|left|''Relation de l'Empire du Maroc'', by Fran\u00e7ois Pidou de Saint Olon, 1695.]]\n[[File:Moroccan woman Estat present de l'empire de Maroc 1694.jpg|thumb|Moroccan woman in ''Estat pr\u00e9sent de l'empire de Maroc'', 1694.]]\n\nin 1689, Pidou de Saint Olon was then nominated as ambassador to the court of the Moroccan ruler [[Mulay Ismail]], in view of the signature of a commercial treaty.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=WcV9iITuB2YC&pg=PA390 ''The Works of John Dryden, Volume XV'' H.T. Swedenberg Jr. p.390 Note 27]</ref><ref name=\"Cochran 111\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=sLEQAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA111 ''A second catalogue of manuscripts, in different languages'' John Cochran p.111]</ref> This responded to the Embassy of [[Mohammad Temim]] to Louis XIV in 1682. In 1690, Pidou de Saint Olon was in the city of [[Sal\u00e9]], where he visited the French Consul [[Jean-Baptiste Estelle]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=idEUAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA267 ''A History of the Jews in North Africa'' Haim Zeev Hirschberg, Eliezer Bashan, Robert Attal p.267]</ref>\n\nHis mission did not succeed however, and he only remained 2\u20133 weeks in Morocco.<ref name=\"Cochran 111\"/> He wrote an account of his visit to Morocco, ''Relation de l'empire de Maroc'' (\"The present state of the Empire of Morocco\").<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=23f9QfMDQF4C&pg=PA1969-IA709 ''New Cambridge Bibliography of English Literature'' by George Watson p.1969]</ref>\n\nAnother Moroccan ambassador [[Abdallah bin Aisha]] would visit France in 1699-1700.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=U09goMOOG5oC&pg=PA197 ''In the lands of the Christians: Arabic travel writing in the seventeenth century'' by Nabil I. Matar p.197]</ref>\n\nFran\u00e7ois Pidou de Saint Olon died in Paris on 27 September 1720.\n\n==See also==\n* [[France-Morocco relations]]\n\n==Works==\n* ''Estat pr\u00e9sent de l'empire de Maroc'', 1694\n* ''Relation de l'empire de Maroc'', 1695\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Francois Pidou de Saint Olon}}\n[[Category:17th-century French diplomats]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of France to Morocco]]\n[[Category:17th century in Morocco]]\n[[Category:17th-century French writers]]\n[[Category:17th-century male writers]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors to the Republic of Genoa]]\n[[Category:1640 births]]\n[[Category:1720 deaths]]\n[[Category:French male writers]]\n", "text_old": "[[Image:ReceptionOfLouisXIVsAmbassadorToSultan.jpg|thumb|upright=1.5|[[Moulay Ismail|Isma\u00efl Ibn Sharif]] receiving Ambassador Fran\u00e7ois Pidou de Saint Olon from [[Louis XIV of France]], by [[Pierre-Denis Martin (1663-1742)|Pierre-Denis Martin]] (1693).]]\n'''Fran\u00e7ois Pidou de Saint Olon''' (1640, [[Touraine]] - 1720, [[Paris]]) was a French diplomat under [[Louis XIV]].\n\n==Embassy to Genoa and Spain==\nIn 1682, he was nominated as the first French resident envoy to the [[Republic of Genoa]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=g4p45mbr02sC&pg=PA240 ''Europa triumphans: court and civic festivals in early modern Europe'' J. R. Mulryne p.240 Note 14]</ref> He was then sent as an envoy to [[Madrid]].\n\n==Embassy to Morocco==\n[[File:Relation de l Empire du Maroc 1695.jpg|thumb|left|''Relation de l'Empire du Maroc'', by Fran\u00e7ois Pidou de Saint Olon, 1695.]]\n[[File:Moroccan woman Estat present de l'empire de Maroc 1694.jpg|thumb|Moroccan woman in ''Estat pr\u00e9sent de l'empire de Maroc'', 1694.]]\n\nin 1689, Pidou de Saint Olon was then nominated as ambassador to the court of the Moroccan ruler [[Mulay Ismail]], in view of the signature of a commercial treaty.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=WcV9iITuB2YC&pg=PA390 ''The Works of John Dryden, Volume XV'' H.T. Swedenberg Jr. p.390 Note 27]</ref><ref name=\"Cochran 111\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=sLEQAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA111 ''A second catalogue of manuscripts, in different languages'' John Cochran p.111]</ref> This responded to the Embassy of [[Mohammad Temim]] to Louis XIV in 1682. In 1690, Pidou de Saint Olon was in the city of [[Sal\u00e9]], where he visited the French Consul [[Jean-Baptiste Estelle]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=idEUAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA267 ''A History of the Jews in North Africa'' Haim Zeev Hirschberg, Eliezer Bashan, Robert Attal p.267]</ref>\n\nHis mission did not succeed however, and he only remained 2\u20133 weeks in Morocco.<ref name=\"Cochran 111\"/> He wrote an account of his visit to Morocco, ''Relation de l'empire de Maroc'' (\"The present state of the Empire of Morocco\").<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=23f9QfMDQF4C&pg=PA1969-IA709 ''New Cambridge Bibliography of English Literature'' by George Watson p.1969]</ref>\n\nAnother Moroccan ambassador [[Abdallah bin Aisha]] would visit France in 1699-1700.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=U09goMOOG5oC&pg=PA197 ''In the lands of the Christians: Arabic travel writing in the seventeenth century'' by Nabil I. Matar p.197]</ref>\n\nFran\u00e7ois Pidou de Saint Olon died in Paris on 27 September 1720.\n\n==See also==\n* [[France-Morocco relations]]\n\n==Works==\n* ''Estat pr\u00e9sent de l'empire de Maroc'', 1694\n* ''Relation de l'empire de Maroc'', 1695\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Francois Pidou de Saint Olon}}\n[[Category:17th-century French diplomats]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of France to Morocco]]\n[[Category:17th century in Morocco]]\n[[Category:17th-century French writers]]\n[[Category:17th-century male writers]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors to the Republic of Genoa]]\n[[Category:1640 births]]\n[[Category:1720 deaths]]\n[[Category:French male writers]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNotes:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fran%C3%A7ois_Pidou_de_Saint_Olon"}
{"title_page": "Stamford, Connecticut", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Stratford, Connecticut|Stafford, Connecticut|Stanford, California}}\n{{short description|City in Connecticut, United States}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| official_name            = Stamford, Connecticut\n| settlement_type          = [[City]]\n| image_skyline            = File:Stamford CT Montage 2018.png\n| image_caption            = Clockwise, from top: [[Downtown Stamford]], [[Harbor Point (Stamford)|Harbor Point]], [[Stamford Museum & Nature Center]], [[Stamford Center for the Arts]], [[Fish Church]], One Stamford Forum, [[Stamford Transportation Center]], [[Old Town Hall (Stamford, Connecticut)|Old Town Hall]], and [[One Landmark Square]]\n| image_seal               = Seal of Stamford, Connecticut.svg\n| image_blank_emblem       = Logo of Stamford, Connecticut.svg\n| blank_emblem_size        = 150px\n| image_flag               = Flag of Stamford, Connecticut.svg\n| nickname                 = Innovating Since 1641, Stamvegas, The City That Works, Lock City\n| image_map                = {{Maplink|frame=yes|plain=y|frame-width=300|frame-height=190|frame-align=center|stroke-width=3|zoom=9|frame-lat=41.07|frame-long=-73.546|type=shape-inverse|stroke-color=#808080|id=Q49169|title=Stamford}}\n| mapsize                  =\n| map_caption              = Interactive map outlining Stamford, Connecticut\n| coordinates              = {{coord|41|03|10|N|73|32|20|W|region:US-CT_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type         = [[Country]]\n| subdivision_name         = {{flag|United States}}\n| subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state]]\n| subdivision_name1        = {{flag|Connecticut}}\n| subdivision_type2        = [[County (United States)|County]]\n| subdivision_name2        = [[Fairfield County, Connecticut|Fairfield]]\n| subdivision_type3        = [[Metropolitan Statistical Area]]\n| subdivision_name3        = [[Greater Bridgeport|Bridgeport-Stamford-Norwalk]]\n| established_title        = Settled (town)\n| established_date         = 1641\n| established_title2       = Incorporated (city)\n| established_date2        = 1893\n| established_title3       = Consolidated\n| established_date3        = 1949\n| named_for                = [[Stamford, Lincolnshire]]\n| government_type          = [[Mayor\u2013council government|Mayor-Board of representatives]]\n| leader_title             = [[Mayor of Stamford, Connecticut|Mayor]]\n| leader_name              = [[David Martin (mayor)|David Martin]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]])\n| unit_pref                = Imperial\n| area_magnitude           = 1 E9\n| area_total_km2           = 134.9\n| area_total_sq_mi         = 52.1\n| area_land_km2            = 97.9\n| area_land_sq_mi          = 37.7\n| area_water_km2           = 37.0\n| area_water_sq_mi         = 14.3\n| area_water_percent       = \n| area_urban_km2           = 1205\n| elevation_m              = 7\n| elevation_ft             = 23\n| population_total         = 122,643\n| population_as_of         = [[2010 U.S. Census|2010]]\n| population_footnotes     = <ref>{{cite web|date=March 2011|url=http://www.ctpost.com/databases/article/Connecticut-population-in-2010-1050512.php?RecordID=136&PageID=3&PrevPageID=2&cpipage=6&CPIsortType=&CPIorderBy=|title=Connecticut population in 2010|format=[[Comma-separated values|CSV]]|work=2011 Population Estimates|publisher=U.S. Census Bureau, Population Division|accessdate=July 9, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/quickfacts/stamfordcityconnecticut|title=U.S. Census Bureau QuickFacts: Stamford city, Connecticut|website=Census.gov|accessdate=January 21, 2019}}</ref>\n| population_density_km2   = 1226\n| population_density_sq_mi = auto\n| population_est           = 129,775\n| pop_est_as_of            = 2018\n| pop_est_footnotes        = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=July 16, 2019}}</ref>\n| population_metro         = 916,829\n| population_demonym       = Stamfordian, Stamfordite\n| population_note          = \n| postal_code_type         = ZIP code\n| postal_code              = 069xx\n| area_code                = [[Area codes 203 and 475|203/475]]\n| area_code_type           = Area code\n| website                  = {{URL|http://www.stamfordct.gov/}}\n| timezone                 = [[Eastern Time Zone|Eastern]]\n| utc_offset               = -5\n| timezone_DST             = [[Eastern Time Zone|Eastern]]\n| utc_offset_DST           = -4\n| blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n| blank_info               = 09-73000\n| blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n| blank1_info              = 0211129\n| blank2_name              = Major highways\n| blank2_info              = [[File:I-95.svg|25px|link=Interstate 95 in Connecticut]] [[File:Merritt Pkwy Shield.svg|25px|link=Merritt Parkway]]\n| blank3_name              = [[Commuter rail|Commuter Rail]]\n| blank3_info              = [[File:Amtrak logo 2.svg|25px|link=Amtrak]] [[File:MTA NYC logo.svg|25px|link=New Haven Line]] [[File:SLE logo.svg|25px|link=Shore Line East]]\n}}\n\n'''Stamford''' is a city in [[Fairfield County, Connecticut|Fairfield County]], [[Connecticut]], United States. According to the [[United States Census Bureau|US Census Bureau]], the population of the city is 129,775 as of July 1, 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/quickfacts/stamfordcityconnecticut|title=census.gov|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref> As of 2017, according to the Census Bureau, the population of Stamford had risen to 131,000, making it the third-largest city in the state (behind [[Bridgeport, Connecticut|Bridgeport]] and [[New Haven, Connecticut|New Haven]]) and the [[New England#Demographics|seventh-largest city in New England]]. Approximately {{convert|30|mi|km|sigfig=1|abbr=off|sp=us}} from [[Manhattan]], Stamford is in the [[Greater Bridgeport|Bridgeport-Stamford-Norwalk-Danbury Metro area]] which is a part of the Greater [[New York metropolitan area]].\n\nStamford is home to eight [[Fortune 500]] companies as of 2019,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fortune.com/fortune500/2019/search/?hqcity=Stamford&hqstate=CT|title=Fortune500|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\"fortune\">{{cite web|url=https://fortune.com/fortune500/2019/search/?hqcity=Stamford|title=Fortune 500|date=29 March 2019|work=Fortune}}</ref> as well as numerous divisions of large corporations. This gives Stamford the largest [[financial centre|financial district]] in the New York metropolitan region outside New York City itself and one of the largest concentrations of corporations in the United States.\n\n==History==\n{{Main|History of Stamford, Connecticut}}\nStamford was known as Rippowam by the [[Siwanoy]] [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] inhabitants to the region, and the very first [[Europe]]an settlers to the area also referred to it as such. The present name is after the town of [[Stamford, Lincolnshire]], England.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Connecticut Magazine: An Illustrated Monthly|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qoEyAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA334|year=1903|publisher=Connecticut Magazine Company|page=334}}</ref> The [[deed]] to Stamford was signed on July 1, 1640, between Captain Turner of the [[New Haven Colony]] and Chief Ponus. By the 18th century, one of the primary industries of the town was merchandising by water, which was possible due to Stamford's proximity to New York.\n[[File:Stamford Aerial 2017.png|thumb|250x250px|Downtown and South End neighborhoods of Stamford. Long Island is in the distance.]]\n\nIn 1692, Stamford was home to a less famous [[witch trial]] than the well-known [[Salem witch trials]], which also occurred in 1692. The accusations were less fanatical and on a smaller scale, but they also grew to prominence through gossip and hysterics.<ref name=\"singular\">{{Cite book|last=Godbeer|first=Richard|title=Escaping Salem|date=January 2005|publisher=Oxford|isbn=0-19-516130-0| chapter=Chapter 1: Katherine Branch's Fits}}</ref>\n\n[[New Canaan, Connecticut|New Canaan]] officially separated from Stamford when it incorporated as a town in 1801, followed by [[Darien, Connecticut|Darien]] in 1820.\n\nStarting in the late 19th century, New York residents built summer homes on the shoreline, and even back then there were some who moved to Stamford permanently and started commuting to Manhattan by train, although the practice became more popular later. Stamford incorporated as a city in 1893.\n\nIn 1950, the [[United States Census Bureau|Census Bureau]] reported the city's population as 94.6% white and 5.2% black.<ref>{{cite web |title=Race and Hispanic Origin for Selected Cities and Other Places: Earliest Census to 1990 |publisher=U.S. Census Bureau |url=https://www.census.gov/population/www/documentation/twps0076/twps0076.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/69hd5KAIE?url=http://www.census.gov/population/www/documentation/twps0076/twps0076.html |archivedate=August 6, 2012 |access-date=December 7, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nIn the 1960s and 1970s, Stamford's commercial real estate boomed as corporations relocated from New York City to peripheral areas.<ref>{{cite crabgrass}}, p.268</ref> A massive urban redevelopment campaign during that time resulted in a downtown with many tall office buildings. The F.D. Rich Company was the city-designated urban renewal developer of the downtown in an ongoing redevelopment project that was contentious, beginning in the 1960s and continuing through the 1970s. The company put up what was the city's tallest structure, One Landmark Square, at 21 floors high, and the GTE building (now One Stamford Forum), along with the Marriott Hotel, the Stamford Town Center and many of the other downtown office buildings. One Landmark Square has since been dwarfed by the new 34-story [[Trump Parc Stamford]] condominium tower, and then again by the Atlantic Station development, another project by the Rich Company in partnership with Cappelli Enterprises.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/09/26/realestate/commercial-property-stamford-conn-pioneer-business-park-that-confounded-critics.html|title=Commercial Property /Stamford, Conn.; A Pioneer Business Park That Confounded Critics|first=Eleanor|last=Charles|date=September 26, 1999|website=Nytimes.com}}</ref> Over the years, other developers have joined in building up the downtown, a process that continued, with breaks during downturns in the economy, through the 1980s and 1990s and into the new century.\n\nSince 2008, an 80-acre mixed-use redevelopment project for the Stamford's [[Harbor Point, Stamford|Harbor Point]] neighborhood has added additional growth south of the city's [[Downtown Stamford|Downtown]] area. Once complete, the redevelopment will include 6,000,000 square feet (560,000 m<sup>2</sup>) of new residential, retail, office and hotel space, and a marina. As of July 2012, roughly 900 of the projected 4,000 Harbor Point residential units had been constructed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ctpost.com/news/article/Trending-Why-one-city-is-booming-4540657.php|title=Trending: Why one city is booming|work=Connecticut Post|date=May 23, 2013}}</ref>\nNew restaurants and recreational activities have come up in the Harbor Point area, which is considered as New Stamford.\n\n==Geography==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=December 2018}}\n[[File:Stamford CT night aerial from the west.jpg|thumb|right|Stamford at night from the west, with [[Norwalk, Connecticut|Norwalk]], [[Bridgeport, Connecticut|Bridgeport]], and [[New Haven, Connecticut|New Haven]] beyond. [[Long Island Sound]] is completely dark.]]\n\n  \nStamford is situated near the southwestern point of Connecticut, on [[Long Island Sound]]. It consists of several neighborhoods and villages including Cove, East Side, Downtown, North Stamford, Glenbrook, West Side, Turn Of River, Waterside, [[Springdale (Stamford)|Springdale]], Belltown, Ridgeway, Newfield, South End, Westover, Shippan, Roxbury and Palmers Hill. North of the [[Merritt Parkway]] is considered the [[North Stamford]] section of the city, encompassing its largest land mass though it is the least densely populated. North Stamford functionally and legally acts as one municipality with the City of Stamford. Stamford borders Pound Ridge, New York to the North, the Long Island Sound to the South, Greenwich, Connecticut to the West, Darien to the East, and New Canaan to the Northeast.\n\nThe city has an area of {{convert|52.09|sqmi|km2}}, making it the largest city by area in the state.<ref>{{cite web |title=Stamford Master Plan |url=https://www.stamfordct.gov/sites/stamfordct/files/u358/final_draft_12.16.14_0.pdf |website=stamfordct.gov |accessdate=4 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Climate===\nUnder the [[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]], Stamford has a [[temperate climate]] (''Cfa''),  with long, hot summers, and cool to cold winters, with precipitation spread fairly evenly throughout the year. Stamford, like the rest of coastal Connecticut, lies in the broad transition zone between the colder continental climates of the northern United States and southern Canada to the north, and the warmer temperate and subtropical climates of the middle and [[south Atlantic states]] to the south.\n\nThe warm/hot season in Stamford is from mid-April through early November. Late day thundershowers are common in the hottest months (June, July, August, September), despite the mostly sunny skies. The cool/cold season is from late November though mid March. Winter weather is far more variable than summer weather along the Connecticut coast, ranging from sunny days with higher temperatures to cold and blustery conditions with occasional snow. Like much of the Connecticut coast and nearby Long Island, NY, some of the winter precipitation is rain or a mix and rain and wet snow in Stamford. Stamford averages about {{convert|30|in|cm|round=5}} of snow annually, compared to inland areas like [[Hartford, Connecticut|Hartford]] and [[Albany, New York|Albany]] which average {{convert|45-60|in|cm}} of snow annually.\n\nAlthough infrequent, [[tropical cyclones]] (hurricanes/tropical storms) have struck Connecticut and the Stamford metropolitan area. Hurricane landfalls have occurred along the Connecticut coast in 1903, 1938, 1944, 1954 (Carol), 1960 (Donna), [[Hurricane Gloria]] in 1985, and [[Hurricane Sandy]] in 2012.\n\nStamford lies in [[USDA]] garden zone 7a. Stamford averages about 90 days annually with freeze. Coastal Connecticut is the broad transition zone where so-called \"subtropical indicator\" plants and other broadleaf evergreens can successfully be cultivated. As such, Southern Magnolias, Needle Palms, Windmill palm, Loblolly Pines, and Crape Myrtles are grown in private and public gardens. Like much of coastal Connecticut, Long Island, and coastal New Jersey, the growing season is rather long in Stamford\u2014averaging 210 days from April{{nbsp}}8 to November{{nbsp}}5 according to the National Weather Service in Bridgeport.\n\n{{Weather box\n|location = Stamford, Connecticut\n|single line = Y\n|Jan record high F =  69\n|Feb record high F =  74\n|Mar record high F =  85\n|Apr record high F =  96\n|May record high F =  97\n|Jun record high F =  97\n|Jul record high F = 102\n|Aug record high F = 104\n|Sep record high F =  97\n|Oct record high F =  86\n|Nov record high F =  82\n|Dec record high F =  76\n|year record high F = 89\n|Jan high F = 38.2\n|Feb high F = 42.3\n|Mar high F = 50.6\n|Apr high F = 63.2\n|May high F = 73.2\n|Jun high F = 81.2\n|Jul high F = 85.6\n|Aug high F = 83.7\n|Sep high F = 76.4\n|Oct high F = 65.2\n|Nov high F = 54.4\n|Dec high F = 43.0\n|Jan low F = 20.0\n|Feb low F = 22.2\n|Mar low F = 29.2\n|Apr low F = 38.8\n|May low F = 48.1\n