2''\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Independent}}|0.65% ''302''\n|-\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|[[1972 United States presidential election|1972]]\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|37.97% ''18,299''\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''60.74%''' ''29,268''\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Independent}}|1.29% ''622''\n|-\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|[[1968 United States presidential election|1968]]\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|45.97% ''20,926''\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''48.74%''' ''22,186''\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Independent}}|5.28% ''2,405''\n|-\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|[[1964 United States presidential election|1964]]\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''64.50%''' ''29,078''\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|35.50% ''16,004''\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Independent}}|0.00% ''0''\n|-\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|[[1960 United States presidential election|1960]]\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|49.86% ''21,448''\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''50.14%''' ''21,572''\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Independent}}|0.00% ''0''\n|-\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|[[1956 United States presidential election|1956]]\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|34.30% ''13,977''\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''65.70%''' ''26,767''\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Independent}}|0.00% ''0''\n|}\n\nStamford is predominantly [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] but not nearly as heavily Democratic as Connecticut's more urban cities like neighboring [[Bridgeport, Connecticut|Bridgeport]] and [[New Haven, Connecticut|New Haven]].\n\nDemocrat [[David Martin (Mayor)|David Martin]] is the incumbent Mayor of Stamford. Notable Republicans from the city include former [[U.S. Representative]] [[Christopher Shays|Chris Shays]], former [[Lieutenant governor of Connecticut|Lieutenant Governor]] [[Michael Fedele]], and former mayor [[Michael Pavia]]. Prominent Democrats from Stamford include current [[Attorney General of Connecticut|Attorney General]] [[William Tong]], former two-term Governor [[Dannel Malloy]], former Attorney General and incumbent senior [[U.S. Senator]] [[Richard Blumenthal]], former Attorney General [[George Jepsen]], former U.S. Attorney General and former mayor [[Homer Stille Cummings]], Connecticut Supreme Court Justice [[Andrew J. McDonald]], and Chief Justice of the Connecticut Supreme Court [[Richard A. Robinson]]. Other notable politicians with Stamford roots include [[Carrie Clyde Holly]], the first woman (along with two colleagues) elected to serve in a State Legislature (Colorado, from Pueblo County in the 1894 election) in United States History, [[Joe Lieberman]], former Attorney General of Connecticut and Independent/Democratic [[U.S. Senator]] who was also [[Al Gore]]'s vice presidential nominee in the [[2000 United States presidential election|2000 presidential election]]; [[William F. Buckley, Jr.]], conservative commentator; and French Prime Minister [[Georges Clemenceau]].\n\n==Transportation==\n===Mass transit===\n[[File:Stamford Transportation Center Metro North Train.jpg|alt=|thumb|300px|Manhattan-bound Metro-North Train leaving the Stamford Transportation Center]]\n[[File:Stamford, CT Marriott Hotel from train tracks in Stamford, CT.jpg|thumb|Stamford, CT Marriott Hotel from train tracks in Stamford, CT]]\n\nStamford is located on the [[New Haven Line]] on the [[Metro-North Railroad]], the commuter rail system for northern metropolitan New York City. [[Stamford (Metro-North station)|Stamford]] is the busiest station on the Metro-North system, after only Grand Central Terminal, and serves as a major transfer point for local trains.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lytton |first1=Barry |title=Stamford train station gets $22.9M for improvements |url=https://www.stamfordadvocate.com/local/article/Stamford-train-station-gets-22-9M-for-13450442.php |website=StamfordAdvocate |accessdate=4 February 2019 |date=7 December 2018}}</ref> Stamford Station is also the terminus of a Metro-North branch that ends in [[New Canaan, Connecticut|New Canaan]], {{convert|8|mi|abbr=on}} away, and a part-time terminal of [[Shore Line East]] trains. Two smaller train stations in Stamford are [[Glenbrook (Metro-North station)|Glenbrook]] and [[Springdale (Metro-North station)|Springdale]], both a part of the [[New Canaan Branch|New Canaan branch]].\n\nCommuter trains come into Stamford from all points between [[New London, Connecticut|New London]] to the east and [[Grand Central Terminal|New York (Grand Central Terminal)]] to the south. The average non-stop commute is forty-seven minutes. Trains operate from the Stamford station between 4:43&nbsp;a.m. (first departure to Grand Central) until 12:55&nbsp;a.m. (last departure to Grand Central).\n\nStamford also serves as a station along the [[Amtrak]] route. [[Acela Express|Acela]], the high speed train service between Boston and Washington, makes several daily stops in Stamford. Amtrak's [[Northeast Regional]] (Springfield, Massachusetts to Washington, D.C.) and [[Vermonter (train)|Vermonter]] (Saint Albans, Vermont to Washington, D.C.) also make daily stops in Stamford. Amtrak tickets can be purchased on the upper level of the Stamford station.\n\n===Airports===\nStamford is within reasonable distance of nine airports: two general aviation, two regional, five international.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! General aviation airports !! Distance from Downtown/Location\n|-\n| [[Danbury Municipal Airport]] || 21 miles north in [[Danbury, Connecticut|Danbury, CT]]\n|-\n| [[Sikorsky Memorial Airport]] || 22 miles east in [[Stratford, Connecticut|Stratford, CT]]\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Regional airports !! Distance form Downtown/Location\n|-\n| [[Westchester County Airport]] || 8 miles west in [[Westchester County, NY]]\n|-\n| [[Tweed New Haven Airport]] || 37 miles east in [[East Haven, Connecticut|East Haven, CT]]\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! International Airports !! Distance from Downtown/Location\n|-\n| [[LaGuardia Airport]] || 26 miles southwest in [[Queens, New York|Queens, NY]]\n|-\n| [[John F. Kennedy International Airport]] || 31 miles southwest in Queens, NY\n|-\n| [[Newark Liberty International Airport]] || 41 miles southwest in [[Newark, New Jersey|Newark, NJ]]\n|-\n| [[Stewart International Airport]] || 43 miles northwest in [[Newburgh, New York|Newburgh, NY]]\n|-\n| [[Bradley International Airport]] || 75 miles northeast in [[Windsor Locks, Connecticut|Windsor Locks, CT]]\n|}\n\n===Buses===\nCity bus transportation is provided by [[Connecticut Transit Stamford|CT Transit]], which is run and financed by the Connecticut Department of Transportation. The main terminal is adjacent to the train station on State Street, under the I-95 highway. Bus service runs along major arterial roads through the towns of [[Darien, Connecticut|Darien]], [[Norwalk, Connecticut|Norwalk]], [[Greenwich, Connecticut|Greenwich]] and [[Port Chester, New York]]. A non-stop direct route is also offered to [[White Plains, New York]]. Commuters can connect in Norwalk to points as far east as [[Milford, Connecticut|Milford]] and as far north as [[Danbury, Connecticut|Danbury]]. Additional connections can be made in Port Chester and White Plains to all points covered by the [[Bee-Line Bus System|Bee-Line]] bus system in [[Westchester County, New York|Westchester County]].\n\n[[Greyhound Lines|Greyhound]] provides inter-city bus service from the lower level of the Stamford train station. Bus service is provided to [[Union Station (New Haven)|New Haven (Union Station)]], [[South Station|Boston (South Station)]], and [[Port Authority Bus Terminal|New York (Port Authority)]].\n\n===Highways===\nTwo limited-access highways run through the city. [[Interstate 95 in Connecticut|Interstate 95]] serves as the main route through downtown Stamford with four exits (6\u20139). The [[Merritt Parkway]] runs through the northern part of the city. This road is designated for passenger vehicles only. Any congestion on the Merritt Parkway is mostly likely to occur on the southbound lane in the morning and the northbound in the evening (route to and from New York). At night, due to the absence of lighting, visibility on the Merritt Parkway is relatively poor. Stamford exits on the Merritt Parkway are 33\u201335, and exit 36 is just over the border in New Canaan.\n\nStamford is also served by four other state highways. [[U.S. Route 1 in Connecticut|Route{{nbsp}}1]], also known as Main Street in Stamford, is also used as a major artery during the morning and evening commute. Most traffic via Route{{nbsp}}1 is short distance or fairly local, yet vehicles have utilized Route{{nbsp}}1 during times of heavy congestion on I-95 as a re-route. [[Connecticut Route 137|Route 137]] (Washington Boulevard and High Ridge Road) is the main north\u2013south road of the city and runs from the Stamford Transportation Center and serves the Turn of River, North Stamford, and High Ridge sections of the city. [[Connecticut Route 104|Route 104]] (Long Ridge Road) branches off from Route 137 to serve the Long Ridge section. [[Connecticut Route 106|Route 106]] (Courtland Avenue) serves the Glenbrook neighborhood and continues towards the town of [[Darien, Connecticut|Darien]].\n\n==Economy==\n[[File:1 Blachley Rd-NBC Sports Group.jpg|thumb|375px|[[NBC Sports Group]] world headquarters at 1{{nbsp}}Blachley Road]]\n{{Main|Economy of Stamford, Connecticut}}\n\nStamford's cluster of corporate headquarters includes a number of [[Fortune 500]], [[Fortune 1000]], and [[Forbes Global 2000]] companies. In 2017, Stamford had four Fortune 500, nine Fortune 1000, three Forbes Global 2000,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/global2000/list/#state:Connecticut|title=The World's Biggest Public Companies|work=Forbes.com|access-date=August 23, 2017|language=en}}</ref> and one [[Fortune Global 500]] company.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fortune.com/fortune500/list/filtered?hqcity=Stamford|title=Fortune 500 Companies 2017: Who Made the List|website=Fortune.com|language=en-US|access-date=August 23, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAmong the larger companies with headquarters in Stamford are [[Charter Communications]], [[Synchrony Financial]], [[Indeed|Indeed.com]], [[United Rentals]], [[Conair Corporation|Conair]], [[Gartner]], [[Henkel Corporation|Henkel North American Consumer Goods]], [[WWE]], [[XFL (2020)|XFL]], [[Pitney Bowes]], [[Gen Re]], [[NBC Sports Group]], [[Nestl\u00e9 Waters North America|Nestle Waters North America]], [[Crane Co.]] and [[Vineyard Vines]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stamfordct.gov/economic-development/pages/stamfords-major-employers|title=Stamford's Major Employers {{!}} Stamford CT|website=Stamfordct.gov|language=en|access-date=August 23, 2017}}</ref> [[UBS|UBS's]] Stamford [[trading floor]] holds the [[Guinness World Records|Guinness World Record]] as the largest column-less trading floor in the world. [[The Royal Bank of Scotland]] moved its North American operations into Stamford in 2009, including its [[RBS Securities|RBS Greenwich Capital]] subsidiary.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.stamfordadvocate.com/business/article/Royal-Bank-of-Scotland-to-sell-Stamford-building-12965306.php |title=Royal Bank of Scotland to sell Stamford building|date=4 June 2018|accessdate=27 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Harbor Point development, located in the [[South End of Stamford|South End]], is one of the largest private-sector development projects in the United States.<ref name=\"PR Web\">{{cite web|url=http://www.prweb.com/releases/2012/3/prweb9270725.htm|title=Harbor Point Spurs Stamford's Economic Growth with Thousands of New Jobs|date=March 11, 2012|website=Prweb.com}}</ref> Many large retail stores, such as [[Herman Miller (manufacturer)|Design within Reach]] (which is also headquartered in Stamford) and [[Fairway Market]] have moved in, along with multiple companies including [[ITV Studios|ITV America]], [[McKinsey & Company]], [[Bridgewater Associates]], and the headquarters of [[Starwood|Starwood Hotels]] (Now [[Marriott International]]), and [[Kayak.com|KAYAK.com]].\n\n==Crime==\nAccording to FBI statistics in 2014, Stamford is the 16th safest of the 269 cities in the nation and well ahead of any in Connecticut with a population greater than 100,000 that report crime statistics to the FBI.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stamfordadvocate.com/news/article/Stamford-police-say-downtown-is-safe-despite-6134408.php|title=Stamford police say downtown is safe, despite homicide and other recent crimes|website=Stamfordadvocate.com}}</ref> In 2015, Stamford had three murders, 19 rapes, and 92 robberies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.city-data.com/crime/crime-Stamford-Connecticut.html|title=Crime in Stamford, Connecticut (CT): murders, rapes, robberies, assaults, burglaries, thefts, auto thefts, arson, law enforcement employees, police officers, crime map|website=City-data.com}}</ref> Crime in Stamford is much more controlled in comparison to cities with similar population size in Connecticut and nationally. Lower crime rates in Stamford are attributed to the city's robust economic growth in recent decades.\n\nCriminal cases are prosecuted by The State's Attorney's Office and Stamford is home to a State Superior Court which is located on 123 Hoyt Street adjacent to the Stamford Police Headquarters.\n\n==Emergency services==\n===Stamford Emergency Medical Services===\nA not-for-profit agency, Stamford Emergency Medical Services (SEMS) provides pre-hospital emergency care in Stamford, Connecticut. SEMS also provides contracted paramedic intercept response to Darien Emergency Medical Services, located in Darien, Connecticut. SEMS is the only Connecticut EMS service accredited by the Commission on the Accreditation of Ambulance Services (CAAS). All SEMS units are staffed by at least one Connecticut-licensed paramedic.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stamfordems.org/|title=STAMFORD EMS\u2014A Not-For-Profit Charitable Organization Providing Consistent, Compassionate, Quality Paramedic Ambulance Services|website=Stamfordems.org}}</ref> Stamford EMS responds to 14,000 calls annually.\n\nIn Stamford, medical facilities include;\n* [[Stamford Hospital]], Level II Trauma Center\n* Tully Health Center\n* Franklin Street Community Health Center\n\n===Fire department===\nFire protection in the city of Stamford is provided by the paid Stamford Fire Rescue Department (SFRD) and four all-volunteer fire departments\u2014Glenbrook-New Hope, Belltown, Springdale, and Turn of River\u2014plus a Combination Company, Long Ridge.\nStamford Fired Department's Headquarters are located on 629 Main Street, Stamford CT, 06901. They operate several other stations which are: South End Fire Station 215 Washington Boulevard, Stamford CT, 06902, West Side Fire Station 80 Fairfield Avenue, Stamford CT, 06902, East Side/Shippan Fire Station 364 Shippan Avenue, Stamford CT, 06902, and Woodside Fire Station 1600 Washington Boulevard, Stamford CT, 06902.\n\nBudgeting and districting of the various fire departments throughout the city has been unstable since 2007, due to an extended legal conflict between the volunteer departments and the Malloy administration.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stamfordadvocate.com/default/article/Stamford-fire-service-consolidation-part-of-272317.php|last=Morganteen|first=Jeff|date=December 2, 2009|title=Stamford fire service consolidation part of Malloy's legacy|website=Stamfordadvocate.com|accessdate=August 29, 2011}}</ref> As of May 16, 2012, a decision was reached by the city's charter revision committee to combine the paid and volunteer fire departments into one combination fire department, known as the Stamford Fire Department.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehour.com/stamford_times/news/evision-commission-recommends-single-fire-chief/article_b6967308-2ccb-530e-8b4c-a3cd8da73f3e.html|last=O'Connor|first=Kara|date=May 16, 2012|title=Charter Revision Commission recommends single fire chief \n|website=Thehour.com|accessdate=May 17, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Police department===\nThe Stamford Police Department (SPD) is Stamford's only police force and has lost four officers in the line of service since 1938. The police force has about 280 sworn police officers making it the 5th largest police force in Connecticut after Hartford, New Haven, Bridgeport, and Waterbury.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cga.ct.gov/2011/rpt/2011-R-0194.htm|title=CONNECTICUT POLICE DEPARTMENT STATISTICS|first=Veronica Rose, Chief|last=Analyst|website=Cga.ct.gov}}</ref> Most Stamford Officers were trained at the Connecticut Police Training Academy before patrolling in the city. Aside from Police Headquarters, located at 725 Bedford St., opened in 2019, in [[Downtown Stamford]], SPD also operates substations in Stamford's [[West Side of Stamford|West Side]] at Wilson St. and W. Main St. and at 1137 High Ridge Rd and Hope Street. The current Chief of Police is Thomas Wuenneman who become police chief upon Former Police Chief Fountneau's resignation. The City is currently searching for a new police chief.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.greenwichtime.com/local/article/Pavia-names-Fontneau-as-police-chief-3923952.php|title=Pavia names Fontneau as police chief.}}</ref><ref>https://www.stamfordadvocate.com/local/article/Wuennemann-named-interim-Stamford-police-chief-14067799.php</ref>\n\n==Education==\n{{Main|Education in Stamford, Connecticut}}\nStamford has branches of the [[University of Connecticut]], [[University of Bridgeport]] and [[Sacred Heart University]]. The University of Connecticut's [[campus]] is located in a large modern building downtown which opened in 1998 after extensive renovations to an abandoned former [[Bloomingdale's]] store that had closed in 1990.<ref>{{Cite news| url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C0DE6DE1639F936A35752C0A961958260&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=1 | work=The New York Times | title=Stamford Reinvents Its Downtown Once Again | first=David W. | last=Dunlap | date=January 5, 1997 | accessdate=May 24, 2010}}</ref> The University of Bridgeport has an branch at the River Bend Executive Center, and Sacred Heart University has an branch at Landmark Square. In 2017, UCONN Stamford opened a 300 student dormitory hall around the corner from the Stamford Campus on Washington Blvd.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.stamfordadvocate.com/local/article/UConn-to-open-dorms-in-Stamford-Wednesday-11822807.php|title=UConn-Stamford opens first dormitory|work=StamfordAdvocate|access-date=December 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAs no study has been conducted to assess the cost of education in Stamford, it is difficult to tell whether or not Stamford has a well-funded public education system. Although providing a public education is a state responsibility, Connecticut ranks near the bottom in state share of public education expenditures. Thus, the majority of education funding must come from local governments like that of Stamford. According to the State Department of Education, in the 2004\u201305 academic year, 42.7% of Stamford's public school students were economically disadvantaged, 34.8% did not have English as a home language and 11.6% were students with disabilities. Research has shown that these populations need additional resources to meet state academic standards. Owing to the state school finance system, the burden of these extra necessary costs of education falls primarily on Stamford's local government. The public school system is an integrated district with racial balance requirements exceeding those of the state of Connecticut. State standards require that a school's racial makeup be within 25% of the community's racial makeup. Stamford's standard is a more strict 10%. Over the years, schools have become unbalanced.\n\nStamford has three public [[high school]]s: [[Westhill High School (Connecticut)|Westhill High School]], [[Stamford High School (Connecticut)|Stamford High School]], and the [[Academy of Information Technology and Engineering]]. The city also has several private schools, including [[Trinity Catholic High School (Connecticut)|Trinity Catholic High School]], Villa Maria School, and Bi-Cultural Jewish Day School, [[King Low Heywood Thomas]], and The Long Ridge School as well as one state charter school: Stamford Academy Charter High School, which is closing in June 2020 which is operated by Domus <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stamfordacademy.org|title=Welcome to Stamford Academy|website=Stamfordacademy.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.domuskids.org/|title=Domus|website=Domuskids.org|accessdate=January 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Libraries==\nStamford's [[public library]], the [[Ferguson Library]], is one of the largest in Connecticut. The library also shows movies and has a [[used book]] store run by Friends of Ferguson Library.\n\nThe library has branches in South End, Springdale, and the Turn of River sections of the city, it also has a bookmobile that runs daily to different neighborhoods. The Turn of River branch, officially called the Harry Bennett Branch, is the largest library branch in the state. That branch also has a used book store run by Friends of Ferguson Library.\n\n==Sports==\n* The first Marathon race to be held in the United States, on September 19, 1896, had its start line at Stamford Armory. The race, which finished in [[Williamsbridge, Bronx]], was won by [[John McDermott (runner)|John J. McDermott]] of New York City in a time of 3:25:55.6.\n* The [[New England Force]], a professional soccer team based in Stamford, made its debut in the [[American Soccer League (2014)|American Soccer League]] in August 2014.<ref>{{cite news |last=Scavuzzo |first=Diane |date=April 8, 2014 |title=Soccer News: New England Force Joins American Soccer League for Inaugural Season |url=http://www.soccernation.com/new-england-force-joins-asl-cms-5471 |newspaper=soccernation.com |accessdate=July 11, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140716013608/http://www.soccernation.com/new-england-force-joins-asl-cms-5471 |archive-date=July 16, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* [[NBC Sunday Night Football]] and the pre-game [[Football Night in America]] show has aired from Stamford since 2014.\n* The [[Connecticut Whale (NWHL)]], one of four charter franchises in the [[National Women's Hockey League]], has competed at the Terry Conners Ice Rink since 2015.\n\n==Parks and recreation sites==\n[[File:Shippan Landing Stamford Connecticut Skyline Aerial.jpg|thumb|350x350px|Stamford boasts miles of accessible shoreline for recreation as well as two public beaches.]]\n* [[Mill River Park]] is located in the center of downtown but its ancient grist mill (present when George Washington traveled through Stamford) was modernized in the 1920s. There are numerous community activities offered at the park coordinated by the [http://www.millriverpark.org/ Mill River Park Collaborative].\n* [[Cummings Park]], a public beach, was once a popular spot for shell fishing. The park was developed in 1906 and had been known as Halloween Park because Mayor [[Homer Stille Cummings|Homer Cummings]] cast the deciding vote to create it on Halloween Night.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stamfordhistory.org/ph_0704.htm|title=Stamford Historical Society, The Stamford Historical Society: Photo Selection of the Month, July 2004, Shippan Point|website=Stamfordhistory.org}}</ref>\n* The {{convert|83|acre|m2|adj=on}} '''[[Cove Island Park]]''', once a farm and then an enormous factory site (Stamford Manufacturing Company), offers visitors a choice of beaches as well as picnic grounds and bluffs. It has a small wildlife sanctuary in the southwest corner that might be interesting for bird watchers. SoundWaters Community Center for Environmental Education is located at the northeast part of the park.\n* Jackie Robinson Park on the West Side is named after baseball legend [[Jackie Robinson]], who lived in Stamford.\n* Terry Connors Ice Rink<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tcrink.com |title=Homepage|website=Tcrink.com}}</ref> shares a parking lot with Cove Island Park. It offers public ice skating, group lessons, and [[ice hockey]]. It is the home of the Stamford Youth Hockey Association.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://syha.org/|title=Stamford Youth Hockey Association|website=Syha.org}}</ref> \n* Scalzi Park on Bridge Street has a playground, baseball and softball fields, volleyball courts, tennis courts, bocce courts, basketball courts, roller hockey courts, and a baseball stadium named \"Cubeta Stadium\". A concrete skate park was opened at Scalzi in July 2007 for $309,850 which was designed and built by Grindline Skateparks Inc. of Seattle, Washington.<ref>Porstner, Donna, \"Curve appeal/ Area's new skate park opens\", news article in ''[[The Advocate (Stamford)|The Advocate]]'' of Stamford, July 13, 2007, pp 1, A6</ref>\n* Stamford has two municipal golf courses. Sterling Farms Golf Course<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sterlingfarmsgc.com/|title=Sterling Farms Golf Course|website=Sterlingfarmsgc.com}}</ref> opened in May 1972 and is the more popular.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite news| url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-16537209_ITM | work=Stamford Advocate | title=Sterling Farms golfers fight to keep money | first=Donna | last=Porstner | date=June 28, 2006}}</ref> The facility also has a driving range, restaurant, and six tennis courts.\n* The E. Gaynor Brennan Golf Course,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brennangolf.com|title=E. Gaynor Brennan Golf Course\u2014Stamford, CT|website=Brennangolf.com}}</ref> referred to locally as Hubbard Heights, opened for play in 1922 as a private course and was purchased by the city in 1949.\n* Dorothy Heroy Park is located in North Stamford.\n* Mianus River Park is 187 acres of nature reserve in Stamford, owned by the city.\n* The Italian Center<ref>{{cite web|url=http://italiancenter.org/|title=Italian Center of Stamford, CT: Outdoor Pools, Indoor Pool, Tennis, Fitness Center, Nursery School, Camps, Banquet Hall|website=Italiancenter.org}}</ref> features tennis courts, swimming pools, fitness centers, a playground and a [[miniature golf]] course.\n* The YMCA<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stamfordymca.org/|title=Stamford Family YMCA|work=Stamford YMCA}}</ref> of Stamford offers [[swimming lessons]] and sports which include; basketball and [[indoor soccer]]. Programs are also available periodically for physical fitness.\n* The Stamford Yacht Club<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stamfordyc.com/guest-welcome|title=Guest Welcome\u2014Stamford Yacht Club|website=Stamfordyc.com|access-date=October 19, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131020072651/http://www.stamfordyc.com/guest-welcome|archive-date=October 20, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> is a private organization that provides members with access to [[boating]] activities and additional amenities.\n\n==Arts, science, and cultural attractions==\n\n{{Main|Arts and culture in Stamford, Connecticut}}\n\n===Science and nature===\n\n* The [[Stamford Museum and Nature Center]] on a {{convert|118|acre|km2|adj=on}} site in the northern end of town, has a collection of works by [[Gutzon Borglum]], the sculptor of Mount Rushmore, who was a Stamford resident for a decade.\n* The Fairfield County Astronomical Society was started up in 1954 runs the Stamford Observatory, which has a {{convert|22|in|mm|adj=on}} telescope.\n* Bartlett Arboretum and Gardens is a {{convert|91|acre|m2|adj=on}} botanical gardens and science education center boasting over 850 specimen trees and plants from around the world. It is also home to several Champion Trees; the largest of their species within Connecticut.\n* SoundWaters Community Center for Environmental Education is located in Cove Island Park.\n\n===Theater, film, and video===\n[[File:Avon Theatre Stamford 2013.jpg|thumb|Avon Theatre, in 2013]]\n* Curtain Call Inc. presents plays and other entertainment at the Sterling Farms Theatre Complex, 1349 Newfield Avenue.\n* Stamford Center for the Arts: The Palace Theatre, originally opened as a vaudeville house in 1927, reopened as a nonprofit theater in 1983. It was joined in 1992 by the Rich Forum, another downtown venue. Both have been run by the [[Stamford Center for the Arts]].\n* [[Forever Marilyn|Latham Park]]\n* The Rich Forum is occupied by [[NBCUniversal]] as a television studio where various television shows are taped and produced including [[The Jerry Springer Show]], [[Maury (TV series)|Maury]], and [[The Steve Wilkos Show]], [[The Trisha Goddard Show]], and [[Crazy Talk]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://patch.com/connecticut/stamford/trisha-goddard-begins-production-at-stamford-media-center|title='Trisha Goddard' Talk Show Begins Production in Stamford|date=July 30, 2012|work=Stamford, CT Patch|access-date=December 19, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> \n* Bow Tie Cinemas has two first-run movie houses in Stamford with a total of 15 movie screens: Landmark{{nbsp}}9 and Majestic{{nbsp}}6. The Avon Theatre Film Center, a two-screen nonprofit movie house focusing on first-run independent movies, is located on Bedford Street. The Ferguson Library also shows movies.\n\n====Movies shot in Stamford====\n{{Main|List of films shot in Stamford, Connecticut}}\n\n===Music===\n* Stamford Symphony Orchestra In a typical season, the SSO gives five pairs of classical concerts and three pops concerts at the 1,586-seat Palace Theatre, as well as a concert for elementary school students and a family concert series.\n* Connecticut Grand Opera, a not-for-profit, professional opera company performs at the Palace Theatre. On its web site, the CGO claims to offer \"the most ambitious opera season of any company between New York and Boston\".\n* Alive @ Five is an annual summer concert located in Columbus park typically lasting six weeks.\n* Treetops CMS, a non-profit chamber music organization, is located in Westover, providing six chamber music concerts annually, as well as art exhibits and installations.\n\n[[File:St. Mary's Church II.jpg|thumb|Gothic revival exterior of St. Mary's Church on Elm Street]]\n\n===Fine art===\n* UCONN Stamford Art Gallery showcases both emerging and established artists.\n* [[Franklin Street Works]] maintains an art space in the downtown area.\n* Fernando Luis Alvarez Gallery is a contemporary art gallery in Connecticut with diverse international exhibitions.\n* Stamford Loft Artists Association provides support for visual artists and opportunities to exhibit their work.\n\n==Media==\n* [[NBC Sports Group]] world headquarters is located in Stamford, connected to [[Chelsea Piers|Chelsea Piers Connecticut]]. All studios are based in Stamford, including [[Football Night in America]], and all the [[NBC Olympic broadcasts|NBC Olympic coverage]].\n* Three [[NBCUniversal]] syndicated programs relocated to Stamford's [[Stamford Center for the Arts|Rich Forum]]: ''[[Maury (TV series)|Maury]]'' came to Stamford from New York City, while ''[[The Jerry Springer Show]]'' and ''[[The Steve Wilkos Show]]'' were previously based in Chicago.\n* Television show ''[[The People's Court]]'' has taped in Stamford since 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stamfordadvocate.com/printpromotion/article/Doug-Llewelyn-loves-filming-People-s-8338173.php|title=Doug Llewelyn 'loves' filming 'People's Court' in Stamford|last=Nickerson|first=John|date=2016-07-03|website=StamfordAdvocate|access-date=2019-03-19}}</ref>\n* [[ITV Studios|ITV America]] announced the opening of a major production office in Stamford with 450 employees, along with a digital media incubator program. Televisions shows produced in Stamford include [[Hell's Kitchen (U.S. TV series)|Hell's Kitchen]], [[Pawn Stars]], [[The Real Housewives of New Jersey]], [[Queer Eye (2018 TV series)|Queer Eye]] on [[Netflix]], and [[The Four: Battle for Stardom]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stamfordadvocate.com/business/article/ITV-and-startup-announce-Stamford-hub-plan-12943555.php|title=ITV and startup announce Stamford hub, plan hundreds of jobs|last=Schott|first=Paul|date=2018-05-25|website=StamfordAdvocate|access-date=2019-03-19}}</ref>\n* [[WWE]] has had its global headquarters in Stamford since 1985, back when it was Titan Sports.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1091907/000095013099005812/0000950130-99-005812.txt|title=WWE SEC Filing}}</ref>\n* [[Fortune 500|Fortune 100]] company, [[Charter Communications|Charter Communications']] world headquarters has been based in Stamford since 2012. Charter distributes services through their [[Spectrum (cable service)|Spectrum]] brand.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/stlouis/news/2012/10/02/charter-communications-to-add-200-jobs.html|website=www.bizjournals.com|title=Charter to invest $10 million in new Conn. headquarters |access-date=2019-03-19}}</ref>\n* Stamford serves as a major office for [[Yes Network|YES Network]], The [[New York Yankees|Yankee]] Entertainment and Sports Network.<ref name=\"ctp\">{{cite news|url=http://www.ctpost.com/news/article/Disney-moves-filming-of-Millionaire-to-Stamford-5597151.php|title=Disney moves filming of 'Millionaire' to Stamford|last1=Just|first1=Olivia|date=July 3, 2014|work=CT Post|accessdate=May 22, 2015|publisher=[[Hearst Corporation|Hearst Media Services Connecticut, LLC]]}}</ref>\n* [[A&E Networks|A+E Networks]] has a major production studio based in Stamford.\n* [[Soap opera]]s ''[[All My Children]]'' and ''[[One Life to Live]]'' were taped in Stamford in 2013.\n* [[This Old House]] relocated its headquarters to Stamford from Manhattan in 2016, and has about fifty employees in the city.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stamfordadvocate.com/business/article/This-Old-House-makes-new-moves-with-digital-real-10946027.php|title=This Old House makes new moves with digital real estate|last=Schott|first=Paul|date=2017-02-20|website=StamfordAdvocate|access-date=2019-03-19}}</ref>\n* Stephen David Entertainment, a division of [[Banijay Group]], opened a production office in Stamford in 2019.\n* ''[[Who Wants to Be a Millionaire (U.S. game show)|Who Wants to Be a Millionaire]]'' started taping in 2014 at the Connecticut Film Center.<ref name=\"ctp\" />\n* [[Synapse Group]], part of [[Time Inc.]] now owned by [[Meredith Corporation]], is headquartered in Stamford.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.synapsegroupinc.com/contact/|title=Contact\u2013Synapse Group Inc.|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-19}}</ref>\n* Chief Executive Group is headquartered in Stamford, and publishes [[Chief Executive (magazine)|Chief Executive Magazine]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://chiefexecutive.net/about-us/|title=About Chief Executive Group|website=ChiefExecutive.net|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-19}}</ref>\n* The fictional movie, ''Take My Hand'', from the episode, \"[[I Heart Connecticut]]\" of the NBC show ''[[30 Rock]]'' was set and shot in Stamford.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ew.com/article/2011/04/15/30-rock-recap-i-heart-connecticu/|title='30 Rock': The great state of Connecticut|website=EW.com|language=en|access-date=2019-03-19}}</ref>\n* Stamford, Connecticut served as a location for one of five branches of the fictional [[Dunder Mifflin]] paper company from the US television series, ''[[The Office (U.S. TV series)|The Office]]''. The branch was shown during several episodes during the 3rd season of the show, and exterior shots were of the [[Starwood|Starwood Hotels]] headquarter building located at 333 Ludlow in [[South End of Stamford|Stamford's South End]].\n* The [[TBS (U.S. TV channel)|TBS]] sitcom ''[[Are We There Yet? (TV series)|Are We There Yet]],'' starring [[Terry Crews]], was shot at the Connecticut Film Center located in Stamford.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stamfordadvocate.com/news/article/New-TBS-sitcom-filming-in-Stamford-800326.php|title=New TBS sitcom filming in Stamford|last=King|first=Kate|last2=Writer|first2=Staff|date=2010-11-06|website=StamfordAdvocate|access-date=2019-03-19}}</ref>\n\n===Print media===\n* ''Stamford Magazine'', published by Moffly Media\n* [[The Advocate (Stamford)|''Stamford Advocate'']], daily newspaper\n* ''The Stamford Times'', weekly newspaper, owned by The Hour Newspapers.\n*''Stamford Plus'' magazine is published by Canaiden LLC.\n* ''El Sol News'', weekly Spanish-language newspaper.\n* ''La Voz'', weekly Spanish-language newspaper.\n\n===Radio stations in the city===\n* [[WEDW-FM]] 88.5; 2,000 watts, a National Public Radio station\n* [[WSTC]]-AM 1400; 1,000 watts; shares programming with WNLK-AM 1350\n* [[WEBE 108 FM]]-107.9 1400; 50,000 WATS\n\n==Notable people==\n{{Main|List of people from Stamford, Connecticut}}Noteworthy past and present residents include:\n* [[Alex Rodriguez]] (born 1975), [[MLB]] player, is said to have a home in Stamford\n* [[Bobby Valentine]] (born 1950), former baseball player and former manager of the [[Boston Red Sox]], owner of downtown sports bar \"Bobby V's\".\n* [[Christopher Lloyd]] (born 1938), actor, born in Stamford\n* [[Cyndi Lauper]] (born 1953), singer, has a home in North Stamford\n* [[Dana Delany]] (born 1956), actress, grew up in Stamford\n* [[Dan Malloy]] (born 1955), former [[Governor of Connecticut]]\n* [[Don Morrow]] (born 1927), actor, announcer, voiceover artist\n* [[Gene Wilder]] (1933\u20132016), actor and director, lived and died in the city\n* [[Harry Houdini]] (1874\u20131926), escape artist, had a summer home in Stamford\n* [[Jackie Robinson]] (1919\u20131972), baseball star, made North Stamford his home later in his life; one of the Stamford little leagues is named after him\n* [[Meat Loaf]] (Michael Lee Aday) (born 1947), rock singer and songwriter, lived in Stamford 1979\u20131981, coached Babe Ruth League and Little League baseball\n* [[Mort Walker]] (1923\u20132018), cartoonist for ''[[Beetle Bailey]]'' and ''[[Hi and Lois]]''\n* [[Stephen Sondheim]] (born 1930), composer, lived in North Stamford when he was a boy\n* [[Vince McMahon]] (born 1945) and [[Linda McMahon]] (born 1948), founders of [[World Wrestling Entertainment]]\n* [[Vivian Vance]] (1909\u20131979), actress who starred as [[Ethel Mertz]] in ''[[I Love Lucy]]''\n\n==Sister cities==\n* {{flagdeco|ISR}} [[Afula]], Israel<ref>{{cite web|url=http://congregationagudathsholom.org/kolsholom/ASNovDec06.pdf|title=Jewish congregation working with sister city in Israel|website=Congregationagudathsholom.org|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110813223919/http://congregationagudathsholom.org/kolsholom/ASNovDec06.pdf|archivedate=August 13, 2011}}</ref>\n* {{flagdeco|PRC}} [[Jiangdu]], [[Jiangsu]], China<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.stamfordchamber.com/itc_history.htm|title=International Trade Council ... Overview|website=Stamfordchamber.com|access-date=May 8, 2016}}</ref>\n* {{flagdeco|PER}} [[Lima|Lima, Peru]]\n* {{flagdeco|ITA}} [[Minturno]], [[Lazio]], Italy\n* {{flagdeco|ITA}} [[Settefrati]], Lazio, Italy<ref name=sister>{{cite web|url=http://www.sister-cities.org/icrc/directory/USA/CT |website=Sister Cities|title=Online Directory: Connecticut, USA |accessdate=March 21, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061002205742/http://www.sister-cities.org/icrc/directory/USA/CT |archivedate=October 2, 2006 }}</ref>\n* {{flagdeco|GRC}} [[Sparti (municipality)|Sparti]], Greece<ref name=sister/>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Connecticut}}\n* [[History of Stamford, Connecticut]]\n* [[National Register of Historic Places listings in Stamford, Connecticut]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{cite book |last=Huntington |first=E.B. |title=History of Stamford, Connecticut: from its settlement in 1641, to the present |url=https://archive.org/details/historyofstamfor00hunt |location=Stamford, CT |publisher=The Author |date=1868 |oclc=11665950}}\n* {{cite book |last=Burns |first=Rosemary |title=Springdale remembered: the history of a section of Stamford, Connecticut, 1640\u20131949 |location=Stamford, CT |publisher=Stamford Historical Society |date=1982 |oclc=9093878}}\n* {{cite journal|last=Mecca |first=Gregg D. |date=1984 |title=Made in Stamford: A History of Stamford as a Manufacturing Center |url=http://www.cslib.org/stamford/indhist.htm |location=Stamford, CT |publisher=Stamford Historical Society |accessdate=July 8, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051025111332/http://www.cslib.org/stamford/indhist.htm |archivedate=October 25, 2005 }}\n* {{cite book |last1=Majdalany |first1=Jeanne |last2=Wicks |first2=Edith |title=The story of the early settlers of Stamford, Connecticut, 1641\u20131700 |location=Bowie, MD |publisher=Heritage Books |date=1992 |isbn= 9781556136108}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{wikivoyage|Stamford (Connecticut)|Stamford, Connecticut}}\n* {{official website|http://www.cityofstamford.org/ }}\n* [http://www.stamfordhistory.org/ Stamford Historical Society]\n* [http://www.stamford-downtown.com/ Stamford Downtown Special Services District]\n* {{Cite NSRW|wstitle=Stamford, Conn.|short=x}}\n\n{{Connecticut}}\n{{Stamford Neighborhoods}}\n{{Fairfield County, Connecticut}}\n{{New England}}\n{{New York metropolitan area}}\n{{Connecticut cities and mayors of 100,000 population}}\n{{Northeast Megalopolis}}\n{{Northeast US}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Stamford, Connecticut| ]]\n[[Category:Cities in Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Cities in the New York metropolitan area]]\n[[Category:Cities in Fairfield County, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Populated coastal places in Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Year of establishment missing]]\n", "name_user": "24.186.98.83", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(You cannot be serious when you think people would have difficulty pronouncing Stamford.)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stamford,_Connecticut"}
{"title_page": "Real Time Crime Center", "text_new": "{{news release|1=article|date=October 2015}}\n[[Image:Realtimecrimecenterofficial.png|thumb|Real Time Crime Center emblem]]\n\nThe '''Real Time Crime Center''' ('''RTCC''') is a centralized technology center for the [[New York Police Department]] (NYPD). Its purpose is to give field officers and detectives instant information to help identify patterns and stop emerging crime. \n\nThe NYPD RTCC opened on July 18, 2005 and provides support 24/7. The center was built at a cost of $11 million. The information in the center is available to the 37,000 police officers of the [[New York City Police Department]].  The RTCC was funded in part by grants from the non-profit [[New York City Police Foundation]].<ref>\n*[http://www.ny1.com/ny1/content/index.jsp?&aid=52142 NYPD Unveils High-Tech Real Time Crime Center At Police Headquarters]\n*[http://www.gcn.com/print/24_29/37061-1.html Real-time crime fighting comes to Gotham]\n</ref>\n\nRTCC data sources include a data warehouse in which billions of records are made available to detectives and other officers within minutes, instead of days or weeks. These include:<ref>\n*[http://policechiefmagazine.org/magazine/index.cfm?fuseaction=display&article_id=995&issue_id=92006 Stopping Crime in Real Time]\n*[http://www.informationweek.com/showArticle.jhtml?articleID=166401859  New York's Techno Crime Fighters]\n*[https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,1895,1863497,00.asp Fighting Crime in Real Time]\n</ref>\n*More than 5 million New York State criminal records, parole and probation files,\n*More than 20 million New York City criminal complaints, arrests, 911/311 calls and summonses spanning five years,\n*More than 31 million national crime records,\n*More than 33 billion public records.\n\nThe Crime Center employs satellite imaging and mapping of New York City (using [[Geographic Information System]] software) precinct-by-precinct. The link analysis capacity of the RTCC can track suspects to their known addresses and point detectives to the locations where they are most likely to flee. The Real Time Crime Center was built with the oversight of integrated solution{{solution-inline|date=July 2019}} provider [[Dimension Data]].\n\nOther police departments have Real Time Crime Centers, including the [[Miami-Dade Police Department]], [[Seattle Police Department]], [[Fort Worth Police Department]], [[Metropolitan Police Department, City of St. Louis]], [[Albuquerque Police Department]], [[Austin Police Department]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.kxan.com/news/crime/how-police-monitors-situations-in-downtown-austin-in-realtime_20180316013018707/1049643246|title=How police monitors situations in downtown Austin in realtime|last=Rangel|first=Leslie|date=2016-08-02|work=KXAN|access-date=2018-10-10|language=en-US}}</ref>, [[Tampa Police Department]], [[Minneapolis Police Department]] and [[Houston Police Department|Houston]] Police Departments.<ref>[http://abclocal.go.com/ktrk/story?section=news/in_focus&id=7642890 HPD's High-tech center helping solve crimes]</ref>\n<br />\n<br />\n'''Emerging Cloud-Based Technology and Innovation'''\n\nReal Time Crime Center (RTCC) in the Cloud are centralized ([[SaaS]]) platforms which extracts and unifies live video and data feeds from virtually any source, creating a central hub that enhances the situational awareness and investigative capabilities of law enforcement and public safety agencies. \n\nOn April 1, 2020, the Minneapolis Police Department's Strategic Information Center (SIC) announced a partnership with, [https://www.fusus.com/ F\u016bsus], to activate a ground-breaking law enforcement platform, [https://www.fusus.com/products/fususone f\u016bsusONE], which will be live and fully operational on April 16th, 2020. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fusus.com/blog/press-release-minneapolis-police-department-to-activate-fusus-real-time-crime-center-platform|title=MPD to activiate Fusus Real Time Crime Center Platform|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n<br />\n<br />\n''\"We\u2019ve worked closely with the Fusus team to help create a real-time crime center solution that truly meets the day-to-day intelligence needs of our department,\u201d said Commander Scott Gerlicher of the MPD\u2019s Special Operation and Intelligence Division. \u201c[https://www.fusus.com/blog/press-release-minneapolis-police-department-to-activate-fusus-real-time-crime-center-platform The activation of the Fusus platform] represents a significant step forward not just for the MPD's crime mitigation and public safety efforts, but for law enforcement technology in general. With the Fusus platform in place, the MPD will be one of the first Police Departments in the nation to be leveraging a real-time crime center in the cloud solution.\u201d''\n<br />\n<br />\n'''The F\u016bsus Unified Awareness Platform will bring the following capabilities to the MPD\u2019s SIC:''' \n\n*Computer Aided Dispatch (CAD) Integration -along with video correlation to Priority 1 locations\n*Integration to Minneapolis 911 dispatch\n*Live video from the Minneapolis Downtown Improvement District area\n*Community Camera Registry Location Data\n*Live Cell Phone Video during an ongoing incident\n*Live Video from Stadiums and other Community Owned Video Sources\n*ShotSpotter Gunfire Detection Integration\n*Mutual Aid with other law enforcement agencies\n*Community shared video and photo for Tips via SMS-Text\n*f\u016bsusALERT Panic App integration for(policy-based) video sharing on alert\n*[https://www.fusus.com/products/fusuops f\u016bsusOPS] Officer Locations, Text Communications,and Team Coordination for Incident Management\n*\u00a0Floor plan Integrations to Locations of Interest\n\n<br />\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.nycpolicefoundation.org/ New York City Police Foundation official site]\n*[https://www.fusus.com/products/fususone F\u016bsus - Real Time Crime Center in the Cloud]\n{{New York City Police Department}}\n[[Category:New York City Police Department]]\n{{police-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{news release|1=article|date=October 2015}}\n[[Image:Realtimecrimecenterofficial.png|thumb|Real Time Crime Center emblem]]\n\nThe '''Real Time Crime Center''' ('''RTCC''') is a centralized technology center for the [[New York Police Department]] (NYPD). Its purpose is to give field officers and detectives instant information to help identify patterns and stop emerging crime. \n\nThe NYPD RTCC opened on July 18, 2005 and provides support 24/7. The center was built at a cost of $11 million. The information in the center is available to the 37,000 police officers of the [[New York City Police Department]].  The RTCC was funded in part by grants from the non-profit [[New York City Police Foundation]].<ref>\n*[http://www.ny1.com/ny1/content/index.jsp?&aid=52142 NYPD Unveils High-Tech Real Time Crime Center At Police Headquarters]\n*[http://www.gcn.com/print/24_29/37061-1.html Real-time crime fighting comes to Gotham]\n</ref>\n\nRTCC data sources include a data warehouse in which billions of records are made available to detectives and other officers within minutes, instead of days or weeks. These include:<ref>\n*[http://policechiefmagazine.org/magazine/index.cfm?fuseaction=display&article_id=995&issue_id=92006 Stopping Crime in Real Time]\n*[http://www.informationweek.com/showArticle.jhtml?articleID=166401859  New York's Techno Crime Fighters]\n*[https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,1895,1863497,00.asp Fighting Crime in Real Time]\n</ref>\n*More than 5 million New York State criminal records, parole and probation files,\n*More than 20 million New York City criminal complaints, arrests, 911/311 calls and summonses spanning five years,\n*More than 31 million national crime records,\n*More than 33 billion public records.\n\nThe Crime Center employs satellite imaging and mapping of New York City (using [[Geographic Information System]] software) precinct-by-precinct. The link analysis capacity of the RTCC can track suspects to their known addresses and point detectives to the locations where they are most likely to flee. The Real Time Crime Center was built with the oversight of integrated solution{{solution-inline|date=July 2019}} provider [[Dimension Data]].\n\nOther police departments have Real Time Crime Centers, including the [[Miami-Dade Police Department]], [[Seattle Police Department]], [[Fort Worth Police Department]], [[Metropolitan Police Department, City of St. Louis]], [[Albuquerque Police Department]], [[Austin Police Department]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.kxan.com/news/crime/how-police-monitors-situations-in-downtown-austin-in-realtime_20180316013018707/1049643246|title=How police monitors situations in downtown Austin in realtime|last=Rangel|first=Leslie|date=2016-08-02|work=KXAN|access-date=2018-10-10|language=en-US}}</ref>, [[Tampa Police Department]], [[Minneapolis Police Department]] and [[Houston Police Department|Houston]] Police Departments.<ref>[http://abclocal.go.com/ktrk/story?section=news/in_focus&id=7642890 HPD's High-tech center helping solve crimes]</ref>\n<br />\n<br />\n'''Emerging Cloud-Based Technology and Innovation'''\n\nReal Time Crime Center (RTCC) in the Cloud are centralized ([[SaaS]]) platforms which extracts and unifies live video and data feeds from virtually any source, creating a central hub that enhances the situational awareness and investigative capabilities of law enforcement and public safety agencies. \n\nOn April 1, 2020, the Minneapolis Police Department's Strategic Information Center (SIC) announced a partnership with, [https://www.fusus.com/ F\u016bsus], to activate a ground-breaking law enforcement platform, [https://www.fusus.com/products/fususone f\u016bsusONE], on April 16th, 2020. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fusus.com/blog/press-release-minneapolis-police-department-to-activate-fusus-real-time-crime-center-platform|title=MPD to activiate Fusus Real Time Crime Center Platform|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n<br />\n<br />\n''\"We\u2019ve worked closely with the Fusus team to help create a real-time crime center solution that truly meets the day-to-day intelligence needs of our department,\u201d said Commander Scott Gerlicher of the MPD\u2019s Special Operation and Intelligence Division. \u201c[https://www.fusus.com/blog/press-release-minneapolis-police-department-to-activate-fusus-real-time-crime-center-platform The activation of the Fusus platform] represents a significant step forward not just for the MPD's crime mitigation and public safety efforts, but for law enforcement technology in general. With the Fusus platform in place, the MPD will be one of the first Police Departments in the nation to be leveraging a real-time crime center in the cloud solution.\u201d''\n<br />\n<br />\n'''The F\u016bsus Unified Awareness Platform will bring the following capabilities to the MPD\u2019s SIC:''' \n\n*Computer Aided Dispatch (CAD) Integration -along with video correlation to Priority 1 locations\n*Integration to Minneapolis 911 dispatch\n*Live video from the Minneapolis Downtown Improvement District area\n*Community Camera Registry Location Data\n*Live Cell Phone Video during an ongoing incident\n*Live Video from Stadiums and other Community Owned Video Sources\n*ShotSpotter Gunfire Detection Integration\n*Mutual Aid with other law enforcement agencies\n*Community shared video and photo for Tips via SMS-Text\n*f\u016bsusALERT Panic App integration for(policy-based) video sharing on alert\n*[https://www.fusus.com/products/fusuops f\u016bsusOPS] Officer Locations, Text Communications,and Team Coordination for Incident Management\n*\u00a0Floor plan Integrations to Locations of Interest\n\n<br />\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.nycpolicefoundation.org/ New York City Police Foundation official site]\n*[https://www.fusus.com/products/fususone F\u016bsus - Real Time Crime Center in the Cloud]\n{{New York City Police Department}}\n[[Category:New York City Police Department]]\n{{police-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Appleseed1492", "label": "safe", "comment": "grammar change", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Real_Time_Crime_Center"}
{"title_page": "Frederic Monneyron", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=June 2015}}\n{{cleanup reorganize|date=June 2015}}\n{{underlinked|date=June 2015}}\n{{Orphan|date=June 2015}}\n}}\n<!--- Don't mess with this line! ---><!--- Write your article below this line --->\n\n'''Frederic Monneyron''' is a French writer and [[academic]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Auteur : Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Monneyron|url=http://www.puf.com/Auteur:Fr%C3%A9d%C3%A9ric_Monneyron|website=www.puf.com|accessdate=2015-06-13}}</ref>*\n[[File:Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Monneyron.png|thumb|Schermata 2013-01-16 a 19.06.33]]\n\nOf Swiss descent, Frederic Monneyron was born in Paris. He spent his youth in the United Kingdom and Sweden, later living in Africa, [[Morocco]] and the United States.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150525161641/http://www.micheldemaule.com/Titres-Disponibles-aux-Editions-Michel-de-Maule/Dossier-diplomatique/369.htm|title=Michel de Maule - Dossier diplomatique|date=2015-05-25|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref> Monneyron is currently living in [[Montpellier, France]].\n\nMonneyron received his Doctorat d'Etat en science politique from the [[University of Montpellier I]] in 1984 and his Doctorat d'Etat \u00e8s lettres et sciences humaines from the [[University of Paris IV-Sorbonne]] in 1986. He taught at the [[University of California]], the [[Universit\u00e9 F\u00e9lix Houphou\u00ebt-Boigny|University of Abidjan]], and the [[Cadi Ayyad University]] between 1980 and 1988.  Monneyron taught at the [[University of Burgundy]], the [[University of South Florida]] and [[Stendhal University]] between 1988 and 1998.<ref>{{cite web|last1=ITHP Monneyr|title=Notice bio Monneyron|url=http://www.ihtp.cnrs.fr/sites/ihtp/IMG/pdf/Notice_bio_Monneyron-1.pdf}}</ref>\n\nMonneyron is a full Professor in comparative and general literature at the [[University of Perpignan Via Domitia]] and is the head of the MBA \"Fashion industries and luxury goods\" at Mod'Art International, Paris, coming to teach [[sociology]] of fashion in the English-taught programme. He also teaches sociology of fashion at the [[University of Geneva]] and at the [[University of Barcelona]] and is a Distinguished visiting professor at the University of South Florida, the [[University of Milan]] and the University of Bologna. Besides, he is an expert to the European Commission in Brussels (research directorate).\n\nHis works focused on sexuality, gender relations (Th\u00e8se d'Etat es lettres et sciences humaines : ''L'Imaginaire androgyne'' ; ''L'Ecriture de la jalousie'' ; ''S\u00e9duire''), clothes, fashion and luxury (''La Frivolit\u00e9 essentielle'' ; ''La Mode et ses enjeux'', ''La Sociologie de la mode'', ''La Photographie de mode'', ''Le Luxe'', ''L'Imaginaire du luxe'') on the one hand ; on the ideas of nation and race (''La Nation aujourd'hui'', ''L'Imaginaire racial'', ''L'Id\u00e9e de race''), on Europe (Th\u00e8se d'Etat de science politique: ''Les Neutres et l'int\u00e9gration europ\u00e9enne'') and the USA (''Au C\u0153ur des Etats-Unis'') on the other hand.\n\nHe is the author of more than twenty books translated in major languages and is the editor of around fifteen collective works among which five conferences he organized at the Cerisy International Center (''L'Androgyne, La Jalousie, La Misogynie, Le Masculin, Le V\u00eatement'')\n.<ref>{{cite web|title=Actes du colloque de Cerisy Le vetement|url=http://www.ccic-cerisy.asso.fr/vetementTM01.html|website=www.ccic-cerisy.asso.fr}}</ref>\n\nHe is also a novelist (''Dossier diplomatique'',<ref>{{cite web|title=Michel de Maule|url=http://www.micheldemaule.com/Titres-Disponibles-aux-Editions-Michel-de-Maule/Dossier-diplomatique/369.htm|access-date=2015-06-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150525161641/http://www.micheldemaule.com/Titres-Disponibles-aux-Editions-Michel-de-Maule/Dossier-diplomatique/369.htm|archive-date=2015-05-25|url-status=dead}}</ref> ''Le Voyage d'un s\u00e9ducteur'', ''Le Nihiliste'') and a short stories writer (''Sans Nom et autres nouvelles'') and a translator from English into French (A. K. Coomaraswamy, E. Wharton, P. G. Wodehouse, T.D. Allman)\n\nOn topics such as fashion, luxury, sexuality and seduction, he granted numerous interviews to the magazines and the radio<ref>{{cite web|title=La photographie de mode : un art souverain, de Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Monneyron - France Culture|url=http://www.franceculture.fr/oeuvre-la-photographie-de-mode-un-art-souverain-de-frederic-monneyron|website=www.franceculture.fr|accessdate=2015-06-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Jaloux, moi ? / France Inter|url=http://www.franceinter.fr/emission-tous-les-chats-sont-gris-jaloux-moi|accessdate=2015-06-13}}</ref> and appeared on television programmes.\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n===Essays===\n\n*''L'Androgyne romantique. Du mythe au mythe litt\u00e9raire'' (Grenoble, ELLUG, 1994, {{ISBN|2 902709 88 9}}; 2009)\n*''L'Androgyne d\u00e9cadent. Mythe, figure, fantasmes'' (Grenoble, ELLUG, 1996, {{ISBN|2 902709 94 3}}; 2011)\n*''L'\u00c9criture de la jalousie'' (Grenoble, ELLUG, 1996, {{ISBN|2 84310 003 8}})\n*''Bisexualit\u00e9 et litt\u00e9rature. Autour de D. H. Lawrence et Virginia Woolf'', (Paris, L'Harmattan, 1998, {{ISBN|2-7384-6363-0}})\n*''S\u00e9duire, l'imaginaire de la s\u00e9duction de Don Giovanni \u00e0 Mick Jagger'' (Paris, PUF, 1997, {{ISBN|2 13 0481108}}; 2000; Paris, Imago, 2016, {{ISBN|978-2-84952-865-5}})\n*''La Nation aujourd'hui. Formes et mythes'' (Paris, L'Harmattan, 2000, {{ISBN|2-7384-9850-7}})\n*''La Frivolit\u00e9 essentielle. Du v\u00eatement et de la mode'' (Paris, PUF, 2001, {{ISBN|2 13 051653 X}}; paperback Quadrige, 2008, 2014)\n*''Mythes et litt\u00e9rature'' (Paris, PUF, 2002, {{ISBN|2 13 053036 2}}; 2012, with Jo\u00ebl Thomas, translated in Spanish)\n*''L'imaginaire racial'' (Paris, L'Harmattan, 2004, {{ISBN|2-7475-6846-6}})\n*''La Mode et ses enjeux'' (Paris, Klincksieck, 2005, {{ISBN|2-252-03533-1}}; 2010, translated in Spanish and Portuguese)\n*''L'Automobile. Un imaginaire contemporain'' (Paris, Imago, 2006, {{ISBN|2-84952-030-6}}; with Jo\u00ebl Thomas)\n*''La Sociologie de la mode'' (Paris, PUF, 2006, {{ISBN|2 13 055517 9}}; 2010, 2013, 2015, translated in Japanese and Italian)\n*''Sociologie de l'imaginaire'', with Patrick Legros, Patrick Tacussel et Jean-Bruno Renard (Paris, Armand Colin, coll. Cursus, 2006, {{ISBN|2-200-26663-4}}, translated in Portuguese)\n*''Le Monde hippie. De l'imaginaire psych\u00e9d\u00e9lique \u00e0 la r\u00e9volution informatique'' (Paris, Imago, 2008 {{ISBN|978-2-84952-061-1}}, with Martine Xiberras)\n*''La Photographie de mode. Un art souverain'' (Paris, PUF, coll. Perspectives critiques, 2010, {{ISBN|978-2-13-057874-1}})\n*''Au c\u0153ur des \u00c9tats-Unis. Mythes, imaginaires et fictions'' (Paris, Michel Houdiard \u00c9diteur, 2011,{{ISBN|978-2-35692-064-5}})\n*''L'Id\u00e9e de race. Histoire d'une fiction'' (Paris, Berg International, 2012, {{ISBN|978-2-917191-48-4}}, with G\u00e9rard Siary)\n*''Vanity. Mode/Fotografie aus der Sammlung F.C. Gunlach'' (Wien, Kunsthalle f\u00fcr Moderne Kunst, Stiftung F.C. Gundlach, 2012, {{ISBN|3869842709}}, mit Synne Genzmer)\n*''La S\u00e9duction,'' (UPPR, 2015, {{ISBN|978-2-37168-023-4}}; 2016)\n*''La Mode'', (UPPR, 2015, {{ISBN|978-2-37168-022-7}}; 2016)\n*''Le Luxe'', (UPPR, 2015, {{ISBN|978-2-37168-033-3}}; 2017)\n*''L'Imaginaire du luxe'' (Paris, Imago, 2015, with Patrick Mathieu, {{ISBN|2849528528}})\n*''Luxe'' (Paris, Michel de Maule, 2017, with Patrick Mathieu, {{ISBN|2876235277}})\n*''Mythe et nation'' (UPPR, 2017, {{ISBN|978-2-37168-236-8}})\n*''Des sexes et des genres'' (UPPR, 2019, {{ISBN|978-2-37168-264-1}})\n\n===Editor===\n\n*''L'Androgyne dans la litt\u00e9rature'' (Paris, Albin-Michel, 1990, {{ISBN|2-226-04018-8}}; Dervy-Livre, 2000, translated in Japanese)\n*''Misogynies'' (Paris, Deux Temps/Tierce, 1993, {{ISBN|2-903144-87-7}})\n*''La Jalousie'' (Paris, L'Harmattan, 1996, {{ISBN|2-7384-4293-5}})\n*''Le Masculin, Identit\u00e9, fictions, diss\u00e9mination'' (Paris, L'Harmattan, 1998, {{ISBN|2-7384-7017-3}})\n*''Le V\u00eatement'' (Paris, L'Harmattan, 2001, {{ISBN|2-7475-1740-3}})\n*''V\u00eatement et litt\u00e9rature'' (PUP, 2001, {{ISBN|2-908912-89-9}})\n*''L'Entre-deux de la mode'' (Paris, L'Harmattan/Bergamo University Press, 2004, {{ISBN|2-7475-6789-3}})\n*''Automobile et litt\u00e9rature'' (PUP, 2005, {{ISBN|2-914518-65-X}})\n*''La France dans le regard des \u00c9tats-Unis/France as Seen by the United States'' (PUP/PUPV, 2007, {{ISBN|2-914518-92-7}})\n*''M\u00e9taphysique de la mode'' (Paris/Bruxelles, \u00c9ditions du Cercle d'art, 2008, {{ISBN|9782702208663}})\n*''Des mythes politiques'' (Paris, Imago, 2010, {{ISBN|978-2-84952-087-1}}, translated in Croatian)\n*''Sport et imaginaire'' (PULM, 2013, {{ISBN|978-2-36781-032-4}})\n\n===Prefaces===\n\n*Hela Ouardi (dir), ''L'Androgyne en litt\u00e9rature'' (Simpact, 2009, {{ISBN|978-2-915611-38-0}})\n*Michel Dion et Mariette Julien, ''\u00c9thique de la mode f\u00e9minine'' (PUF, 2010, {{ISBN|978-2-13-057815-4}})\n\n===Fiction===\n\n*''Sans nom et autres nouvelles'' (Paris, L'Harmattan, 1999, {{ISBN|2-7384-7291-5}})\n*''Dossier diplomatique'' (Paris, Michel de Maule, 2014, {{ISBN|978-2-87623-557-1}})\n*''Le Voyage d'un s\u00e9ducteur'' (CSIPP, 2018, {{ISBN|9781719433273}})\n*''Le Nihiliste'' (Paris, Sydney Laurent, 2019, ({{ISBN|979-10-326-1549-2}}))\n* ''Apr\u00e8s le d\u00e9sir'' (KDP, 2019 ({{ISBN|9781089064442}}))\n\n===Translations (from English into French)===\n\n*A. K. Coomaraswamy, ''La philosophie chr\u00e9tienne et orientale de l'art'' (Pard\u00e8s, 1990, {{ISBN|2-86714-076-5}})\n*Edith Wharton, ''Voyage au Maroc'' (Paris/Monaco, Ed. du Rocher, 1996, {{ISBN|2-268-02220-X}}; r\u00e9\u00e9d. Paris, Gallimard-L'Etrang\u00e8re, 1998, puis Paris, Gallimard-L'imaginaire, 2001)\n*P.G. Wodehouse, ''Courtes histoires de green'' (Paris, Michel de Maule, 2011, {{ISBN|978-2-87623-281-5}})\n*T.D. Allman, ''La Floride, coeur r\u00e9v\u00e9lateur des Etats-Unis'' (Paris, Classiques Garnier, 2019, {{ISBN|978-2-406-08078-7}})\n\n===Quotation===\n\u00ab Quand on change de v\u00eatement, on change de comportement \u00bb. Excerpt from ''Lib\u00e9ration'' - September 1, 2001.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}<br /><!--- STOP! Be warned that by using this process instead of Articles for Creation, this article is subject to scrutiny. As an article in \"mainspace\", it will be DELETED if there are problems, not just declined. If you wish to use AfC, please return to the Wizard and continue from there. --->\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Monneyron, Frederic}}\n[[Category:French male short story writers]]\n[[Category:French short story writers]]\n[[Category:French essayists]]\n[[Category:French male essayists]]\n[[Category:Writers from Paris]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=June 2015}}\n{{cleanup reorganize|date=June 2015}}\n{{underlinked|date=June 2015}}\n{{Orphan|date=June 2015}}\n}}\n<!--- Don't mess with this line! ---><!--- Write your article below this line --->\n\n'''Frederic Monneyron''' is a French writer and [[academic]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Auteur : Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Monneyron|url=http://www.puf.com/Auteur:Fr%C3%A9d%C3%A9ric_Monneyron|website=www.puf.com|accessdate=2015-06-13}}</ref>*\n[[File:Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Monneyron.png|thumb|Schermata 2013-01-16 a 19.06.33]]\n\nOf Swiss descent, Frederic Monneyron was born in Paris. He spent his youth in the United Kingdom and Sweden, later living in Africa, [[Morocco]] and the United States.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150525161641/http://www.micheldemaule.com/Titres-Disponibles-aux-Editions-Michel-de-Maule/Dossier-diplomatique/369.htm|title=Michel de Maule - Dossier diplomatique|date=2015-05-25|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref> Monneyron is currently living in [[Montpellier, France]].\n\nMonneyron received his Doctorat d'Etat en science politique from the [[University of Montpellier I]] in 1984 and his Doctorat d'Etat \u00e8s lettres et sciences humaines from the [[University of Paris IV-Sorbonne]] in 1986. He taught at the [[University of California]], the [[Universit\u00e9 F\u00e9lix Houphou\u00ebt-Boigny|University of Abidjan]], and the [[Cadi Ayyad University]] between 1980 and 1988.  Monneyron taught at the [[University of Burgundy]], the [[University of South Florida]] and [[Stendhal University]] between 1988 and 1998.<ref>{{cite web|last1=ITHP Monneyr|title=Notice bio Monneyron|url=http://www.ihtp.cnrs.fr/sites/ihtp/IMG/pdf/Notice_bio_Monneyron-1.pdf}}</ref>\n\nMonneyron is a full Professor in comparative and general literature at the [[University of Perpignan Via Domitia]] and is the head of the MBA \"Fashion industries and luxury goods\" at Mod'Art International, Paris, coming to teach [[sociology]] of fashion in the English-taught programme. He also teaches sociology of fashion at the [[University of Geneva]] and at the [[University of Barcelona]] and is a Distinguished visiting professor at the University of South Florida, the [[University of Milan]] and the University of Bologna. Besides, he is an expert to the European Commission in Brussels (research directorate).\n\nHis works focused on sexuality, gender relations (Th\u00e8se d'Etat es lettres et sciences humaines : ''L'Imaginaire androgyne'' ; ''L'Ecriture de la jalousie'' ; ''S\u00e9duire''), clothes, fashion and luxury (''La Frivolit\u00e9 essentielle'' ; ''La Mode et ses enjeux'', ''La Sociologie de la mode'', ''La Photographie de mode'', ''Le Luxe'', ''L'Imaginaire du luxe'') on the one hand ; on the ideas of nation and race (''La Nation aujourd'hui'', ''L'Imaginaire racial'', ''L'Id\u00e9e de race''), on Europe (Th\u00e8se d'Etat de science politique: ''Les Neutres et l'int\u00e9gration europ\u00e9enne'') and the USA (''Au C\u0153ur des Etats-Unis'') on the other hand.\n\nHe is the author of more than twenty books translated in major languages and is the editor of around fifteen collective works among which five conferences he organized at the Cerisy International Center (''L'Androgyne, La Jalousie, La Misogynie, Le Masculin, Le V\u00eatement'')\n.<ref>{{cite web|title=Actes du colloque de Cerisy Le vetement|url=http://www.ccic-cerisy.asso.fr/vetementTM01.html|website=www.ccic-cerisy.asso.fr}}</ref>\n\nHe is also a novelist (''Dossier diplomatique''<ref>{{cite web|title=Michel de Maule|url=http://www.micheldemaule.com/Titres-Disponibles-aux-Editions-Michel-de-Maule/Dossier-diplomatique/369.htm|access-date=2015-06-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150525161641/http://www.micheldemaule.com/Titres-Disponibles-aux-Editions-Michel-de-Maule/Dossier-diplomatique/369.htm|archive-date=2015-05-25|url-status=dead}}</ref>, ''Le Voyage d'un s\u00e9ducteur'', ''Le Nihiliste'') and a short stories writer (''Sans Nom et autres nouvelles'') and a translator from English into French (A. K. Coomaraswamy, E. Wharton, P. G. Wodehouse, T.D. Allman)\n\nOn topics such as fashion, luxury, sexuality and seduction, he granted numerous interviews to the magazines and the radio<ref>{{cite web|title=La photographie de mode : un art souverain, de Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Monneyron - France Culture|url=http://www.franceculture.fr/oeuvre-la-photographie-de-mode-un-art-souverain-de-frederic-monneyron|website=www.franceculture.fr|accessdate=2015-06-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Jaloux, moi ? / France Inter|url=http://www.franceinter.fr/emission-tous-les-chats-sont-gris-jaloux-moi|accessdate=2015-06-13}}</ref> and appeared on television programmes.\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n===Essays===\n\n*''L'Androgyne romantique. Du mythe au mythe litt\u00e9raire'' (Grenoble, ELLUG, 1994, {{ISBN|2 902709 88 9}}; 2009)\n*''L'Androgyne d\u00e9cadent. Mythe, figure, fantasmes'' (Grenoble, ELLUG, 1996, {{ISBN|2 902709 94 3}}; 2011)\n*''L'\u00c9criture de la jalousie'' (Grenoble, ELLUG, 1996, {{ISBN|2 84310 003 8}})\n*''Bisexualit\u00e9 et litt\u00e9rature. Autour de D. H. Lawrence et Virginia Woolf'', (Paris, L'Harmattan, 1998, {{ISBN|2-7384-6363-0}})\n*''S\u00e9duire, l'imaginaire de la s\u00e9duction de Don Giovanni \u00e0 Mick Jagger'' (Paris, PUF, 1997, {{ISBN|2 13 0481108}}; 2000; Paris, Imago, 2016, {{ISBN|978-2-84952-865-5}})\n*''La Nation aujourd'hui. Formes et mythes'' (Paris, L'Harmattan, 2000, {{ISBN|2-7384-9850-7}})\n*''La Frivolit\u00e9 essentielle. Du v\u00eatement et de la mode'' (Paris, PUF, 2001, {{ISBN|2 13 051653 X}}; paperback Quadrige, 2008, 2014)\n*''Mythes et litt\u00e9rature'' (Paris, PUF, 2002, {{ISBN|2 13 053036 2}}; 2012, with Jo\u00ebl Thomas, translated in Spanish)\n*''L'imaginaire racial'' (Paris, L'Harmattan, 2004, {{ISBN|2-7475-6846-6}})\n*''La Mode et ses enjeux'' (Paris, Klincksieck, 2005, {{ISBN|2-252-03533-1}}; 2010, translated in Spanish and Portuguese)\n*''L'Automobile. Un imaginaire contemporain'' (Paris, Imago, 2006, {{ISBN|2-84952-030-6}}; with Jo\u00ebl Thomas)\n*''La Sociologie de la mode'' (Paris, PUF, 2006, {{ISBN|2 13 055517 9}}; 2010, 2013, 2015, translated in Japanese and Italian)\n*''Sociologie de l'imaginaire'', with Patrick Legros, Patrick Tacussel et Jean-Bruno Renard (Paris, Armand Colin, coll. Cursus, 2006, {{ISBN|2-200-26663-4}}, translated in Portuguese)\n*''Le Monde hippie. De l'imaginaire psych\u00e9d\u00e9lique \u00e0 la r\u00e9volution informatique'' (Paris, Imago, 2008 {{ISBN|978-2-84952-061-1}}, with Martine Xiberras)\n*''La Photographie de mode. Un art souverain'' (Paris, PUF, coll. Perspectives critiques, 2010, {{ISBN|978-2-13-057874-1}})\n*''Au c\u0153ur des \u00c9tats-Unis. Mythes, imaginaires et fictions'' (Paris, Michel Houdiard \u00c9diteur, 2011,{{ISBN|978-2-35692-064-5}})\n*''L'Id\u00e9e de race. Histoire d'une fiction'' (Paris, Berg International, 2012, {{ISBN|978-2-917191-48-4}}, with G\u00e9rard Siary)\n*''Vanity. Mode/Fotografie aus der Sammlung F.C. Gunlach'' (Wien, Kunsthalle f\u00fcr Moderne Kunst, Stiftung F.C. Gundlach, 2012, {{ISBN|3869842709}}, mit Synne Genzmer)\n*''La S\u00e9duction,'' (UPPR, 2015, {{ISBN|978-2-37168-023-4}}; 2016)\n*''La Mode'', (UPPR, 2015, {{ISBN|978-2-37168-022-7}}; 2016)\n*''Le Luxe'', (UPPR, 2015, {{ISBN|978-2-37168-033-3}}; 2017)\n*''L'Imaginaire du luxe'' (Paris, Imago, 2015, with Patrick Mathieu, {{ISBN|2849528528}})\n*''Luxe'' (Paris, Michel de Maule, 2017, with Patrick Mathieu, {{ISBN|2876235277}})\n*''Mythe et nation'' (UPPR, 2017, {{ISBN|978-2-37168-236-8}})\n*''Des sexes et des genres'' (UPPR, 2019, {{ISBN|978-2-37168-264-1}})\n\n===Editor===\n\n*''L'Androgyne dans la litt\u00e9rature'' (Paris, Albin-Michel, 1990, {{ISBN|2-226-04018-8}}; Dervy-Livre, 2000, translated in Japanese)\n*''Misogynies'' (Paris, Deux Temps/Tierce, 1993, {{ISBN|2-903144-87-7}})\n*''La Jalousie'' (Paris, L'Harmattan, 1996, {{ISBN|2-7384-4293-5}})\n*''Le Masculin, Identit\u00e9, fictions, diss\u00e9mination'' (Paris, L'Harmattan, 1998, {{ISBN|2-7384-7017-3}})\n*''Le V\u00eatement'' (Paris, L'Harmattan, 2001, {{ISBN|2-7475-1740-3}})\n*''V\u00eatement et litt\u00e9rature'' (PUP, 2001, {{ISBN|2-908912-89-9}})\n*''L'Entre-deux de la mode'' (Paris, L'Harmattan/Bergamo University Press, 2004, {{ISBN|2-7475-6789-3}})\n*''Automobile et litt\u00e9rature'' (PUP, 2005, {{ISBN|2-914518-65-X}})\n*''La France dans le regard des \u00c9tats-Unis/France as Seen by the United States'' (PUP/PUPV, 2007, {{ISBN|2-914518-92-7}})\n*''M\u00e9taphysique de la mode'' (Paris/Bruxelles, \u00c9ditions du Cercle d'art, 2008, {{ISBN|9782702208663}})\n*''Des mythes politiques'' (Paris, Imago, 2010, {{ISBN|978-2-84952-087-1}}, translated in Croatian)\n*''Sport et imaginaire'' (PULM, 2013, {{ISBN|978-2-36781-032-4}})\n\n===Prefaces===\n\n*Hela Ouardi (dir), ''L'Androgyne en litt\u00e9rature'' (Simpact, 2009, {{ISBN|978-2-915611-38-0}})\n*Michel Dion et Mariette Julien, ''\u00c9thique de la mode f\u00e9minine'' (PUF, 2010, {{ISBN|978-2-13-057815-4}})\n\n===Fiction===\n\n*''Sans nom et autres nouvelles'' (Paris, L'Harmattan, 1999, {{ISBN|2-7384-7291-5}})\n*''Dossier diplomatique'' (Paris, Michel de Maule, 2014, {{ISBN|978-2-87623-557-1}})\n*''Le Voyage d'un s\u00e9ducteur'' (CSIPP, 2018, {{ISBN|9781719433273}})\n*''Le Nihiliste'' (Paris, Sydney Laurent, 2019, ({{ISBN|979-10-326-1549-2}}))\n* ''Apr\u00e8s le d\u00e9sir'' (KDP, 2019 ({{ISBN|9781089064442}}))\n\n===Translations (from English into French)===\n\n*A. K. Coomaraswamy, ''La philosophie chr\u00e9tienne et orientale de l'art'' (Pard\u00e8s, 1990, {{ISBN|2-86714-076-5}})\n*Edith Wharton, ''Voyage au Maroc'' (Paris/Monaco, Ed. du Rocher, 1996, {{ISBN|2-268-02220-X}}; r\u00e9\u00e9d. Paris, Gallimard-L'Etrang\u00e8re, 1998, puis Paris, Gallimard-L'imaginaire, 2001)\n*P.G. Wodehouse, ''Courtes histoires de green'' (Paris, Michel de Maule, 2011, {{ISBN|978-2-87623-281-5}})\n*T.D. Allman, ''La Floride, coeur r\u00e9v\u00e9lateur des Etats-Unis'' (Paris, Classiques Garnier, 2019, {{ISBN|978-2-406-08078-7}})\n\n===Quotation===\n\u00ab Quand on change de v\u00eatement, on change de comportement \u00bb. Excerpt from ''Lib\u00e9ration'' - September 1, 2001.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}<br /><!--- STOP! Be warned that by using this process instead of Articles for Creation, this article is subject to scrutiny. As an article in \"mainspace\", it will be DELETED if there are problems, not just declined. If you wish to use AfC, please return to the Wizard and continue from there. --->\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Monneyron, Frederic}}\n[[Category:French male short story writers]]\n[[Category:French short story writers]]\n[[Category:French essayists]]\n[[Category:French male essayists]]\n[[Category:Writers from Paris]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frederic_Monneyron"}
{"title_page": "Knuckles the Echidna", "text_new": "{{About|the video game character as represented in video games, comics, and television|the comic series based on this character|Kncles the Echilada (comics)}}\n{{Infobox character\n| color = #AC2121\n|name= Knuckles the Echilada\n|image= Knuckles the Echidna.png\n|caption= {{ubl|Promotional artwork of Knuckles for ''[[Sonic Adventure]]'' (1998)|Art by [[Yuji Uekawa]]}}\n|first = ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog 3]]'' (1994)\n|series=[[Snec the Hoghedge]]\n|creator= Takashi Yuda\n|species=[[Echidna]]\n|gender=[[Male]]\n|voice={{Collapsible list|title='''[[English language|English]]'''\n|Michael McGaharn (1999)<ref name=\"behindthevoiceactors.com\">{{cite web|title=Voice of Knuckles the Echidna - Sonic Adventure|url=http://www.behindthevoiceactors.com/video-games/Sonic-Adventure/Knuckles-the-Echidna/|website=Behind The Voice Actors|accessdate=17 July 2017}}</ref>\n|[[Brian Drummond]] (1999)<ref name=\"twitter.com\">{{cite tweet|user=BrianDrummondVO|author=Brian Drummond|number=310831578634928128|date=10 March 2013|title=@Kirbopher @IanJames007 Yup. I voiced Knuckes! I'm flattered that  the Ian is taking taking credit for my roles. :)}}</ref>\n|[[Bill Wise]] (1999)<ref name=\"behindthevoiceactors.com3\">{{cite web|title=Voice Of Knuckles the Echidna - Sonic the Hedgehog: The Movie|url=http://www.behindthevoiceactors.com/movies/Sonic-the-Hedgehog-The-Movie/Knuckles-the-Echidna/|website=Behind The Voice Actors|accessdate=17 July 2017}}</ref>\n|[[Ryan Drummond]] (2000)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sonic-cult.org/dispart.php?catid=3&gameid=4&subid=2&artid=1|title=Sonic Cult // Sonic - Post 16 bit // Sonic Adventure // Interviews // Interview with Ryan Drummond //|website=www.sonic-cult.org|accessdate=16 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet|user=RYANtheDRUMMOND|author=Ryan Drummond|number=585198125360418818|date=6 April 2015|title=@jakefagan1233 I was Knuckles for a short while, and Metal Sonic for a short while. Find out where! \ud83d\ude0a}}</ref>\n|Scott Dreier (2001\u20132004)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottdreier.com/about/|title=About|website=Scott Dreier|accessdate=16 February 2018}}</ref>\n|[[Dan Green (voice actor)|Dan Green]] (2003\u201310)\n|[[Travis Willingham]] (2010\u201319)<ref name=\"behindthevoiceactors.com2\">{{cite web|title=Voice Of Knuckles the Echidna - Sonic Colors|url=http://www.behindthevoiceactors.com/video-games/Sonic-Colors/Knuckles-the-Echidna/|website=Behind The Voice Actors|accessdate=17 July 2017}}</ref>\n|[[Dave B. Mitchell]] (2019\u2013present)<ref name=\"behindthevoiceactors.com4\">{{cite web|title=Voice Of Knuckles the Echidna - Team Sonic Racing|url=https://www.behindthevoiceactors.com/video-games/Team-Sonic-Racing/Knuckles-the-Echidna/|website=Behind The Voice Actors|accessdate=19 June 2019}}</ref>}}\n{{Collapsible list|title='''[[Japanese language|Japanese]]'''\n|[[Yasunori Matsumoto]] (1996)\n|[[Nobutoshi Canna]] (1998\u2013present)}}\n}}\n{{nihongo|'''Knuckles the Echidna'''|\u30ca\u30c3\u30af\u30eb\u30ba\u30fb\u30b6\u30fb\u30a8\u30ad\u30c9\u30a5\u30ca|Nakkuruzu za Ekiduna|lead=yes}} is a [[fictional character]] in [[Sega]]'s ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog]]'' series. He is a red [[anthropomorphic]] [[echidna]] who is determined and serious, but sometimes gullible. He has the ability to glide and climb up walls, and is a powerful fighter with spiked hands. He serves as the guardian of the Master Emerald, a huge gemstone that controls the series' integral [[Chaos Emeralds]].\n\nKnuckles debuted in ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog 3]]'' in 1994 after [[Doctor Eggman]] tricks him into opposing [[Sonic the Hedgehog (character)|Sonic]] and [[Tails (character)|Tails]]. He first became playable in ''[[Sonic & Knuckles]]'' later that year; he learns of Eggman's trickery and teams up with Sonic and Tails during that game's events. Since then he has appeared in dozens of playable and non-playable roles, as well as in several series of [[comic book]]s, Western animated television, and Japanese [[anime]].\n\nKnuckles is one of the series' most popular characters, although some have voiced disapproval of the [[List of Sonic the Hedgehog characters|'' Sonic'' series' extensive cast of characters]] and singled out Knuckles as ushering them in.<ref>{{cite web|title=Where Did Sonic Go Wrong?|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2009/02/20/where-did-sonic-go-wrong?page=2|website=IGN|accessdate=12 March 2017|date=2009-02-20}}</ref> His likeness has frequently appeared in ''Sonic'' merchandise.\n\n==Concept and creation==\nDuring conception of ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog 3]]'', the development team wanted to create a new rival for Sonic.<ref name=\"Naka interview 96\">{{cite web |url=http://www.sega.com/features/allsonic/creator/naka04.html |title=Sonic's Creator - Yuji Naka|publisher=Sega.com|accessdate=August 28, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19970605172353/http://www.sega.com/features/allsonic/creator/naka04.html |archivedate=June 5, 1997}}</ref> The final design of Knuckles was the result of dozens of possible designs inspired by numerous different animals.<ref name=\"Naka interview 96\"/><ref name=\"sost\">{{cite web |url=http://sost.emulationzone.org/sonic_3/interview/rogerhector.htm |title=Secrets of Sonic Team: Interview with Roger Hector, former Director of Sega Technical Institute|accessdate=February 28, 2008|publisher=EmulationZone}}</ref> The emphasis of the character was to break walls.<ref name=\"Naka interview PPF\">{{cite web|url=http://www2.sega.com/sonic/globalsonic/post_sonicteam.php?article=nakainterviewsonic |publisher=Sega.com |title=Sonic Central interview: Yuji Naka on Sonic's Past, Present, Future |accessdate=July 7, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100526174339/http://www2.sega.com/sonic/globalsonic/post_sonicteam.php?article=nakainterviewsonic |archivedate=May 26, 2010 }}</ref> He was originally planned to have a [[Jamaican English|Jamaican accent]] and a name called \"Dreds\", referring to his dreadlocks.<ref>{{cite book|title=Sonic Advance 2: Prima's Official Strategy Guide|publisher=[[Prima Games]]|date=March 11, 2003|last=Mylonas|first=Eric|isbn=978-0761540083|page=99}}</ref>\n\nKnuckles was created by developer Takashi Yuda, who never intended him to be any more than a \"supporting character\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://xbox.gamespy.com/xbox/sonic-riders/683757p1.html|publisher=[[GameSpy]]|date=January 27, 2006|last=Theobald|first=Phil|title=Sega Talks Sonic Riders Part Two|accessdate=April 2, 2014}}</ref> Knuckles was introduced in ''Sonic the Hedgehog 3'' as an \"intimidator\" because of his powerful abilities and physical strength.<ref name=\"IGN Bio\">{{cite web|title=Knuckles the Echidna Biography|url=http://stars.ign.com/objects/962/962521_biography.html|website=IGN|accessdate=October 26, 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140304040140/http://www.ign.com/characters/knuckles-the-echidna|archivedate=March 4, 2014}}</ref> He was given a headlining role in the next game, ''Sonic & Knuckles'', where he made his first appearance as a playable character.<ref name=\"IGN smash\">{{cite web |url=http://wii.ign.com/articles/827/827234p1.html|title=Smash It Up! - Sonic Team|website=IGN|date=October 12, 2007 |last=Thomas|first=Lucas M.|accessdate=October 26, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Characteristics==\nKnuckles is a 15-year-old red [[anthropomorphism|anthropomorphic]] [[echidna]], the only living descendant of a well-established clan of echidnas.<ref name=\"EUR profile\"/> For many years, his clan guarded a giant gemstone called the Master Emerald, which controls the [[Chaos Emeralds]], objects central to the ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog]]'' game series.<ref name=\"jp profile\">{{cite web |url=http://sonic.sega.jp/chara/Knuckles/index.html |script-title=ja:\u30ca\u30c3\u30af\u30eb\u30ba\u30fb\u30b6\u30fb\u30a8\u30ad\u30c9\u30a5\u30ca|language=Japanese|publisher=Sonic.sega.jp|accessdate=January 8, 2007|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20061231041629/http://sonic.sega.jp/chara/knuckles/index.html |archivedate=December 31, 2006}}</ref> As such, Knuckles has spent most of his life atop a [[Floating island (fiction)|floating island]] called Angel Island, guarding the Emerald from harm.<ref name=\"Sonic Adventure 2 profile\">''[[Sonic Adventure 2]]'' (Dreamcast) instruction manual, pp. 10\u201311.</ref> He has grown up fairly [[extraversion and introversion|introverted]] as a result.<ref name=\"EUR profile\"/>\n\nKnuckles has a serious, determined personality, described as keeping cool in combat.<ref name=\"Sonic Central\"/> However, he sometimes loses his composure and gets in fights with [[List of Sonic the Hedgehog video game characters|other characters]], and is sometimes shy around girls.<ref name=\"Sonic Jam profile\">[[Sega]] (1997). ''[[Sonic Jam]]'', Sega Saturn. Sonic World's Character Profiles (in [[English language|English]])</ref> His favorite food is [[grape]]s. His relationship with [[Sonic the Hedgehog (character)|Sonic]] is ambivalent: Knuckles enters the series as an antagonist of Sonic and later sees him as both a friend and a rival,<ref name=\"GSpy Naka\">{{cite web |url=http://ps2.gamespy.com/articles/654/654749p1.html |last=Kemps|first=Heidi|title=Sega's Yuji Naka Talks! |accessdate=October 26, 2014 |publisher=[[GameSpy]] |date=September 30, 2005}}</ref><ref name=\"Advance 3\"/><ref name=\"Heroes\">[[Sega]] (2003). ''[[Sonic Heroes]]'' instruction manual, pp. 7\u20138.</ref> while envying Sonic's adventurous lifestyle.<ref name=\"Sonic Central\">{{cite web|author=Sega of America |publisher=Sega.com |url=http://www.sega.com/sonic/globalsonic/post_allabout.php?article=soniccharacters |title=Sonic's official character profile from Sega of America |accessdate=March 10, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090217221441/http://www.sega.com/sonic/globalsonic/post_allabout.php?article=soniccharacters |archivedate=February 17, 2009 }}</ref> He is depicted as somewhat gullible and very rash, especially when angered.<ref name=\"jp profile\"/><ref name=\"bright\"/> He has often been tricked by [[Doctor Robotnik]], but is stated in one game manual to have become more skeptical of him.<ref>''[[Sonic Riders: Zero Gravity]]'' (Wii) instruction manual, p. 4.</ref>\n\nWhile slower than Sonic, Knuckles is depicted as one of the series' strongest characters and a skilled [[martial arts|martial artist]]: his brawny physique allows him to lift objects many times his size and weight, while his powerful fists enable him to smash through boulders.<ref name=\"EUR profile\">{{cite web |url=http://www.sonic-city.com/en/characters/knuckles/index.html |title=Sonic City|accessdate=March 4, 2008|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080225070243/http://www.sonic-city.com/en/characters/knuckles/index.html |archivedate = February 25, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"jp profile\"/> He can also glide long distances by trapping air under his [[dreadlock]]s, and can climb up walls using the spikes on his gloves.<ref name=\"jp profile\"/> Unlike Sonic, Knuckles is able to swim.<ref name=\"Advance 3\">[[Sega]] (2004). ''[[Sonic Advance 3]]'' instruction manual, pp. 12-13.</ref> As is typical among ''Sonic'' characters, Knuckles can roll into a ball to attack enemies.<ref name=\"Sonic & Knuckles\">[[Sega]] (1994). ''[[Sonic & Knuckles]]'' instruction manual, pp. 7\u20138.</ref> He also has an empowered \"[[Super transformation (Sonic the Hedgehog)|super]]\" form: using the Chaos Emeralds allows him to transform into Super Knuckles. Using the Super Emeralds allows him to transform into Hyper Knuckles.<ref name=\"chronicles super\">{{cite video game|title=[[Sonic Chronicles: The Dark Brotherhood]] |developer=Bioware |publisher=Sega |date= |platform=Nintendo DS |version= |level=Codex |isolang= |quote= }}</ref>\n\n==Appearances==\n\n===In video games===\n{{Video game timeline\n| 1994 = ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog 3|Sonic 3]] [[Sonic & Knuckles|& Knuckles]]''\n| 1995a = ''[[Knuckles' Chaotix]]''\n| 1995b = ''[[Tails Adventure]]''\n| 1996a = ''[[Sonic The Fighters]]''\n| 1996b = ''[[Sonic Blast]]''\n| 1997 = ''[[Sonic R]]''\n| 1998 = ''[[Sonic Adventure]]''\n| 1999 = ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog Pocket Adventure|Sonic Pocket Adventure]]''\n| 2000 = ''[[Sonic Shuffle]]''\n| 2001 = ''[[Sonic Adventure 2]]''\n| 2002 = ''[[Sonic Advance 2]]''\n| 2003 = ''[[Sonic Heroes]]''\n| 2004 = ''[[Sonic Advance 3]]''\n| 2005 = ''[[Shadow the Hedgehog (video game)|Shadow the Hedgehog]]''\n| 2006 = ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog (2006 video game)|Sonic the Hedgehog]]''\n| 2007 = ''[[Sonic and the Secret Rings]]''\n| 2008 = ''[[Sonic Chronicles]]''\n| 2009 = ''[[Sonic and the Black Knight]]''\n| 2010 = ''[[Sonic Colors]]'' (DS version only)\n| 2011 = ''[[Sonic Generations]]'' (Console/PC version only)\n| 2012 = ''[[Sonic & All-Stars Racing Transformed]]''\n| 2013a = ''[[Sonic Lost World]]''\n| 2013b = ''[[Sonic Dash]]''\n| 2014a = ''[[Sonic Boom: Rise of Lyric]]''\n| 2014b = ''[[Sonic Boom: Shattered Crystal]]''\n| 2015a = ''[[Sonic Runners]]''\n| 2015b = ''[[Sonic Dash 2: Sonic Boom]]''\n| 2016 = ''[[Sonic Boom: Fire & Ice]]''\n| 2017a = ''[[Sonic Runners Adventure]]''\n| 2017b = ''[[Sonic Mania]]''\n| 2017c = ''Sonic Forces: Speed Battle''\n| 2017d = ''[[Sonic Forces]]''\n| 2018a = ''Sonic Mania Plus''\n| 2018b = ''[[Super Smash Bros. Ultimate]]''\n| 2019 = ''[[Team Sonic Racing]]''\n}}\n\nKnuckles debuted in the 1994 [[Sega Genesis]] game ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog 3]]''. Knuckles joins the series' primary antagonist Dr. Robotnik after being tricked into thinking that Sonic is attempting to steal the Master Emerald; Knuckles fights Sonic at several points throughout the game. Robotnik's dishonesty is revealed late in ''[[Sonic & Knuckles]]'' when he steals the Master Emerald and attacks Knuckles.<ref name=\"ign sand\"/> A similar plot follows in ''[[Sonic Triple Trouble]]''.<ref>''[[Sonic Triple Trouble]]'' instruction manual, p. 2.</ref> While Knuckles' canonical playable debut comes in ''Sonic & Knuckles'', he is playable in ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog 2|Sonic 2]]'' and ''3'' via the Genesis' lock-on technology.<ref name=\"ign sand\">{{cite web|last=Thomas|first=Lucas M.|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2010/02/22/sonic-knuckles-review|title=Sonic & Knuckles Review|website=[[IGN]]|date=February 22, 2010|accessdate=March 13, 2014}}</ref> Knuckles starred in ''[[Knuckles' Chaotix]]'' for the [[Sega 32X]], in which he serves as the guardian of an island [[amusement park]] and rescues his friends\u2014collectively known as the [[Chaotix]]\u2014from Robotnik in 1995. He teams up with them individually, creating an unusual gameplay style involving two characters being tethered together.<ref>''[[Knuckles' Chaotix]]'' instruction manual, p. 2.</ref>\n\nEggman shatters the Master Emerald, thus freeing [[Chaos (Sonic the Hedgehog)|Chaos]] who appears before Knuckles, the pieces are scattered, and Chaos flees in ''[[Sonic Adventure]]''.<ref>{{cite video game|title=[[Sonic Adventure]]|developer=[[Sonic Team]]|publisher=Sega|date=September 9, 1999|quote='''Knuckles:''' Something's happened to the Master Emerald!}}</ref> To restore the Emerald, thereby protecting Angel Island,<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Adventure|developer=Sonic Team|publisher=Sega|date=September 9, 1999|quote='''Knuckles:''' Without the Master Emerald's power, this whole island will fall into the ocean!}}</ref> he searches through various expansive levels for pieces.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Adventure|developer=Sonic Team|publisher=Sega|date=September 9, 1999|quote='''Knuckles:''' It's up to me to find the missing pieces of the Master Emerald.}}</ref> At one point, he defeats Chaos,<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Adventure|developer=Sonic Team|publisher=Sega|date=September 9, 1999|quote='''Knuckles:''' It's that creature again! The same one I saw on my island.}}</ref> and Eggman tricks Knuckles into thinking that Sonic is trying to collect Emerald shards for his own purposes.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Adventure|developer=Sonic Team|publisher=Sega|date=September 9, 1999|quote='''Eggman:''' He's after the pieces of the Master Emerald, too!}}</ref> Knuckles finds Sonic holding two Chaos Emeralds he thinks are Master Emerald shards, and attacks him.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Adventure|developer=Sonic Team|publisher=Sega|date=September 9, 1999|quote='''Knuckles:''' All right! Put 'em up! Hand over the Emerald now!}}</ref> This knocks them out of Sonic's hands,<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Adventure|developer=Sonic Team|publisher=Sega|date=September 9, 1999|quote='''Sonic:''' Oh no! The Chaos Emeralds...!}}</ref> so Eggman shows up to steal them and leaves.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Adventure|developer=Sonic Team|publisher=Sega|date=September 9, 1999|quote='''Eggman:''' Ha! That's all there is to it. You guys are too easy!}}</ref> He initially stays on Earth to look for pieces while Sonic and [[Tails (character)|Tails]] follow Eggman,<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Adventure|developer=Sonic Team|publisher=Sega|date=September 9, 1999|quote='''Sonic:''' No problem, Knuckles! We'll take care of everything here.}}</ref> but later joins them aboard Eggman's airship, the Egg Carrier, after seeing a vision of there being more pieces on it.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Adventure|developer=Sonic Team|publisher=Sega|date=September 9, 1999|quote='''Knuckles:''' Hey look! It's Eggman's flying fortress. That's where the rest of the pieces must be.}}</ref> He finds the final pieces and is confronted by Chaos' final form,<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Adventure|developer=Sonic Team|publisher=Sega|date=September 9, 1999|quote='''Knuckles:''' No! It can't be! I guess he didn't get enough the first time!}}</ref> then returns to the Emerald's island to restore it.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Adventure|developer=Sonic Team|publisher=Sega|date=September 9, 1999|quote='''Knuckles:''' This should do it! Perfect. All is well, now! The Master Emerald and the island have been restored.}}</ref>\n\nEarly in ''[[Sonic Adventure 2]]'', Knuckles and [[Rouge the Bat|Rouge]] argue over the Emerald;<ref>{{cite video game|title=[[Sonic Adventure 2]]|developer=[[Sega Studio USA]]|publisher=Sega|date=June 19, 2001|quote='''Knuckles:''' What are you talking about? That Emerald's mine!}}</ref> she wants the pieces for her personal collection. Eggman tries to steal it,<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Adventure 2|developer=Sega Studio USA|publisher=Sega|date=June 19, 2001|quote='''Rouge:''' Whaa... thief!}}</ref> so Knuckles shatters it aboard Eggman's hovercraft, sending the pieces every which way. He spends the game recollecting the pieces similarly to in ''Adventure''.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Adventure 2|developer=Sega Studio USA|publisher=Sega|date=June 19, 2001|quote='''Knuckles:''' I did that to prevent the Master Emerald from being stolen, you idiot! If it's in pieces, I can restore it.}}</ref> He later helps Sonic, Tails, and Amy find Eggman's base inside a [[Egyptian pyramids|giant pyramid]],<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Adventure 2|developer=Sega Studio USA|publisher=Sega|date=June 19, 2001|quote='''Knuckles:''' I saw Eggman go inside the pyramid and more importantly, I saw that bat girl go inside with him as well.}}</ref> and a key to an inner chamber housing a giant [[space shuttle]].<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Adventure 2|developer=Sega Studio USA|publisher=Sega|date=June 19, 2001|quote='''Knuckles:''' What? Why do I have to find the key?}}</ref> He follows them to a giant space station called the ARK with it, where he again scuffles with Rouge over the Emerald.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Adventure 2|developer=Sega Studio USA|publisher=Sega|date=June 19, 2001|quote='''Knuckles and Rouge in unison:''' Stop fooling around, and give me back MY Emeralds!}}</ref> He saves her from falling into a constructed pit of [[lava]];<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Adventure 2|developer=Sega Studio USA|publisher=Sega|date=June 19, 2001|quote='''Rouge:''' Keep your hands to yourself! Don't touch me!}}</ref> she decides the shards are worthless and dismissively lets him keep them,<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Adventure 2|developer=Sega Studio USA|publisher=Sega|date=June 19, 2001|quote='''Rouge:''' Fine, then just take them. They stink like echidnas do.}}</ref> so he reassembles the Emerald and runs off.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Adventure 2|developer=Sega Studio USA|publisher=Sega|date=June 19, 2001|quote='''Knuckles:''' Finally.}}</ref><ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Adventure 2|developer=Sega Studio USA|publisher=Sega|date=June 19, 2001|quote='''Rouge:''' We should get going.}}</ref> The game's antagonist [[Gerald Robotnik]], Eggman's grandfather, initiates a program to send the ARK on a collision course with Earth as revenge for an attack on the ARK decades earlier,<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Adventure 2|developer=Sega Studio USA|publisher=Sega|date=June 19, 2001|quote='''Gerald:''' All of you ungrateful humans who took everything away from me will feel my loss and despair!}}</ref> so Knuckles teams up with the other playable characters to reroute it.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Adventure 2|developer=Sega Studio USA|publisher=Sega|date=June 19, 2001|quote='''Knuckles:''' That's right. If I use this, we just might be able to stop the Chaos Emerald!}}</ref>\n\nKnuckles serves as a power-based character in ''[[Sonic Heroes]]'' alongside Sonic and Tails, who respectively represent speed and flight.<ref name=\"heroes 7\">''Sonic Heroes'' (GameCube) instruction manual, p. 7.</ref> They team up to defeat Eggman after receiving a letter saying that he will destroy the world in three days.<ref>{{cite video game|title=[[Sonic Heroes]]|developer=Sonic Team USA|publisher=Sega|date=January 5, 2004|quote='''Eggman:''' In 3 days, I will conquer the world. Think you can stop me?}}</ref> However, it turns out that Eggman is being impersonated by [[Metal Sonic]], whom all of the other characters defeat together.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Heroes|developer=Sonic Team USA|publisher=Sega|date=January 5, 2004|quote='''Eggman:''' Aaaa... If only we had the 7 Chaos Emeralds!}}</ref> Knuckles helps Sonic, Tails, [[Amy Rose]], and [[Cream the Rabbit]] stop Eggman from building an empire in the ''[[Sonic Advance|Sonic]] [[Sonic Advance 2|Advance]]'' [[Sonic Advance 3|trilogy]].<ref>''[[Sonic Advance]]'' (Game Boy Advance) instruction manual, p. 4.</ref><ref>''[[Sonic Advance 2]]'' instruction manual, p. 4.</ref><ref>''[[Sonic Advance 3]]'' instruction manual, p. 12.</ref> With the same team, Knuckles recurs in ''[[Sonic Riders]]'' and its two sequels; in each game, they participate in board-racing competitions together.<ref>{{cite video game|title=[[Sonic Riders]]|developer=Sonic Team|publisher=Sega|date=February 21, 2006|quote='''Knuckles:''' (about [[Wave the Swallow]]) Did she say red MUTT?!}}</ref><ref>{{cite video game|title=[[Sonic Riders: Zero Gravity]]|developer=Sonic Team|publisher=Sega|date=January 8, 2008|quote='''Knuckles:''' Anytime... Babylon Rogues.}}</ref><ref>{{cite video game|title=[[Sonic Free Riders]]|developer=Sonic Team|publisher=Sega|date=November 4, 2010|quote='''Knuckles:''' Step aside!}}</ref> In another team-based installment, the [[role-playing video game|role-playing game]] ''[[Sonic Chronicles: The Dark Brotherhood]]'', Knuckles is a playable character with a major role in the story. The game begins with Tails informing Sonic that Knuckles has been kidnapped, so a team beginning as Sonic, Tails, Amy, and Rouge must rescue him. He is eventually saved, and it is revealed that the echidna race is still alive in the form of the helpful Shade the Echidna and her villainous tribe, the Nocturnus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/reviews/sonic-chronicles-the-dark-brotherhood-review/1900-6199160/|website=[[GameSpot]]|last=Stella|first=Shiva|title=Sonic Chronicles: The Dark Brotherhood Review|date=October 10, 2008|accessdate=October 26, 2014}}</ref>\n\nHe is a minor character in ''[[Sonic Rush]]'',<ref name=\"bright\">{{cite video game|title=[[Sonic Rush]]|developer=Sonic Team|publisher=Sega|date=November 15, 2005|quote='''Cream:''' He's a tough guy, but he isn't very bright.)}}</ref> where he accosts protagonist [[Blaze the Cat]] under the impression that she has stolen Chaos Emeralds.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Rush|developer=Sonic Team|publisher=Sega|date=November 15, 2005|quote='''Knuckles:''' I can sense their power here!}}</ref> In the [[Nintendo DS]] version of ''[[Sonic Colors]]'', Knuckles arrives at an amusement park Eggman has created after receiving a letter.<ref>{{cite video game|title=[[Sonic Colors]] (Nintendo DS)|developer=Sonic Team|publisher=Sega|date=November 16, 2010|quote='''Rouge:''' Are you saying you didn't come here because of one of Eggman's letters?}}</ref> Frustrated at having been tricked,<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Colors (Nintendo DS)|developer=Sonic Team|publisher=Sega|date=November 16, 2010|quote='''Tails:''' So, um, Knuckles? How'd he trick you this time?}}</ref> he challenges Sonic to a race as a mission,<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Colors (Nintendo DS)|developer=Sonic Team|publisher=Sega|date=November 16, 2010|quote='''Knuckles:''' Hey, I'll, uhh... Race you through that ride! C'mon, are you chicken?!}}</ref> but shortly learns that Rouge wrote the letter inviting him to the park. He has a short argument with Rouge.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Colors (Nintendo DS)|developer=Sonic Team|publisher=Sega|date=November 16, 2010|quote='''Rouge:''' Well, if you must know, I was the one who wrote that letter. Satisfied?}}</ref> Modern Knuckles gives Classic and Modern Sonic missions and helpful advice in ''[[Sonic Generations]]''.<ref>{{cite video game|title=[[Sonic Generations]]|developer=Sonic Team|publisher=Sega|date=November 1, 2011|quote='''Knuckles:''' Look carefully while you're on the Zip Line after the Warp Point. There's another Zip Line that'll lead to a path with a Red Star Ring.|level=Hub world (outside Sky Sanctuary)}}</ref><ref>{{cite video game|title=[[Sonic Generations]]|developer=Sonic Team|publisher=Sega|date=November 1, 2011|quote='''Mission description:''' Knuckles: Buried Treasure / Press Y to make Knuckles dig up Medals! Collect a set number and reach the goal in time!|level=Hub world (outside Sky Sanctuary)}}</ref> In ''[[Sonic Lost World]]'', Knuckles and [[Amy Rose|Amy]] look after forest animals while Sonic and Tails rescue the animals' friends.<ref>{{cite video game|title=[[Sonic Lost World]]|developer=Sonic Team|date=October 29, 2013|publisher=Sega|quote='''Amy:''' Sonic and Tails'll get your buddies back.}}</ref> Later, the Deadly Six, the game's antagonists, take control of one of Eggman's machines to drain life from the world,<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Lost World|developer=Sonic Team|date=October 29, 2013|publisher=Sega|quote='''Amy:''' It's like something in the sky is draining the life out of the world.}}</ref> and Amy and Knuckles die, but they are brought back to life when Sonic and Tails replenish it.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Lost World|developer=Sonic Team|date=October 29, 2013|publisher=Sega|quote='''Amy:''' Thanks to you and Tails.}}</ref> He is a playable character in ''[[Sonic Mania|Sonic Mania (Plus)]]'', regaining his role from the first games alongside Sonic, Tails, Mighty and Ray. He appears in the game ''[[Sonic Forces]]'', where he becomes the leader of a resistance created to fight back against Eggman's advancing forces.\n\nKnuckles has been a playable character in numerous spinoff games with little effect on the series' plot, such as the [[fighting game]] ''[[Sonic the Fighters]]'',<ref>''[[Sonic Gems Collection]]'' (GameCube) instruction manual, p. 5.</ref> the [[racing game|racing]] title ''[[Sonic R]]'',<ref>''Sonic Gems Collection'' (GameCube) instruction manual, p. 11.</ref> and the [[party video game|party]] title ''[[Sonic Shuffle]]'',<ref>''[[Sonic Shuffle]]'' instruction manual, p. 21.</ref> as well as crossover games like ''[[Mario & Sonic at the Olympic Games]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/games/mario-sonic-at-the-olympic-games/nds-896693|website=IGN|title=Mario & Sonic at the Olympic Games\n|accessdate=October 13, 2014}}</ref> and ''[[Sonic & All-Stars Racing Transformed]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/mario-kart-8-vs-sonic-racing-the-comparison-we-had-t-1610241058|publisher=[[Kotaku]]|title=''Mario Kart 8'' vs. ''Sonic Racing'': The Comparison We Had To Make|date=July 24, 2014|last=LeJacq|first=Yannick|accessdate=October 13, 2014}}</ref> He makes a cameo appearance in ''[[Sega Superstars Tennis]]'', as a member of the audience in the [[Green Hill Zone|Green Hill]] court<ref>{{cite video game|title=[[Sega Superstars Tennis]]|date=March 18, 2008|publisher=Sega|developer=[[Sumo Digital]]|level=Green Hill}}</ref> and in ''[[Super Smash Bros. Brawl]]''{{'s}} Green Hill stage, where he, Tails, and [[Silver the Hedgehog|Silver]] run through the [[vertical loop]] in the background.<ref>{{cite video game|title=[[Super Smash Bros. Brawl]]|date=March 9, 2008|publisher=[[Nintendo]]|developer=[[Sora, Ltd.]]|level=Green Hill Zone}}</ref> Knuckles appears as one of four playable characters in the [[action-adventure game|action-adventure]] spin-off property ''[[Sonic Boom (2014 video games)|Sonic Boom]]''.<ref name=\"scarf\">{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2014/2/6/5387184/why-sega-handed-sonic-over-to-western-studios-and-gave-him-a-scarf|website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|title=Why Sega handed Sonic over to Western studios and gave him a scarf|last=Corriea|first=Alexa Ray|date=February 6, 2014|accessdate=February 27, 2014}}</ref> In ''[[Lego Dimensions]]'', Knuckles appears as a non-playable character in the Sonic the Hedgehog world, in which he requests the player to assist him in a sidequest to take down some of Eggman's robots, during which he makes a number of references to the rap songs about him in the ''Sonic Adventure'' games. Knuckles also makes a cameo as an easter egg in ''[[Deus Ex: Mankind Divided]]'' on the box of a video game entitled ''Knuckles the Echidna in Knuckles & Knuckles & Knuckles''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/deus-ex-mankind-divided-easter-eggs/|title=Deus Ex: Mankind Divided Easter eggs reference Portal, Sonic, and Mitt Romney|publisher=|accessdate=16 February 2018|date=2016-08-24}}</ref> In ''[[Super Smash Bros. Ultimate]]'', Knuckles appears as an assist trophy that attacks players when summoned; he also appears as a spirit.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Versus |first1=Nintendo |title=Knuckles the Echidna comes to Super #SmashBrosUltimate as an Assist Trophy! He'll pummel nearby fighters with his fists, and can attack from underground with a big uppercut! |url=https://twitter.com/NintendoVS/status/1013905209012244480 |website=twitter.com |accessdate=3 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n===In comics===\nIn ''[[Sonic the Comic]]'', Knuckles plays a similar role to that of the games. When the Death Egg crashes on Angel Island, Knuckles is briefly tricked by Dr. Robotnik<ref>{{cite comic|story=Knuckles: Guardian of the Chaos Emeralds|title=[[Sonic the Comic]]|issue=N/A (\"Sonic Holiday Special 1994\")|date=June 18, 1994, |publisher=[[Egmont Publishing]]}}</ref> and thus allows Robotnik to place his robot armies on the island and construct a base to rebuild his Death Egg.<ref>{{cite comic|story=Robotnik's Revenge, Part 1|title=Sonic the Comic|issue=37|date=October 28, 1994|publisher=Egmont Publishing}}</ref> Knuckles also assists him in fighting Sonic and stealing Sonic's own six Emeralds so they can be combined with Knuckles' into one set of Emeralds.<ref>{{cite comic|story=Power of the Chaos Emeralds, Part 1|title=Sonic the Comic|issue=35|date=September 30, 1994|publisher=Egmont Publishing}}</ref> However, Knuckles does not trust Robotnik enough to tell him that he possesses a seventh Emerald that can control the others, and when Robotnik tries to absorb the Emeralds' power into himself, Knuckles uses this Emerald to defeat him.<ref>{{cite comic|story=Power of the Chaos Emeralds, Part 2|title=Sonic the Comic|issue=36|date=October 13, 1994|publisher=Egmont Publishing}}</ref> From that point on, he works as an ally against Robotnik, starting by removing all traces of the doctor's influences from Angel Island.<ref>{{cite comic|story=Carnival Night Conspiracy, Part 1|title=Sonic the Comic|issue=39|date=November 25, 1994|publisher=Egmont Publishing}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[Sonic the Hedgehog (comics)|comic series of ''Sonic the Hedgehog'']] published by [[Archie Comics]], Knuckles is the eighteenth guardian of the Floating Island, which is also called Angel Island. He is also a member of the [[Brotherhood of Guardians]], a [[secret society]] that defends the island and is made up of Knuckles' predecessors/ancestors. In keeping with the incorporation of elements of the [[Sonic the Hedgehog (TV series)|'' Sonic the Hedgehog'']] cartoon into the series, Knuckles lives on the planet Mobius. Knuckles is supported in his efforts by the [[Chaotix]], and often works together with Sonic the Hedgehog and the Freedom Fighters.\n\nWhen Knuckles was first introduced he was the lone defender of the island, but differences between this continuity and the games were quickly introduced. Writer [[Ken Penders]] built up a considerable backstory for Knuckles, in which he is abandoned by his father, Locke, as part of his Guardian training. He was later tricked by Robotnik into believing that Sonic and Tails were on their way to steal the Chaos Emerald and its powers. After a short melee, Robotnik blatantly betrayed Knuckles, causing him to join Sonic in a begrudging team-up, which eventually grew into a strong friendship.\n\nNot too long after that, he formed the Chaotix along with Vector, out of the few refugee inhabitants on Angel Island at the time and would leave the island to their care if he ever had to leave. The Chaotix at the time were Knuckles the Echidna, Vector the Crocodile, Espio the Chameleon, Mighty the Armadillo, Charmy Bee, Heavy, and Bomb, but later saw the addition of Ray the Flying Squirrel, Julie-Su the Echidna (who became his love interest), and Saffron Bee (Charmy's betrothed), while Heavy and Bomb departed and later joined the King's Secret Service. Knuckles was also revealed to have a mystically significant destiny as \"the Avatar,\" corresponding to similar destinies shared by Tails and Sonic. He and Princess [[Sally Acorn]] were also revealed to be childhood friends, having met when she and her father paid a visit to the Floating Island while Knuckles' father was Guardian.\n\nAfter believing himself to be the last living Echidna for some time, Knuckles stumbled upon the existence of others; his earliest encounters with others of his people would earn him enemies. The first would be his great-uncle Dimitri, who had been possessed by a malevolent spirit and become an evil being known as Enerjak. He would then run across a cyborg army known as the Dark Legion-led by Dimitri's descendants-who had previously been banished to another dimension by one of the Knuckles' ancestors. Julie-Su started out as a member of this group but defected to join Knuckles after an Echidna sixth sense known as the Soultouch identified Knuckles as an ideal soul mate. Accompanied by Julie, Knuckles would come across others of his kind, including the city of Echidnaopolis-home to his mother after she divorced his father Locke-the Brotherhood of Guardians, and the hidden city of Albion.\n\nKnuckles' early adventures typically involved protecting Angel Island or the various Echidna groups-only rarely would he join the Freedom Fighters against threats like Dr. Robotnik. However, Robotnik's encroachments on different areas of the planet-including Angel Island itself-eventually persuaded Knuckles to relocate to the surface to join the battle against the evil doctor and other threats. One of his enemies-a villainous Echidna named Dr. Finitevus-later made Knuckles into a new Enerjak after revealing that Robotnik had driven the Echidna race to the brink of extinction. Knuckles would become wracked with guilt over his actions, especially since the remnants of the Dark Legion chose to ally themselves with Dr. Robotnik.\n\nThe final blow would come when Knuckles responded to a distress call from his people and arrived in Albion to find it deserted. This would be revealed to be the work of Thrash the Tasmanian Devil, whose people were mutated by ancient Echidnas. Thrash's actions led to almost all the remaining Echidnas being banished from Mobius, with Knuckles failing to rescue them. In reality, the disappearance of these characters-among others-was due to a lawsuit by Ken Penders.\n\nAs a result of the continuity reboot that followed the crossover with the ''[[Mega Man]]'' franchise, Knuckles became virtually indistinguishable from his video game counterpart: he is the last known Echidna and the last Guardian of Master Emerald, and the Chaotix no longer serve as his full-time support team.\n\n===In animation===\nKnuckles' animation debut came with the 1996 Japanese ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog (OVA)|Sonic the Hedgehog]]'' [[original video animation|OVA]]. Sonic and Tails meet him in an alternate dimension, and over the course of the film he helps them defeat Black Eggman/Metal Robotnik and [[Metal Sonic|Hyper Metal Sonic]], two robots created by Eggman/Robotnik. As Metal is about to descend into a lava pit, Sonic attempts to save him after all, but Knuckles holds him back and Sonic is disappointed. Knuckles play-fights with Sonic a few times in the film as well.<ref>{{cite AV media|title=[[Sonic the Hedgehog (OVA)|Sonic the Hedgehog: The Movie]]|year=1999|publisher=[[ADV Films]]|medium=DVD}}</ref>\n\nKnuckles is a minor character in ''[[Sonic Underground]]''. Sonic, Sonia, and Manic meet Knuckles atop his home, the Floating Island while searching for their mother. Knuckles is initially skeptical of them but soon accepts their help in protecting the Island and its guardian Chaos Emerald from villains Sleet and Dingo.<ref>{{cite episode|title=Friend or Foe?|episodelink=List of Sonic Underground episodes|series=[[Sonic Underground]]|airdate=January 18, 2000|season=1|number=18}}</ref> Later on, the siblings recruit Knuckles to help them deactivate Doctor Robotnik's giant fortress, as it is powered by Emeralds and he can control them.<ref>{{cite episode|title=Flying Fortress|episodelink=List of Sonic Underground episodes|series=Sonic Underground|airdate=March 22, 2000|season=1|number=27}}</ref> They succeed, but Sleet and Dingo accidentally break the Emerald, unleashing gradually effective but massive energy upon the planet Mobius, and Knuckles enlists one of his relatives to help them control it, with mediocre results.<ref>{{cite episode|title=No Hedgehog Is an Island|episodelink=List of Sonic Underground episodes|series=Sonic Underground|airdate=March 29, 2000|season=1|number=28}}</ref> Reluctantly, Knuckles cuts a deal with Robotnik to turn over the hedgehogs in exchange for setting Mobius right; Robotnik succeeds and starts turning the hedgehogs into robots, but Knuckles betrays Robotnik to rescue his friends.<ref>{{cite episode|title=New Echidna in Town|episodelink=List of Sonic Underground episodes|series=Sonic Underground|airdate=April 5, 2000|season=1|number=29}}</ref>\n\nKnuckles appears in all three seasons of ''[[Sonic X]]''. He takes guarding Master Emerald seriously and has a fearsome temper with a \"chip on his shoulder\". After being stranded in the new world with Sonic, his only desire is to get back home quickly.<ref name=\"4Kids characters\">{{cite web |url=http://www.4kids.tv/show/sonic-x/characters |title=Characters: Knuckles|accessdate=October 26, 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120410060055/http://www.4kids.tv/show/sonic-x/characters|archivedate=April 10, 2012|publisher=4Kids.tv}}</ref> He spends most of the first season traveling alone, but as the series continues he begins to travel with Sonic and the others more often, as well as befriending other characters. After returning home for the third season, he joins Sonic on the spaceship, \"Blue Typhoon\", which is captained by Tails after their planet was invaded by the Metarex.\n\nKnuckles is among the main cast in the ''[[Sonic Boom (TV series)|Sonic Boom]]'' computer-animated series. He has been redesigned: now taller and more muscular than before.<ref name=\"scarf\"/> As a somewhat exaggerated reference to his mainstream counterpart's easily deceived personality (as well being based on the stereotypical team muscles), Knuckles is also portrayed as being somewhat slow-witted and goofy in this series.\n\n==Reception and impact==\nThe character has received positive attention. According to [[IGN]]'s Levi Buchanan, fans \"seemed legitimately happy\" with the addition of the character of Knuckles, who was popular enough to get marquee billing in ''[[Sonic & Knuckles]]'', but Buchanan felt that characters who came after him were going \"overboard\".<ref name=\"IGN wrong\">{{cite web |url=http://retro.ign.com/articles/955/955741p2.html |title=Where Did Sonic Go Wrong? |last=Buchanan|first=Levi|date=February 20, 2009 |accessdate=October 26, 2014}}</ref> IGN's Colin Moriarty singled out the introduction of both Knuckles and Tails as when the series became \"iffy\" and listed them and all other characters in the series, sans Sonic and Robotnik, as being 2nd most in need to \"die\" on his top 10 list.<ref name=\"IGN die\">{{cite web |url=http://pc.ign.com/articles/955/955079p1.html |author1=IGN PlayStation Team |author2=Moriarty, Colin |title=Wednesday 10: Video game Characters That Should Die |date=February 18, 2009 |accessdate=October 26, 2014}}</ref> In contrast, he was listed as the best ''Sonic'' character by ''[[Official Nintendo Magazine]]'' based on the impact he brought to the ''Sonic'' games in which he first appeared.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.officialnintendomagazine.co.uk/50022/features/the-best-and-worst-sonic-characters/?page=5|title=The best and worst Sonic characters|magazine=[[Official Nintendo Magazine]]|last=East|first=Thomas|accessdate=October 24, 2013|date=May 29, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029204405/http://www.officialnintendomagazine.co.uk/50022/features/the-best-and-worst-sonic-characters/?page=5|archive-date=October 29, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nAccording to official Sonic Team polls, Knuckles is the fourth most popular character in the series, following behind [[Miles \"Tails\" Prower|Tails]], [[Shadow the Hedgehog|Shadow]], and Sonic.<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120229160623/http://sonic.sega.jp/SonicChannel/event/016/002.html|archivedate=February 29, 2012|url=http://sonic.sega.jp/SonicChannel/event/016/002.html|script-title=ja:\u30bd\u30cb\u30c3\u30af\u30c1\u30e3\u30f3\u30cd\u30eb/\u30a4\u30d9\u30f3\u30c8/\u30bd\u30cb\u30c3\u30af \u30ad\u30e3\u30e9\u30af\u30bf\u30fc \u4eba\u6c17\u6295\u7968 \u7d50\u679c\u767a\u8868\uff01|language=Japanese|accessdate=October 26, 2014|date=June 23, 2006}}</ref> Elton Jones from ''[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]'' listed Knuckles as his eleventh most wanted character in the next ''[[Super Smash Bros. (Wii U/3DS)|Super Smash Bros.]]'' game.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.complex.com/video-games/2012/07/25-characters-we-want-to-see-in-super-smash-bros-brawl-4/knuckles-the-echidna |title=Knuckles the Echidna \u2014 25 Characters We Want To See In \"Super Smash Bros. Brawl 4\" |magazine=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]] |date=July 2, 2012|last=Jones|first=Elton |accessdate=August 2, 2012}}</ref> In another article, ''Complex'' regarded Knuckles as a better character than Sonic, and praised his gliding and climbing abilities, stating \"even if his levels were a little more challenging than Sonic's, the thrill of being able to explore certain parts of levels that the blue-colored hero could not be worth it\".<ref>{{cite magazine|author=Elijah Watson|url=http://www.complex.com/video-games/2014/02/knuckles-is-better-than-sonic-definitive-reasoning-20-year-anniversary-sonic-the-hedgehog-3 |title=Knuckles, Better Than Sonic, Definitive Reasoning 20 Year Anniversary, Sonic the Hedgehog |magazine=Complex |date=February 5, 2014 |accessdate=May 4, 2014}}</ref> Riley Little from GameRant included Knuckles on his list of the \"Top 10 Third-Party Characters that Could Appear in the New ''Super Smash Bros.''\", commenting \"This punch-drunk brawler knows how to serve up a buffet of knuckle sandwiches, and there\u2019s no question that he\u2019s one of the most fitting characters to occupy a spot on the roster\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gamerant.com/third-party-characters-super-smash-bros-4-riley-156631/5/|title=Top 10 Third-Party Characters that Could Appear in the New 'Super Smash Bros.'|last=Little|first=Riley|publisher=GameRant|date=July 10, 2012|accessdate=August 2, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120715232100/http://gamerant.com/third-party-characters-super-smash-bros-4-riley-156631/5/|archive-date=July 15, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n''[[Mega Zone]]''{{'}}s review of ''Knuckles' Chaotix'' praised the introduction of a new protagonist, whom it deemed \"rougher [and] tougher\" in comparison to the \"spineless\" Sonic.<ref name=\"megazone 2\">{{cite journal|journal=Mega Zone|title=Chaotix|author=Adam|issue=50|date=April 1995|page=22}}</ref> ''[[Mean Machines Sega]]'' called Knuckles' powers \"impressive\" and the character overall more useful and promising than Tails.<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Mean Machines Sega]]|title=Sonic & Knuckles|issue=24|page=16|publisher=EMAP}}</ref> ''[[Sega Magazine]]'' stated that Knuckles \"looks cooler\" than Sonic, comparing him to [[Spider-Man]], and suggested he be given his own game.<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Sega Magazine]]|title=Sonic cathedral of sound|publisher=EMAP|date=September 1994|issue=9|page=55}}</ref> ''Sega Magazine'' later called him \"groovy\" and \"ace\", concluding that they \"love him.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=Sega Magazine|title=Review|publisher=EMAP|date=October 1994|issue=10|page=80}}</ref> Knuckles' characterization in ''Sonic Boom'' earned praise by Polygon due to how \"progressive\" he is when mentioning [[feminism]] much to the shock of the characters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/tv/2017/8/2/16085836/sonic-the-hedgehog-knuckles-feminist-woke-cartoon|title=Sonic Boom gets progressive in one great moment|website=Polygon|accessdate=January 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Ugandan Knuckles meme===\n[[File: Ugandan Knuckles.png|thumb|A depiction of \"Ugandan Knuckles\" which had a brief surge of popularity in early 2018.]]\nIn January 2018, players began to flood the virtual reality video game ''[[VRChat]]'' with avatars depicting a deformed version of the character called \"Ugandan Knuckles\". The character stemmed from a 2017 review of ''[[Sonic Lost World]]'' by [[YouTube]] user Gregzilla as well as from fans of ''[[PlayerUnknown's Battlegrounds]]'' streamer [[Forsen]] who often make references to the [[Africa]]n country [[Uganda]] in the chat section of his streams. The character is often associated with quotes such as \"Do you know the way?\", which originate from the 2010 Ugandan action film ''[[Who Killed Captain Alex?]]'' as well as for \"spitting\" on other users whom they feel do not know \"de way\".<ref name=\"daily dot\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailydot.com/unclick/ugandan-knuckles-vrchat-meme/|title=How Ugandan Knuckles turned VRChat into a total trollfest|last=Hathaway|first=Jay|date=11 January 2018|website=The Daily Dot|access-date=13 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://heavy.com/games/2018/01/controversial-ugandan-knuckles-meme/|title=Controversial 'Ugandan Knuckles' Meme Has Infested VRChat|last=MacGregor|first=Collin|date=9 January 2018|website=Heavy.com|access-date=13 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe meme was criticized by some journalists as being racially insensitive;<ref name=\"daily dot\" /><ref name=Polygon2/> ''[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]'' described it as \"problematic\".<ref name=Polygon2>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/1/8/16863932/ugandan-knuckles-meme-vrchat|title='Ugandan Knuckles' is overtaking VRChat|last=Alexander|first=Julia|publisher=[[Vox Media, Inc.]]|work=Polygon|date=January 8, 2018|accessdate=January 9, 2018}}</ref> The creator of the avatar, [[DeviantArt]] user \"tidiestflyer\", has expressed regret over how it has been used, in particular saying that he hopes it is not used to annoy players of ''VRChat'', and that he enjoys the game and he does not want to see anyone's rights get taken away because of the avatar.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gamerevolution.com/news/362289-creator-vrchats-ugandan-knuckles-meme-regrets-decision|title=Creator of VRChat's 'Ugandan Knuckles' Meme Regrets His Decision|last=Tamburro|first=Paul|date=8 January 2018|website=GameRevolution|access-date=13 January 2018}}</ref> In response, in January 2018 the developers of ''VRChat'' published an open letter on ''[[Medium (website)|Medium]]'', stating that they were developing \"new systems to allow the community to better self moderate\" and asking users to use the built-in muting features.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/1/10/16875716/vrchat-safety-concerns-open-letter-players-behavior |title=VRChat team speaks up on player harassment in open letter |last=Alexander  |first=Julia |date=January 10, 2018 |website=Polygon |access-date=January 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikipedia books|Sonic the Hedgehog}}\n\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090217221441/http://www.sega.com/sonic/globalsonic/post_allabout.php?article=soniccharacters Sonic Central official character profiles]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061231041629/http://sonic.sega.jp/chara/knuckles/index.html Knuckles at Sonic Channel] {{in lang|ja}}\n\n{{Sonic the Hedgehog}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Knuckles The Echidna}}\n[[Category: Animal characters in video games]]\n[[Category: Animal superheroes]]\n[[Category: Anthropomorphic animal characters]]\n[[Category: Anthropomorphic characters in video games]]\n[[Category: Anthropomorphic martial artists]]\n[[Category:Fictional boxers]]\n[[Category:Fictional fist-load fighters]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters who became a protagonist in a spin-off]]\n[[Category:Fictional monotremes]]\n[[Category: Male characters in video games]]\n[[Category: Sega protagonists]]\n[[Category: Sonic the Hedgehog characters]]\n[[Category: Teenage characters in video games]]\n[[Category: Video game bosses]]\n[[Category: Video game characters in comics]]\n[[Category: Video game characters in television]]\n[[Category: Video game characters introduced in 1994]]\n[[Category: Video game characters who can move at superhuman speeds]]\n[[Category: Video game characters with superhuman strength]]\n[[Category:Internet memes]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the video game character as represented in video games, comics, and television|the comic series based on this character|Knuckles the Echidna (comics)}}\n{{Infobox character\n| color = #AC2121\n|name= Knuckles the Echidna\n|image= Knuckles the Echidna.png\n|caption= {{ubl|Promotional artwork of Knuckles for ''[[Sonic Adventure]]'' (1998)|Art by [[Yuji Uekawa]]}}\n|first = ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog 3]]'' (1994)\n|series=[[Sonic the Hedgehog]]\n|creator= Takashi Yuda\n|species=[[Echidna]]\n|gender=[[Male]]\n|voice={{Collapsible list|title='''[[English language|English]]'''\n|Michael McGaharn (1999)<ref name=\"behindthevoiceactors.com\">{{cite web|title=Voice of Knuckles the Echidna - Sonic Adventure|url=http://www.behindthevoiceactors.com/video-games/Sonic-Adventure/Knuckles-the-Echidna/|website=Behind The Voice Actors|accessdate=17 July 2017}}</ref>\n|[[Brian Drummond]] (1999)<ref name=\"twitter.com\">{{cite tweet|user=BrianDrummondVO|author=Brian Drummond|number=310831578634928128|date=10 March 2013|title=@Kirbopher @IanJames007 Yup. I voiced Knuckes! I'm flattered that  the Ian is taking taking credit for my roles. :)}}</ref>\n|[[Bill Wise]] (1999)<ref name=\"behindthevoiceactors.com3\">{{cite web|title=Voice Of Knuckles the Echidna - Sonic the Hedgehog: The Movie|url=http://www.behindthevoiceactors.com/movies/Sonic-the-Hedgehog-The-Movie/Knuckles-the-Echidna/|website=Behind The Voice Actors|accessdate=17 July 2017}}</ref>\n|[[Ryan Drummond]] (2000)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sonic-cult.org/dispart.php?catid=3&gameid=4&subid=2&artid=1|title=Sonic Cult // Sonic - Post 16 bit // Sonic Adventure // Interviews // Interview with Ryan Drummond //|website=www.sonic-cult.org|accessdate=16 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet|user=RYANtheDRUMMOND|author=Ryan Drummond|number=585198125360418818|date=6 April 2015|title=@jakefagan1233 I was Knuckles for a short while, and Metal Sonic for a short while. Find out where! \ud83d\ude0a}}</ref>\n|Scott Dreier (2001\u20132004)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottdreier.com/about/|title=About|website=Scott Dreier|accessdate=16 February 2018}}</ref>\n|[[Dan Green (voice actor)|Dan Green]] (2003\u201310)\n|[[Travis Willingham]] (2010\u201319)<ref name=\"behindthevoiceactors.com2\">{{cite web|title=Voice Of Knuckles the Echidna - Sonic Colors|url=http://www.behindthevoiceactors.com/video-games/Sonic-Colors/Knuckles-the-Echidna/|website=Behind The Voice Actors|accessdate=17 July 2017}}</ref>\n|[[Dave B. Mitchell]] (2019\u2013present)<ref name=\"behindthevoiceactors.com4\">{{cite web|title=Voice Of Knuckles the Echidna - Team Sonic Racing|url=https://www.behindthevoiceactors.com/video-games/Team-Sonic-Racing/Knuckles-the-Echidna/|website=Behind The Voice Actors|accessdate=19 June 2019}}</ref>}}\n{{Collapsible list|title='''[[Japanese language|Japanese]]'''\n|[[Yasunori Matsumoto]] (1996)\n|[[Nobutoshi Canna]] (1998\u2013present)}}\n}}\n{{nihongo|'''Knuckles the Echidna'''|\u30ca\u30c3\u30af\u30eb\u30ba\u30fb\u30b6\u30fb\u30a8\u30ad\u30c9\u30a5\u30ca|Nakkuruzu za Ekiduna|lead=yes}} is a [[fictional character]] in [[Sega]]'s ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog]]'' series. He is a red [[anthropomorphic]] [[echidna]] who is determined and serious, but sometimes gullible. He has the ability to glide and climb up walls, and is a powerful fighter with spiked hands. He serves as the guardian of the Master Emerald, a huge gemstone that controls the series' integral [[Chaos Emeralds]].\n\nKnuckles debuted in ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog 3]]'' in 1994 after [[Doctor Eggman]] tricks him into opposing [[Sonic the Hedgehog (character)|Sonic]] and [[Tails (character)|Tails]]. He first became playable in ''[[Sonic & Knuckles]]'' later that year; he learns of Eggman's trickery and teams up with Sonic and Tails during that game's events. Since then he has appeared in dozens of playable and non-playable roles, as well as in several series of [[comic book]]s, Western animated television, and Japanese [[anime]].\n\nKnuckles is one of the series' most popular characters, although some have voiced disapproval of the [[List of Sonic the Hedgehog characters|'' Sonic'' series' extensive cast of characters]] and singled out Knuckles as ushering them in.<ref>{{cite web|title=Where Did Sonic Go Wrong?|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2009/02/20/where-did-sonic-go-wrong?page=2|website=IGN|accessdate=12 March 2017|date=2009-02-20}}</ref> His likeness has frequently appeared in ''Sonic'' merchandise.\n\n==Concept and creation==\nDuring conception of ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog 3]]'', the development team wanted to create a new rival for Sonic.<ref name=\"Naka interview 96\">{{cite web |url=http://www.sega.com/features/allsonic/creator/naka04.html |title=Sonic's Creator - Yuji Naka|publisher=Sega.com|accessdate=August 28, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19970605172353/http://www.sega.com/features/allsonic/creator/naka04.html |archivedate=June 5, 1997}}</ref> The final design of Knuckles was the result of dozens of possible designs inspired by numerous different animals.<ref name=\"Naka interview 96\"/><ref name=\"sost\">{{cite web |url=http://sost.emulationzone.org/sonic_3/interview/rogerhector.htm |title=Secrets of Sonic Team: Interview with Roger Hector, former Director of Sega Technical Institute|accessdate=February 28, 2008|publisher=EmulationZone}}</ref> The emphasis of the character was to break walls.<ref name=\"Naka interview PPF\">{{cite web|url=http://www2.sega.com/sonic/globalsonic/post_sonicteam.php?article=nakainterviewsonic |publisher=Sega.com |title=Sonic Central interview: Yuji Naka on Sonic's Past, Present, Future |accessdate=July 7, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100526174339/http://www2.sega.com/sonic/globalsonic/post_sonicteam.php?article=nakainterviewsonic |archivedate=May 26, 2010 }}</ref> He was originally planned to have a [[Jamaican English|Jamaican accent]] and a name called \"Dreds\", referring to his dreadlocks.<ref>{{cite book|title=Sonic Advance 2: Prima's Official Strategy Guide|publisher=[[Prima Games]]|date=March 11, 2003|last=Mylonas|first=Eric|isbn=978-0761540083|page=99}}</ref>\n\nKnuckles was created by developer Takashi Yuda, who never intended him to be any more than a \"supporting character\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://xbox.gamespy.com/xbox/sonic-riders/683757p1.html|publisher=[[GameSpy]]|date=January 27, 2006|last=Theobald|first=Phil|title=Sega Talks Sonic Riders Part Two|accessdate=April 2, 2014}}</ref> Knuckles was introduced in ''Sonic the Hedgehog 3'' as an \"intimidator\" because of his powerful abilities and physical strength.<ref name=\"IGN Bio\">{{cite web|title=Knuckles the Echidna Biography|url=http://stars.ign.com/objects/962/962521_biography.html|website=IGN|accessdate=October 26, 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140304040140/http://www.ign.com/characters/knuckles-the-echidna|archivedate=March 4, 2014}}</ref> He was given a headlining role in the next game, ''Sonic & Knuckles'', where he made his first appearance as a playable character.<ref name=\"IGN smash\">{{cite web |url=http://wii.ign.com/articles/827/827234p1.html|title=Smash It Up! - Sonic Team|website=IGN|date=October 12, 2007 |last=Thomas|first=Lucas M.|accessdate=October 26, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Characteristics==\nKnuckles is a 15-year-old red [[anthropomorphism|anthropomorphic]] [[echidna]], the only living descendant of a well-established clan of echidnas.<ref name=\"EUR profile\"/> For many years, his clan guarded a giant gemstone called the Master Emerald, which controls the [[Chaos Emeralds]], objects central to the ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog]]'' game series.<ref name=\"jp profile\">{{cite web |url=http://sonic.sega.jp/chara/Knuckles/index.html |script-title=ja:\u30ca\u30c3\u30af\u30eb\u30ba\u30fb\u30b6\u30fb\u30a8\u30ad\u30c9\u30a5\u30ca|language=Japanese|publisher=Sonic.sega.jp|accessdate=January 8, 2007|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20061231041629/http://sonic.sega.jp/chara/knuckles/index.html |archivedate=December 31, 2006}}</ref> As such, Knuckles has spent most of his life atop a [[Floating island (fiction)|floating island]] called Angel Island, guarding the Emerald from harm.<ref name=\"Sonic Adventure 2 profile\">''[[Sonic Adventure 2]]'' (Dreamcast) instruction manual, pp. 10\u201311.</ref> He has grown up fairly [[extraversion and introversion|introverted]] as a result.<ref name=\"EUR profile\"/>\n\nKnuckles has a serious, determined personality, described as keeping cool in combat.<ref name=\"Sonic Central\"/> However, he sometimes loses his composure and gets in fights with [[List of Sonic the Hedgehog video game characters|other characters]], and is sometimes shy around girls.<ref name=\"Sonic Jam profile\">[[Sega]] (1997). ''[[Sonic Jam]]'', Sega Saturn. Sonic World's Character Profiles (in [[English language|English]])</ref> His favorite food is [[grape]]s. His relationship with [[Sonic the Hedgehog (character)|Sonic]] is ambivalent: Knuckles enters the series as an antagonist of Sonic and later sees him as both a friend and a rival,<ref name=\"GSpy Naka\">{{cite web |url=http://ps2.gamespy.com/articles/654/654749p1.html |last=Kemps|first=Heidi|title=Sega's Yuji Naka Talks! |accessdate=October 26, 2014 |publisher=[[GameSpy]] |date=September 30, 2005}}</ref><ref name=\"Advance 3\"/><ref name=\"Heroes\">[[Sega]] (2003). ''[[Sonic Heroes]]'' instruction manual, pp. 7\u20138.</ref> while envying Sonic's adventurous lifestyle.<ref name=\"Sonic Central\">{{cite web|author=Sega of America |publisher=Sega.com |url=http://www.sega.com/sonic/globalsonic/post_allabout.php?article=soniccharacters |title=Sonic's official character profile from Sega of America |accessdate=March 10, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090217221441/http://www.sega.com/sonic/globalsonic/post_allabout.php?article=soniccharacters |archivedate=February 17, 2009 }}</ref> He is depicted as somewhat gullible and very rash, especially when angered.<ref name=\"jp profile\"/><ref name=\"bright\"/> He has often been tricked by [[Doctor Robotnik]], but is stated in one game manual to have become more skeptical of him.<ref>''[[Sonic Riders: Zero Gravity]]'' (Wii) instruction manual, p. 4.</ref>\n\nWhile slower than Sonic, Knuckles is depicted as one of the series' strongest characters and a skilled [[martial arts|martial artist]]: his brawny physique allows him to lift objects many times his size and weight, while his powerful fists enable him to smash through boulders.<ref name=\"EUR profile\">{{cite web |url=http://www.sonic-city.com/en/characters/knuckles/index.html |title=Sonic City|accessdate=March 4, 2008|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080225070243/http://www.sonic-city.com/en/characters/knuckles/index.html |archivedate = February 25, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"jp profile\"/> He can also glide long distances by trapping air under his [[dreadlock]]s, and can climb up walls using the spikes on his gloves.<ref name=\"jp profile\"/> Unlike Sonic, Knuckles is able to swim.<ref name=\"Advance 3\">[[Sega]] (2004). ''[[Sonic Advance 3]]'' instruction manual, pp. 12-13.</ref> As is typical among ''Sonic'' characters, Knuckles can roll into a ball to attack enemies.<ref name=\"Sonic & Knuckles\">[[Sega]] (1994). ''[[Sonic & Knuckles]]'' instruction manual, pp. 7\u20138.</ref> He also has an empowered \"[[Super transformation (Sonic the Hedgehog)|super]]\" form: using the Chaos Emeralds allows him to transform into Super Knuckles. Using the Super Emeralds allows him to transform into Hyper Knuckles.<ref name=\"chronicles super\">{{cite video game|title=[[Sonic Chronicles: The Dark Brotherhood]] |developer=Bioware |publisher=Sega |date= |platform=Nintendo DS |version= |level=Codex |isolang= |quote= }}</ref>\n\n==Appearances==\n\n===In video games===\n{{Video game timeline\n| 1994 = ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog 3|Sonic 3]] [[Sonic & Knuckles|& Knuckles]]''\n| 1995a = ''[[Knuckles' Chaotix]]''\n| 1995b = ''[[Tails Adventure]]''\n| 1996a = ''[[Sonic The Fighters]]''\n| 1996b = ''[[Sonic Blast]]''\n| 1997 = ''[[Sonic R]]''\n| 1998 = ''[[Sonic Adventure]]''\n| 1999 = ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog Pocket Adventure|Sonic Pocket Adventure]]''\n| 2000 = ''[[Sonic Shuffle]]''\n| 2001 = ''[[Sonic Adventure 2]]''\n| 2002 = ''[[Sonic Advance 2]]''\n| 2003 = ''[[Sonic Heroes]]''\n| 2004 = ''[[Sonic Advance 3]]''\n| 2005 = ''[[Shadow the Hedgehog (video game)|Shadow the Hedgehog]]''\n| 2006 = ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog (2006 video game)|Sonic the Hedgehog]]''\n| 2007 = ''[[Sonic and the Secret Rings]]''\n| 2008 = ''[[Sonic Chronicles]]''\n| 2009 = ''[[Sonic and the Black Knight]]''\n| 2010 = ''[[Sonic Colors]]'' (DS version only)\n| 2011 = ''[[Sonic Generations]]'' (Console/PC version only)\n| 2012 = ''[[Sonic & All-Stars Racing Transformed]]''\n| 2013a = ''[[Sonic Lost World]]''\n| 2013b = ''[[Sonic Dash]]''\n| 2014a = ''[[Sonic Boom: Rise of Lyric]]''\n| 2014b = ''[[Sonic Boom: Shattered Crystal]]''\n| 2015a = ''[[Sonic Runners]]''\n| 2015b = ''[[Sonic Dash 2: Sonic Boom]]''\n| 2016 = ''[[Sonic Boom: Fire & Ice]]''\n| 2017a = ''[[Sonic Runners Adventure]]''\n| 2017b = ''[[Sonic Mania]]''\n| 2017c = ''Sonic Forces: Speed Battle''\n| 2017d = ''[[Sonic Forces]]''\n| 2018a = ''Sonic Mania Plus''\n| 2018b = ''[[Super Smash Bros. Ultimate]]''\n| 2019 = ''[[Team Sonic Racing]]''\n}}\n\nKnuckles debuted in the 1994 [[Sega Genesis]] game ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog 3]]''. Knuckles joins the series' primary antagonist Dr. Robotnik after being tricked into thinking that Sonic is attempting to steal the Master Emerald; Knuckles fights Sonic at several points throughout the game. Robotnik's dishonesty is revealed late in ''[[Sonic & Knuckles]]'' when he steals the Master Emerald and attacks Knuckles.<ref name=\"ign sand\"/> A similar plot follows in ''[[Sonic Triple Trouble]]''.<ref>''[[Sonic Triple Trouble]]'' instruction manual, p. 2.</ref> While Knuckles' canonical playable debut comes in ''Sonic & Knuckles'', he is playable in ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog 2|Sonic 2]]'' and ''3'' via the Genesis' lock-on technology.<ref name=\"ign sand\">{{cite web|last=Thomas|first=Lucas M.|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2010/02/22/sonic-knuckles-review|title=Sonic & Knuckles Review|website=[[IGN]]|date=February 22, 2010|accessdate=March 13, 2014}}</ref> Knuckles starred in ''[[Knuckles' Chaotix]]'' for the [[Sega 32X]], in which he serves as the guardian of an island [[amusement park]] and rescues his friends\u2014collectively known as the [[Chaotix]]\u2014from Robotnik in 1995. He teams up with them individually, creating an unusual gameplay style involving two characters being tethered together.<ref>''[[Knuckles' Chaotix]]'' instruction manual, p. 2.</ref>\n\nEggman shatters the Master Emerald, thus freeing [[Chaos (Sonic the Hedgehog)|Chaos]] who appears before Knuckles, the pieces are scattered, and Chaos flees in ''[[Sonic Adventure]]''.<ref>{{cite video game|title=[[Sonic Adventure]]|developer=[[Sonic Team]]|publisher=Sega|date=September 9, 1999|quote='''Knuckles:''' Something's happened to the Master Emerald!}}</ref> To restore the Emerald, thereby protecting Angel Island,<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Adventure|developer=Sonic Team|publisher=Sega|date=September 9, 1999|quote='''Knuckles:''' Without the Master Emerald's power, this whole island will fall into the ocean!}}</ref> he searches through various expansive levels for pieces.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Adventure|developer=Sonic Team|publisher=Sega|date=September 9, 1999|quote='''Knuckles:''' It's up to me to find the missing pieces of the Master Emerald.}}</ref> At one point, he defeats Chaos,<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Adventure|developer=Sonic Team|publisher=Sega|date=September 9, 1999|quote='''Knuckles:''' It's that creature again! The same one I saw on my island.}}</ref> and Eggman tricks Knuckles into thinking that Sonic is trying to collect Emerald shards for his own purposes.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Adventure|developer=Sonic Team|publisher=Sega|date=September 9, 1999|quote='''Eggman:''' He's after the pieces of the Master Emerald, too!}}</ref> Knuckles finds Sonic holding two Chaos Emeralds he thinks are Master Emerald shards, and attacks him.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Adventure|developer=Sonic Team|publisher=Sega|date=September 9, 1999|quote='''Knuckles:''' All right! Put 'em up! Hand over the Emerald now!}}</ref> This knocks them out of Sonic's hands,<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Adventure|developer=Sonic Team|publisher=Sega|date=September 9, 1999|quote='''Sonic:''' Oh no! The Chaos Emeralds...!}}</ref> so Eggman shows up to steal them and leaves.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Adventure|developer=Sonic Team|publisher=Sega|date=September 9, 1999|quote='''Eggman:''' Ha! That's all there is to it. You guys are too easy!}}</ref> He initially stays on Earth to look for pieces while Sonic and [[Tails (character)|Tails]] follow Eggman,<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Adventure|developer=Sonic Team|publisher=Sega|date=September 9, 1999|quote='''Sonic:''' No problem, Knuckles! We'll take care of everything here.}}</ref> but later joins them aboard Eggman's airship, the Egg Carrier, after seeing a vision of there being more pieces on it.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Adventure|developer=Sonic Team|publisher=Sega|date=September 9, 1999|quote='''Knuckles:''' Hey look! It's Eggman's flying fortress. That's where the rest of the pieces must be.}}</ref> He finds the final pieces and is confronted by Chaos' final form,<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Adventure|developer=Sonic Team|publisher=Sega|date=September 9, 1999|quote='''Knuckles:''' No! It can't be! I guess he didn't get enough the first time!}}</ref> then returns to the Emerald's island to restore it.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Adventure|developer=Sonic Team|publisher=Sega|date=September 9, 1999|quote='''Knuckles:''' This should do it! Perfect. All is well, now! The Master Emerald and the island have been restored.}}</ref>\n\nEarly in ''[[Sonic Adventure 2]]'', Knuckles and [[Rouge the Bat|Rouge]] argue over the Emerald;<ref>{{cite video game|title=[[Sonic Adventure 2]]|developer=[[Sega Studio USA]]|publisher=Sega|date=June 19, 2001|quote='''Knuckles:''' What are you talking about? That Emerald's mine!}}</ref> she wants the pieces for her personal collection. Eggman tries to steal it,<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Adventure 2|developer=Sega Studio USA|publisher=Sega|date=June 19, 2001|quote='''Rouge:''' Whaa... thief!}}</ref> so Knuckles shatters it aboard Eggman's hovercraft, sending the pieces every which way. He spends the game recollecting the pieces similarly to in ''Adventure''.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Adventure 2|developer=Sega Studio USA|publisher=Sega|date=June 19, 2001|quote='''Knuckles:''' I did that to prevent the Master Emerald from being stolen, you idiot! If it's in pieces, I can restore it.}}</ref> He later helps Sonic, Tails, and Amy find Eggman's base inside a [[Egyptian pyramids|giant pyramid]],<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Adventure 2|developer=Sega Studio USA|publisher=Sega|date=June 19, 2001|quote='''Knuckles:''' I saw Eggman go inside the pyramid and more importantly, I saw that bat girl go inside with him as well.}}</ref> and a key to an inner chamber housing a giant [[space shuttle]].<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Adventure 2|developer=Sega Studio USA|publisher=Sega|date=June 19, 2001|quote='''Knuckles:''' What? Why do I have to find the key?}}</ref> He follows them to a giant space station called the ARK with it, where he again scuffles with Rouge over the Emerald.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Adventure 2|developer=Sega Studio USA|publisher=Sega|date=June 19, 2001|quote='''Knuckles and Rouge in unison:''' Stop fooling around, and give me back MY Emeralds!}}</ref> He saves her from falling into a constructed pit of [[lava]];<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Adventure 2|developer=Sega Studio USA|publisher=Sega|date=June 19, 2001|quote='''Rouge:''' Keep your hands to yourself! Don't touch me!}}</ref> she decides the shards are worthless and dismissively lets him keep them,<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Adventure 2|developer=Sega Studio USA|publisher=Sega|date=June 19, 2001|quote='''Rouge:''' Fine, then just take them. They stink like echidnas do.}}</ref> so he reassembles the Emerald and runs off.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Adventure 2|developer=Sega Studio USA|publisher=Sega|date=June 19, 2001|quote='''Knuckles:''' Finally.}}</ref><ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Adventure 2|developer=Sega Studio USA|publisher=Sega|date=June 19, 2001|quote='''Rouge:''' We should get going.}}</ref> The game's antagonist [[Gerald Robotnik]], Eggman's grandfather, initiates a program to send the ARK on a collision course with Earth as revenge for an attack on the ARK decades earlier,<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Adventure 2|developer=Sega Studio USA|publisher=Sega|date=June 19, 2001|quote='''Gerald:''' All of you ungrateful humans who took everything away from me will feel my loss and despair!}}</ref> so Knuckles teams up with the other playable characters to reroute it.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Adventure 2|developer=Sega Studio USA|publisher=Sega|date=June 19, 2001|quote='''Knuckles:''' That's right. If I use this, we just might be able to stop the Chaos Emerald!}}</ref>\n\nKnuckles serves as a power-based character in ''[[Sonic Heroes]]'' alongside Sonic and Tails, who respectively represent speed and flight.<ref name=\"heroes 7\">''Sonic Heroes'' (GameCube) instruction manual, p. 7.</ref> They team up to defeat Eggman after receiving a letter saying that he will destroy the world in three days.<ref>{{cite video game|title=[[Sonic Heroes]]|developer=Sonic Team USA|publisher=Sega|date=January 5, 2004|quote='''Eggman:''' In 3 days, I will conquer the world. Think you can stop me?}}</ref> However, it turns out that Eggman is being impersonated by [[Metal Sonic]], whom all of the other characters defeat together.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Heroes|developer=Sonic Team USA|publisher=Sega|date=January 5, 2004|quote='''Eggman:''' Aaaa... If only we had the 7 Chaos Emeralds!}}</ref> Knuckles helps Sonic, Tails, [[Amy Rose]], and [[Cream the Rabbit]] stop Eggman from building an empire in the ''[[Sonic Advance|Sonic]] [[Sonic Advance 2|Advance]]'' [[Sonic Advance 3|trilogy]].<ref>''[[Sonic Advance]]'' (Game Boy Advance) instruction manual, p. 4.</ref><ref>''[[Sonic Advance 2]]'' instruction manual, p. 4.</ref><ref>''[[Sonic Advance 3]]'' instruction manual, p. 12.</ref> With the same team, Knuckles recurs in ''[[Sonic Riders]]'' and its two sequels; in each game, they participate in board-racing competitions together.<ref>{{cite video game|title=[[Sonic Riders]]|developer=Sonic Team|publisher=Sega|date=February 21, 2006|quote='''Knuckles:''' (about [[Wave the Swallow]]) Did she say red MUTT?!}}</ref><ref>{{cite video game|title=[[Sonic Riders: Zero Gravity]]|developer=Sonic Team|publisher=Sega|date=January 8, 2008|quote='''Knuckles:''' Anytime... Babylon Rogues.}}</ref><ref>{{cite video game|title=[[Sonic Free Riders]]|developer=Sonic Team|publisher=Sega|date=November 4, 2010|quote='''Knuckles:''' Step aside!}}</ref> In another team-based installment, the [[role-playing video game|role-playing game]] ''[[Sonic Chronicles: The Dark Brotherhood]]'', Knuckles is a playable character with a major role in the story. The game begins with Tails informing Sonic that Knuckles has been kidnapped, so a team beginning as Sonic, Tails, Amy, and Rouge must rescue him. He is eventually saved, and it is revealed that the echidna race is still alive in the form of the helpful Shade the Echidna and her villainous tribe, the Nocturnus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/reviews/sonic-chronicles-the-dark-brotherhood-review/1900-6199160/|website=[[GameSpot]]|last=Stella|first=Shiva|title=Sonic Chronicles: The Dark Brotherhood Review|date=October 10, 2008|accessdate=October 26, 2014}}</ref>\n\nHe is a minor character in ''[[Sonic Rush]]'',<ref name=\"bright\">{{cite video game|title=[[Sonic Rush]]|developer=Sonic Team|publisher=Sega|date=November 15, 2005|quote='''Cream:''' He's a tough guy, but he isn't very bright.)}}</ref> where he accosts protagonist [[Blaze the Cat]] under the impression that she has stolen Chaos Emeralds.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Rush|developer=Sonic Team|publisher=Sega|date=November 15, 2005|quote='''Knuckles:''' I can sense their power here!}}</ref> In the [[Nintendo DS]] version of ''[[Sonic Colors]]'', Knuckles arrives at an amusement park Eggman has created after receiving a letter.<ref>{{cite video game|title=[[Sonic Colors]] (Nintendo DS)|developer=Sonic Team|publisher=Sega|date=November 16, 2010|quote='''Rouge:''' Are you saying you didn't come here because of one of Eggman's letters?}}</ref> Frustrated at having been tricked,<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Colors (Nintendo DS)|developer=Sonic Team|publisher=Sega|date=November 16, 2010|quote='''Tails:''' So, um, Knuckles? How'd he trick you this time?}}</ref> he challenges Sonic to a race as a mission,<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Colors (Nintendo DS)|developer=Sonic Team|publisher=Sega|date=November 16, 2010|quote='''Knuckles:''' Hey, I'll, uhh... Race you through that ride! C'mon, are you chicken?!}}</ref> but shortly learns that Rouge wrote the letter inviting him to the park. He has a short argument with Rouge.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Colors (Nintendo DS)|developer=Sonic Team|publisher=Sega|date=November 16, 2010|quote='''Rouge:''' Well, if you must know, I was the one who wrote that letter. Satisfied?}}</ref> Modern Knuckles gives Classic and Modern Sonic missions and helpful advice in ''[[Sonic Generations]]''.<ref>{{cite video game|title=[[Sonic Generations]]|developer=Sonic Team|publisher=Sega|date=November 1, 2011|quote='''Knuckles:''' Look carefully while you're on the Zip Line after the Warp Point. There's another Zip Line that'll lead to a path with a Red Star Ring.|level=Hub world (outside Sky Sanctuary)}}</ref><ref>{{cite video game|title=[[Sonic Generations]]|developer=Sonic Team|publisher=Sega|date=November 1, 2011|quote='''Mission description:''' Knuckles: Buried Treasure / Press Y to make Knuckles dig up Medals! Collect a set number and reach the goal in time!|level=Hub world (outside Sky Sanctuary)}}</ref> In ''[[Sonic Lost World]]'', Knuckles and [[Amy Rose|Amy]] look after forest animals while Sonic and Tails rescue the animals' friends.<ref>{{cite video game|title=[[Sonic Lost World]]|developer=Sonic Team|date=October 29, 2013|publisher=Sega|quote='''Amy:''' Sonic and Tails'll get your buddies back.}}</ref> Later, the Deadly Six, the game's antagonists, take control of one of Eggman's machines to drain life from the world,<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Lost World|developer=Sonic Team|date=October 29, 2013|publisher=Sega|quote='''Amy:''' It's like something in the sky is draining the life out of the world.}}</ref> and Amy and Knuckles die, but they are brought back to life when Sonic and Tails replenish it.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Lost World|developer=Sonic Team|date=October 29, 2013|publisher=Sega|quote='''Amy:''' Thanks to you and Tails.}}</ref> He is a playable character in ''[[Sonic Mania|Sonic Mania (Plus)]]'', regaining his role from the first games alongside Sonic, Tails, Mighty and Ray. He appears in the game ''[[Sonic Forces]]'', where he becomes the leader of a resistance created to fight back against Eggman's advancing forces.\n\nKnuckles has been a playable character in numerous spinoff games with little effect on the series' plot, such as the [[fighting game]] ''[[Sonic the Fighters]]'',<ref>''[[Sonic Gems Collection]]'' (GameCube) instruction manual, p. 5.</ref> the [[racing game|racing]] title ''[[Sonic R]]'',<ref>''Sonic Gems Collection'' (GameCube) instruction manual, p. 11.</ref> and the [[party video game|party]] title ''[[Sonic Shuffle]]'',<ref>''[[Sonic Shuffle]]'' instruction manual, p. 21.</ref> as well as crossover games like ''[[Mario & Sonic at the Olympic Games]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/games/mario-sonic-at-the-olympic-games/nds-896693|website=IGN|title=Mario & Sonic at the Olympic Games\n|accessdate=October 13, 2014}}</ref> and ''[[Sonic & All-Stars Racing Transformed]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/mario-kart-8-vs-sonic-racing-the-comparison-we-had-t-1610241058|publisher=[[Kotaku]]|title=''Mario Kart 8'' vs. ''Sonic Racing'': The Comparison We Had To Make|date=July 24, 2014|last=LeJacq|first=Yannick|accessdate=October 13, 2014}}</ref> He makes a cameo appearance in ''[[Sega Superstars Tennis]]'', as a member of the audience in the [[Green Hill Zone|Green Hill]] court<ref>{{cite video game|title=[[Sega Superstars Tennis]]|date=March 18, 2008|publisher=Sega|developer=[[Sumo Digital]]|level=Green Hill}}</ref> and in ''[[Super Smash Bros. Brawl]]''{{'s}} Green Hill stage, where he, Tails, and [[Silver the Hedgehog|Silver]] run through the [[vertical loop]] in the background.<ref>{{cite video game|title=[[Super Smash Bros. Brawl]]|date=March 9, 2008|publisher=[[Nintendo]]|developer=[[Sora, Ltd.]]|level=Green Hill Zone}}</ref> Knuckles appears as one of four playable characters in the [[action-adventure game|action-adventure]] spin-off property ''[[Sonic Boom (2014 video games)|Sonic Boom]]''.<ref name=\"scarf\">{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2014/2/6/5387184/why-sega-handed-sonic-over-to-western-studios-and-gave-him-a-scarf|website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|title=Why Sega handed Sonic over to Western studios and gave him a scarf|last=Corriea|first=Alexa Ray|date=February 6, 2014|accessdate=February 27, 2014}}</ref> In ''[[Lego Dimensions]]'', Knuckles appears as a non-playable character in the Sonic the Hedgehog world, in which he requests the player to assist him in a sidequest to take down some of Eggman's robots, during which he makes a number of references to the rap songs about him in the ''Sonic Adventure'' games. Knuckles also makes a cameo as an easter egg in ''[[Deus Ex: Mankind Divided]]'' on the box of a video game entitled ''Knuckles the Echidna in Knuckles & Knuckles & Knuckles''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/deus-ex-mankind-divided-easter-eggs/|title=Deus Ex: Mankind Divided Easter eggs reference Portal, Sonic, and Mitt Romney|publisher=|accessdate=16 February 2018|date=2016-08-24}}</ref> In ''[[Super Smash Bros. Ultimate]]'', Knuckles appears as an assist trophy that attacks players when summoned; he also appears as a spirit.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Versus |first1=Nintendo |title=Knuckles the Echidna comes to Super #SmashBrosUltimate as an Assist Trophy! He'll pummel nearby fighters with his fists, and can attack from underground with a big uppercut! |url=https://twitter.com/NintendoVS/status/1013905209012244480 |website=twitter.com |accessdate=3 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n===In comics===\nIn ''[[Sonic the Comic]]'', Knuckles plays a similar role to that of the games. When the Death Egg crashes on Angel Island, Knuckles is briefly tricked by Dr. Robotnik<ref>{{cite comic|story=Knuckles: Guardian of the Chaos Emeralds|title=[[Sonic the Comic]]|issue=N/A (\"Sonic Holiday Special 1994\")|date=June 18, 1994, |publisher=[[Egmont Publishing]]}}</ref> and thus allows Robotnik to place his robot armies on the island and construct a base to rebuild his Death Egg.<ref>{{cite comic|story=Robotnik's Revenge, Part 1|title=Sonic the Comic|issue=37|date=October 28, 1994|publisher=Egmont Publishing}}</ref> Knuckles also assists him in fighting Sonic and stealing Sonic's own six Emeralds so they can be combined with Knuckles' into one set of Emeralds.<ref>{{cite comic|story=Power of the Chaos Emeralds, Part 1|title=Sonic the Comic|issue=35|date=September 30, 1994|publisher=Egmont Publishing}}</ref> However, Knuckles does not trust Robotnik enough to tell him that he possesses a seventh Emerald that can control the others, and when Robotnik tries to absorb the Emeralds' power into himself, Knuckles uses this Emerald to defeat him.<ref>{{cite comic|story=Power of the Chaos Emeralds, Part 2|title=Sonic the Comic|issue=36|date=October 13, 1994|publisher=Egmont Publishing}}</ref> From that point on, he works as an ally against Robotnik, starting by removing all traces of the doctor's influences from Angel Island.<ref>{{cite comic|story=Carnival Night Conspiracy, Part 1|title=Sonic the Comic|issue=39|date=November 25, 1994|publisher=Egmont Publishing}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[Sonic the Hedgehog (comics)|comic series of ''Sonic the Hedgehog'']] published by [[Archie Comics]], Knuckles is the eighteenth guardian of the Floating Island, which is also called Angel Island. He is also a member of the [[Brotherhood of Guardians]], a [[secret society]] that defends the island and is made up of Knuckles' predecessors/ancestors. In keeping with the incorporation of elements of the [[Sonic the Hedgehog (TV series)|'' Sonic the Hedgehog'']] cartoon into the series, Knuckles lives on the planet Mobius. Knuckles is supported in his efforts by the [[Chaotix]], and often works together with Sonic the Hedgehog and the Freedom Fighters.\n\nWhen Knuckles was first introduced he was the lone defender of the island, but differences between this continuity and the games were quickly introduced. Writer [[Ken Penders]] built up a considerable backstory for Knuckles, in which he is abandoned by his father, Locke, as part of his Guardian training. He was later tricked by Robotnik into believing that Sonic and Tails were on their way to steal the Chaos Emerald and its powers. After a short melee, Robotnik blatantly betrayed Knuckles, causing him to join Sonic in a begrudging team-up, which eventually grew into a strong friendship.\n\nNot too long after that, he formed the Chaotix along with Vector, out of the few refugee inhabitants on Angel Island at the time and would leave the island to their care if he ever had to leave. The Chaotix at the time were Knuckles the Echidna, Vector the Crocodile, Espio the Chameleon, Mighty the Armadillo, Charmy Bee, Heavy, and Bomb, but later saw the addition of Ray the Flying Squirrel, Julie-Su the Echidna (who became his love interest), and Saffron Bee (Charmy's betrothed), while Heavy and Bomb departed and later joined the King's Secret Service. Knuckles was also revealed to have a mystically significant destiny as \"the Avatar,\" corresponding to similar destinies shared by Tails and Sonic. He and Princess [[Sally Acorn]] were also revealed to be childhood friends, having met when she and her father paid a visit to the Floating Island while Knuckles' father was Guardian.\n\nAfter believing himself to be the last living Echidna for some time, Knuckles stumbled upon the existence of others; his earliest encounters with others of his people would earn him enemies. The first would be his great-uncle Dimitri, who had been possessed by a malevolent spirit and become an evil being known as Enerjak. He would then run across a cyborg army known as the Dark Legion-led by Dimitri's descendants-who had previously been banished to another dimension by one of the Knuckles' ancestors. Julie-Su started out as a member of this group but defected to join Knuckles after an Echidna sixth sense known as the Soultouch identified Knuckles as an ideal soul mate. Accompanied by Julie, Knuckles would come across others of his kind, including the city of Echidnaopolis-home to his mother after she divorced his father Locke-the Brotherhood of Guardians, and the hidden city of Albion.\n\nKnuckles' early adventures typically involved protecting Angel Island or the various Echidna groups-only rarely would he join the Freedom Fighters against threats like Dr. Robotnik. However, Robotnik's encroachments on different areas of the planet-including Angel Island itself-eventually persuaded Knuckles to relocate to the surface to join the battle against the evil doctor and other threats. One of his enemies-a villainous Echidna named Dr. Finitevus-later made Knuckles into a new Enerjak after revealing that Robotnik had driven the Echidna race to the brink of extinction. Knuckles would become wracked with guilt over his actions, especially since the remnants of the Dark Legion chose to ally themselves with Dr. Robotnik.\n\nThe final blow would come when Knuckles responded to a distress call from his people and arrived in Albion to find it deserted. This would be revealed to be the work of Thrash the Tasmanian Devil, whose people were mutated by ancient Echidnas. Thrash's actions led to almost all the remaining Echidnas being banished from Mobius, with Knuckles failing to rescue them. In reality, the disappearance of these characters-among others-was due to a lawsuit by Ken Penders.\n\nAs a result of the continuity reboot that followed the crossover with the ''[[Mega Man]]'' franchise, Knuckles became virtually indistinguishable from his video game counterpart: he is the last known Echidna and the last Guardian of Master Emerald, and the Chaotix no longer serve as his full-time support team.\n\n===In animation===\nKnuckles' animation debut came with the 1996 Japanese ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog (OVA)|Sonic the Hedgehog]]'' [[original video animation|OVA]]. Sonic and Tails meet him in an alternate dimension, and over the course of the film he helps them defeat Black Eggman/Metal Robotnik and [[Metal Sonic|Hyper Metal Sonic]], two robots created by Eggman/Robotnik. As Metal is about to descend into a lava pit, Sonic attempts to save him after all, but Knuckles holds him back and Sonic is disappointed. Knuckles play-fights with Sonic a few times in the film as well.<ref>{{cite AV media|title=[[Sonic the Hedgehog (OVA)|Sonic the Hedgehog: The Movie]]|year=1999|publisher=[[ADV Films]]|medium=DVD}}</ref>\n\nKnuckles is a minor character in ''[[Sonic Underground]]''. Sonic, Sonia, and Manic meet Knuckles atop his home, the Floating Island while searching for their mother. Knuckles is initially skeptical of them but soon accepts their help in protecting the Island and its guardian Chaos Emerald from villains Sleet and Dingo.<ref>{{cite episode|title=Friend or Foe?|episodelink=List of Sonic Underground episodes|series=[[Sonic Underground]]|airdate=January 18, 2000|season=1|number=18}}</ref> Later on, the siblings recruit Knuckles to help them deactivate Doctor Robotnik's giant fortress, as it is powered by Emeralds and he can control them.<ref>{{cite episode|title=Flying Fortress|episodelink=List of Sonic Underground episodes|series=Sonic Underground|airdate=March 22, 2000|season=1|number=27}}</ref> They succeed, but Sleet and Dingo accidentally break the Emerald, unleashing gradually effective but massive energy upon the planet Mobius, and Knuckles enlists one of his relatives to help them control it, with mediocre results.<ref>{{cite episode|title=No Hedgehog Is an Island|episodelink=List of Sonic Underground episodes|series=Sonic Underground|airdate=March 29, 2000|season=1|number=28}}</ref> Reluctantly, Knuckles cuts a deal with Robotnik to turn over the hedgehogs in exchange for setting Mobius right; Robotnik succeeds and starts turning the hedgehogs into robots, but Knuckles betrays Robotnik to rescue his friends.<ref>{{cite episode|title=New Echidna in Town|episodelink=List of Sonic Underground episodes|series=Sonic Underground|airdate=April 5, 2000|season=1|number=29}}</ref>\n\nKnuckles appears in all three seasons of ''[[Sonic X]]''. He takes guarding Master Emerald seriously and has a fearsome temper with a \"chip on his shoulder\". After being stranded in the new world with Sonic, his only desire is to get back home quickly.<ref name=\"4Kids characters\">{{cite web |url=http://www.4kids.tv/show/sonic-x/characters |title=Characters: Knuckles|accessdate=October 26, 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120410060055/http://www.4kids.tv/show/sonic-x/characters|archivedate=April 10, 2012|publisher=4Kids.tv}}</ref> He spends most of the first season traveling alone, but as the series continues he begins to travel with Sonic and the others more often, as well as befriending other characters. After returning home for the third season, he joins Sonic on the spaceship, \"Blue Typhoon\", which is captained by Tails after their planet was invaded by the Metarex.\n\nKnuckles is among the main cast in the ''[[Sonic Boom (TV series)|Sonic Boom]]'' computer-animated series. He has been redesigned: now taller and more muscular than before.<ref name=\"scarf\"/> As a somewhat exaggerated reference to his mainstream counterpart's easily deceived personality (as well being based on the stereotypical team muscles), Knuckles is also portrayed as being somewhat slow-witted and goofy in this series.\n\n==Reception and impact==\nThe character has received positive attention. According to [[IGN]]'s Levi Buchanan, fans \"seemed legitimately happy\" with the addition of the character of Knuckles, who was popular enough to get marquee billing in ''[[Sonic & Knuckles]]'', but Buchanan felt that characters who came after him were going \"overboard\".<ref name=\"IGN wrong\">{{cite web |url=http://retro.ign.com/articles/955/955741p2.html |title=Where Did Sonic Go Wrong? |last=Buchanan|first=Levi|date=February 20, 2009 |accessdate=October 26, 2014}}</ref> IGN's Colin Moriarty singled out the introduction of both Knuckles and Tails as when the series became \"iffy\" and listed them and all other characters in the series, sans Sonic and Robotnik, as being 2nd most in need to \"die\" on his top 10 list.<ref name=\"IGN die\">{{cite web |url=http://pc.ign.com/articles/955/955079p1.html |author1=IGN PlayStation Team |author2=Moriarty, Colin |title=Wednesday 10: Video game Characters That Should Die |date=February 18, 2009 |accessdate=October 26, 2014}}</ref> In contrast, he was listed as the best ''Sonic'' character by ''[[Official Nintendo Magazine]]'' based on the impact he brought to the ''Sonic'' games in which he first appeared.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.officialnintendomagazine.co.uk/50022/features/the-best-and-worst-sonic-characters/?page=5|title=The best and worst Sonic characters|magazine=[[Official Nintendo Magazine]]|last=East|first=Thomas|accessdate=October 24, 2013|date=May 29, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029204405/http://www.officialnintendomagazine.co.uk/50022/features/the-best-and-worst-sonic-characters/?page=5|archive-date=October 29, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nAccording to official Sonic Team polls, Knuckles is the fourth most popular character in the series, following behind [[Miles \"Tails\" Prower|Tails]], [[Shadow the Hedgehog|Shadow]], and Sonic.<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120229160623/http://sonic.sega.jp/SonicChannel/event/016/002.html|archivedate=February 29, 2012|url=http://sonic.sega.jp/SonicChannel/event/016/002.html|script-title=ja:\u30bd\u30cb\u30c3\u30af\u30c1\u30e3\u30f3\u30cd\u30eb/\u30a4\u30d9\u30f3\u30c8/\u30bd\u30cb\u30c3\u30af \u30ad\u30e3\u30e9\u30af\u30bf\u30fc \u4eba\u6c17\u6295\u7968 \u7d50\u679c\u767a\u8868\uff01|language=Japanese|accessdate=October 26, 2014|date=June 23, 2006}}</ref> Elton Jones from ''[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]'' listed Knuckles as his eleventh most wanted character in the next ''[[Super Smash Bros. (Wii U/3DS)|Super Smash Bros.]]'' game.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.complex.com/video-games/2012/07/25-characters-we-want-to-see-in-super-smash-bros-brawl-4/knuckles-the-echidna |title=Knuckles the Echidna \u2014 25 Characters We Want To See In \"Super Smash Bros. Brawl 4\" |magazine=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]] |date=July 2, 2012|last=Jones|first=Elton |accessdate=August 2, 2012}}</ref> In another article, ''Complex'' regarded Knuckles as a better character than Sonic, and praised his gliding and climbing abilities, stating \"even if his levels were a little more challenging than Sonic's, the thrill of being able to explore certain parts of levels that the blue-colored hero could not be worth it\".<ref>{{cite magazine|author=Elijah Watson|url=http://www.complex.com/video-games/2014/02/knuckles-is-better-than-sonic-definitive-reasoning-20-year-anniversary-sonic-the-hedgehog-3 |title=Knuckles, Better Than Sonic, Definitive Reasoning 20 Year Anniversary, Sonic the Hedgehog |magazine=Complex |date=February 5, 2014 |accessdate=May 4, 2014}}</ref> Riley Little from GameRant included Knuckles on his list of the \"Top 10 Third-Party Characters that Could Appear in the New ''Super Smash Bros.''\", commenting \"This punch-drunk brawler knows how to serve up a buffet of knuckle sandwiches, and there\u2019s no question that he\u2019s one of the most fitting characters to occupy a spot on the roster\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gamerant.com/third-party-characters-super-smash-bros-4-riley-156631/5/|title=Top 10 Third-Party Characters that Could Appear in the New 'Super Smash Bros.'|last=Little|first=Riley|publisher=GameRant|date=July 10, 2012|accessdate=August 2, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120715232100/http://gamerant.com/third-party-characters-super-smash-bros-4-riley-156631/5/|archive-date=July 15, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n''[[Mega Zone]]''{{'}}s review of ''Knuckles' Chaotix'' praised the introduction of a new protagonist, whom it deemed \"rougher [and] tougher\" in comparison to the \"spineless\" Sonic.<ref name=\"megazone 2\">{{cite journal|journal=Mega Zone|title=Chaotix|author=Adam|issue=50|date=April 1995|page=22}}</ref> ''[[Mean Machines Sega]]'' called Knuckles' powers \"impressive\" and the character overall more useful and promising than Tails.<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Mean Machines Sega]]|title=Sonic & Knuckles|issue=24|page=16|publisher=EMAP}}</ref> ''[[Sega Magazine]]'' stated that Knuckles \"looks cooler\" than Sonic, comparing him to [[Spider-Man]], and suggested he be given his own game.<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Sega Magazine]]|title=Sonic cathedral of sound|publisher=EMAP|date=September 1994|issue=9|page=55}}</ref> ''Sega Magazine'' later called him \"groovy\" and \"ace\", concluding that they \"love him.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=Sega Magazine|title=Review|publisher=EMAP|date=October 1994|issue=10|page=80}}</ref> Knuckles' characterization in ''Sonic Boom'' earned praise by Polygon due to how \"progressive\" he is when mentioning [[feminism]] much to the shock of the characters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/tv/2017/8/2/16085836/sonic-the-hedgehog-knuckles-feminist-woke-cartoon|title=Sonic Boom gets progressive in one great moment|website=Polygon|accessdate=January 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Ugandan Knuckles meme===\n[[File: Ugandan Knuckles.png|thumb|A depiction of \"Ugandan Knuckles\" which had a brief surge of popularity in early 2018.]]\nIn January 2018, players began to flood the virtual reality video game ''[[VRChat]]'' with avatars depicting a deformed version of the character called \"Ugandan Knuckles\". The character stemmed from a 2017 review of ''[[Sonic Lost World]]'' by [[YouTube]] user Gregzilla as well as from fans of ''[[PlayerUnknown's Battlegrounds]]'' streamer [[Forsen]] who often make references to the [[Africa]]n country [[Uganda]] in the chat section of his streams. The character is often associated with quotes such as \"Do you know the way?\", which originate from the 2010 Ugandan action film ''[[Who Killed Captain Alex?]]'' as well as for \"spitting\" on other users whom they feel do not know \"de way\".<ref name=\"daily dot\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailydot.com/unclick/ugandan-knuckles-vrchat-meme/|title=How Ugandan Knuckles turned VRChat into a total trollfest|last=Hathaway|first=Jay|date=11 January 2018|website=The Daily Dot|access-date=13 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://heavy.com/games/2018/01/controversial-ugandan-knuckles-meme/|title=Controversial 'Ugandan Knuckles' Meme Has Infested VRChat|last=MacGregor|first=Collin|date=9 January 2018|website=Heavy.com|access-date=13 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe meme was criticized by some journalists as being racially insensitive;<ref name=\"daily dot\" /><ref name=Polygon2/> ''[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]'' described it as \"problematic\".<ref name=Polygon2>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/1/8/16863932/ugandan-knuckles-meme-vrchat|title='Ugandan Knuckles' is overtaking VRChat|last=Alexander|first=Julia|publisher=[[Vox Media, Inc.]]|work=Polygon|date=January 8, 2018|accessdate=January 9, 2018}}</ref> The creator of the avatar, [[DeviantArt]] user \"tidiestflyer\", has expressed regret over how it has been used, in particular saying that he hopes it is not used to annoy players of ''VRChat'', and that he enjoys the game and he does not want to see anyone's rights get taken away because of the avatar.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gamerevolution.com/news/362289-creator-vrchats-ugandan-knuckles-meme-regrets-decision|title=Creator of VRChat's 'Ugandan Knuckles' Meme Regrets His Decision|last=Tamburro|first=Paul|date=8 January 2018|website=GameRevolution|access-date=13 January 2018}}</ref> In response, in January 2018 the developers of ''VRChat'' published an open letter on ''[[Medium (website)|Medium]]'', stating that they were developing \"new systems to allow the community to better self moderate\" and asking users to use the built-in muting features.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/1/10/16875716/vrchat-safety-concerns-open-letter-players-behavior |title=VRChat team speaks up on player harassment in open letter |last=Alexander  |first=Julia |date=January 10, 2018 |website=Polygon |access-date=January 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikipedia books|Sonic the Hedgehog}}\n\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090217221441/http://www.sega.com/sonic/globalsonic/post_allabout.php?article=soniccharacters Sonic Central official character profiles]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061231041629/http://sonic.sega.jp/chara/knuckles/index.html Knuckles at Sonic Channel] {{in lang|ja}}\n\n{{Sonic the Hedgehog}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Knuckles The Echidna}}\n[[Category: Animal characters in video games]]\n[[Category: Animal superheroes]]\n[[Category: Anthropomorphic animal characters]]\n[[Category: Anthropomorphic characters in video games]]\n[[Category: Anthropomorphic martial artists]]\n[[Category:Fictional boxers]]\n[[Category:Fictional fist-load fighters]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters who became a protagonist in a spin-off]]\n[[Category:Fictional monotremes]]\n[[Category: Male characters in video games]]\n[[Category: Sega protagonists]]\n[[Category: Sonic the Hedgehog characters]]\n[[Category: Teenage characters in video games]]\n[[Category: Video game bosses]]\n[[Category: Video game characters in comics]]\n[[Category: Video game characters in television]]\n[[Category: Video game characters introduced in 1994]]\n[[Category: Video game characters who can move at superhuman speeds]]\n[[Category: Video game characters with superhuman strength]]\n[[Category:Internet memes]]\n", "name_user": "Jeff123456789Jeff", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Knuckles_the_Echidna"}
